<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-01 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School officials here learned a lesson the
hard way after a quarter of the students played hooky _ many with
their parents' approval.
   ``I don't think any member of the present school board will ever
vote to hold classes on Memorial Day again,'' said Karen Coleman, a
spokeswoman for the Seminole County School Board.
   Seminole was one of 24 of Florida's 67 counties to hold classes
Monday. Absentees totaled 5,000 of Seminole's enrollment of 20,033.
   Many parents called the school district's offices to make it
clear they regarded the day as a family holiday, Coleman said.
   ``Some were really angry about having school on Memorial Day,''
she said. ``They were all blunt in saying they were keeping their
kids home and were going to celebrate the holiday.''
   ``I know we're taking a beating on this,'' said School Board
Chairman Joe Williams. ``I guarantee it won't happen next year.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The warming trend in U.S.-Soviet
relations has prompted the Russians to order out for ice cream.
   Baskin-Robbins Ice Cream announced Tuesday it has signed a
licensing agreement to open its first store in a communist country,
with its 31 flavors becoming available in Moscow by July.
   However, a spokeswoman said it is too soon to say if Moscovites
will be ordering ice cream with such names as ``Catherine the
Grape,'' ``Lenin's Lemon,'' ``Tutti-Frutti Rasputti,'' or
``Ivanilla the Terrible.''
   Baskin-Robbins executives haven't yet thought of Russian names
for their 31 flavors, said spokeswoman Marilyn Novak.
   Still, ``the Soviets have expressed particular interest in
having Pralines 'n Cream and Jamoca Almond Fudge,'' Ms. Novak said.
``They have requested those two, along with other typical American
ice creams.''
   The Soviets, who already enjoy excellent domestic ice cream,
will operate the store, while the company will train Soviet
employees, provide the necessary equipment and decor, and supply
the ice cream itself, she said.
   A cone will sell for about a ruble, or roughly $1.60, Ms. Novak
said.
   ``We're going to be putting our first store at the Rossiya
Hotel,'' Ms. Novak said. The 8,000-room hotel is located near Red
Square.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's and Arizona's most colossal
cockroaches faced off feeler-to-feeler for the honor of
representing the two-state region in a national ``roach-off.''
   The largest Oriental cockroach entered in Tuesday's contest
measured 1.18 inch and was nurtured on a diet of paper, eggs and
breakfast cereal by two Elm Street Elementary School students in
Oxnard.
   Nick Preston and Paul Parrish said they will donate their $500
prize toward a science camp for their class of gifted 3rd- and
4th-graders, even though their teachers and classmates wouldn't let
them bring the bugs to school.
   ``They thought it was pretty disgusting,'' said Paul, 9, whose
father is an exterminator. ``I like bugs. I like to catch spiders.''
   But alas, the boys' roach won't represent California and Arizona
in the ``Great American Roach-Off,'' a national event sponsored by
a pest-control company that recognizes a different variety of the
household pest, the American cockroach, as the continent's
pre-eminent insect.
   The regional roach-off entrant will be a 1.71-inch American
cockroach submitted by a Mrs. Rauich of Palm Springs, said contest
organizer Michael Bohdan, who didn't know her first name.
   Both bugs were dead, in keeping with contest rules, and neither
measured up to Florida's entrant in the contest, 1.75 inch.
   The grand prize in the national contest, to be judged July 7 at
the Philadelphia Zoo, is $1,000.
   Paul and Nick produced their winner as part of a science project
to determine roaches' favorite food. The bugs turned up their
feelers at almost nothing, devouring paste, paper and electrical
wiring as well as scrambled eggs and cereal.
</TEXT>
