<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Runner-Raffle     06-01 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Runner-Raffle,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Runner Stumbles Over Raffle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A distance runner's plan to finance a
964-mile jog across Great Britain with a raffle has been tripped up
by the state Gambling Commission, which says the plan is illegal.
   ``We didn't know anything about it,'' Dick Goodman, a
68-year-old real-estate agent and long-distance runner, said
Tuesday. ``I've never don anything in my life that is wrong.''
   Goodman said he has located two corporate sponsors willing to
put up the $10,000 to $12,000 needed, and will return the
approximately $800 he had raised from the $10 raffle tickets, as
the commission has ordered.
   Only bona fide non-profit organizations are allowed to operate
raffles, and state law sets the maximum raffle ticket price at $5,
said Ron Layton, a commission spokesman.
   Goodman had enticed raffle purchasers with the chance to win
round trip tickets for two to London.
   He said the setback won't alter plans for his 20-day jaunt from
John O'Groats, Scotland, to Land's End, on the southern tip of
England, scheduled to begin June 21. The 5-foot-8 Goodman, who
weighs 140 pounds, plans to run 50 miles a day to complete the
route.
   ``No man 68 years old ever ran it,'' said Goodman, a World War
II veteran who took up running 26 years ago because he was getting
out of shape.
   Plans call for running nine to 10 hours a day, with breaks for
massages and meals. Goodman's coach is Bill Emmerton of Santa
Monica, Calif., a long-distance runner who ran the Great Britain
route in 1965.
   It is the longest run yet for Goodman, whose past efforts have
raised thousands of dollars for charities around the state. The
current run is not for charity, he said. The money is needed to pay
for air fare, a training van and pace car, food and hotels.
   In 1985, Goodman ran 130 miles from the Kingdome in Seattle to
the Peace Arch near Blaine, his boyhood home, on the Canadian
border. That raised $20,000 for a nursing home in Blaine.
   Next May, he plans to run 2,000 miles across the old Pony
Express route from St. Joseph, Mo., to San Francisco.
</TEXT>
