<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Children     06-01 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Children,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number Of Children In China Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's family planning policy, which calls for
no more than one child per couple, has in six years reduced by 30.1
million the number of children under the age of 14, the State
Statistics Bureau said today.
   The bureau said China now has 307.15 million children under 14,
compared to 337.25 million in 1982.
   It found the proportion of children in China's total population
of 1.07 billion to be 28.68 percent, down from 33.45 percent six
years ago, the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   The bureau attributed the decline to the family planning policy,
which has been largely successful in China's crowded cities but has
met resistance in many rural areas, where two or more children is
still the norm.
   The bureau said children account for just 18.36 percent of the
population in Shanghai, China's largest city, while making up 36
percent in the remote western areas of Tibet and Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
