<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-StudentSuicide     06-01 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Student Suicide,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Growing Number Of Students Commit Suicide Over Exams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressure from school work and exams
drove at least 50 secondary school students to commit suicide last
year and 10 students killed themselves in May alone, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Korea Herald reported a growing number of suicides among
high school and middle school students because of pressure from
school work and college entrance examinations.
   It warned that the number of student suicides would increase
unless education policy changes.
   The latest death was reported Monday, when a 17-year-old
student, upset over his poor academic performance, jumped from a
bridge to his death. He left a note that said, ``Sorry for my lack
of responsibility.''
   On May 18, the newspaper said, a 16-year-old high school girl
jumped to her death from an apartment one day after two high school
girls killed themselves over their poor school record.
   Most suicide notes left behind by students blamed pressure from
hard school work or poor exam results.
   ``I want to live in a country where there is no examination,''
said a suicide note from an 18-year-old student in the southern
city of Andong.
   To reduce the pressure, educators are proposing drastic reforms
of the system, which puts heavy emphasis on rote learning, the
paper said.
</TEXT>
