<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hutton-Libel     06-01 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hutton-Libel,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Attorney General In Court Over Check-Kiting Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Attorney General Griffin B. Bell
ignored evidence that top E.F. Hutton executives orchestrated a
widespread check-kiting scheme when he blamed mid-level managers in
a defamatory report, the lawyer for one of those managers says.
   Bell, a defendant in a defamation suit brought by one of six
branch managers he criticized in the 1985 report about the
check-kiting scheme, was trying to shift the blame away from top
management, the lawyer argued Tuesday in U.S. District Court.
   ``He cleared the company, he cleared the management and put the
blame out on regional managers and branch managers,'' Stephen G.
Milliken, a lawyer for former Hutton manager John M. Pearce, said
as the defamation trial got under way.
   Bell, a private attorney in Atlanta, was retained by Hutton to
conduct the internal investigation after the company pleaded guilty
May 2, 1985, to 2,000 counts of mail and wire fraud for
manipulating its checking accounts.
   The company admitted writing checks for amounts exceeding money
in the accounts, thereby giving itself interest-free loans. The
accounts were replenished before the overdrawn checks cleared,
enabling Hutton to make extra money by ``riding the float.''
   Hutton, which is now part of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., agreed
to pay a $2 million fine and reimburse banks that were victims of
the check-kiting scheme. Federal investigators said the company had
interest-free use of $250 million a day.
   Milliken said the practice was conceived in the late 1970s by
Hutton management and promoted as a way to get interest-free loans
from banks.
   ``The entire operation was known to New York, understood by New
York, created by New York,'' Milliken said. But ``Mr. Bell, by his
investigation cleared everybody in New York.''
   Bell, a partner in the Atlanta law firm of King & Spalding, was
retained shortly after the guilty plea was entered by the company.
He produced a report three months later that recommended that
Pearce and eight other branch and regional executives be
disciplined.
   The report exonerated all but one top management official, whom
Bell recommended be stripped of any duties involving Hutton's
banking activities.
   Bell's attorney, Earl J. Silbert, said the former attorney
general's probe ``was a carefuly, thorough, meticulous and fair and
independent investigation.''
   Silbert charged that Pearce violated company policies limiting
overdrafts in order to make extra money. Pearce overdrew by as much
as 400 percent to take his 10 percent share of interest profits
that were given branch managers as an incentive for efficient cash
management, Silbert said.
   Bell carefully refrained from accusing top managers because
there was insufficient evidence they did anything wrong, he said.
   But Pearce and the others named in the report were criticized
because ``their conduct was so egregious and abusive and so
aggravated and the evidence of proof so overwhelming that he would
have been derelict in his responsibility if he had not so named
them,'' said Silbert, a former U.S. attorney.
   Milliken said the overdrafting policies were so important to
Hutton's business strategy that Pearce was admonished when he did
not write checks for more than the amounts in the accounts.
   ``They taught him to overdraft, they told him what branches to
use,'' he said.
   Milliken argued that Bell's independence was undermined by his
relationship to Hutton, which paid King & Spalding $2.5 million to
conduct the investigation.
   ``Hutton was supplying the information, Hutton was supplying the
fee, Hutton was controlling the timing of when the report would be
released,'' Milliken said.
   Bell, a former federal appeals judge who was President Carter's
first attorney general, was paid at a rate of $1,711 an hour for
518 hours of work.
   Pearce also sued Hutton, but a federal appeals court ruled that
his claim against the brokerage firm must first be submitted to
arbitration by the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
