<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Summit-Indians Bjt   06-01 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Indians, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Outrages Indians by Saying America `Humored' Their
Ancestors</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDs: Suzan in 4th graf is correct
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only American Indian in Congress says
President Reagan _ in claiming the United States ``humored'' native
Americans by putting them on reservations _ appears to have learned
all he knows on the subject from his old Western movies.
   ``I only wish the president knew as much about American Indians
as he seems to know about the Russians,'' said Rep. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, a Northern Cheyenne who represents the western half of
Colorado. ``It's incredible he knows so little.''
   Campbell, a Democrat, joined a chorus of Indian groups and
others in denouncing Reagan's remarks to students at Moscow State
University on Tuesday.
   ``Maybe we made a mistake'' in trying to maintain Indian
cultures, Reagan said. ``Maybe we should not have humored them in
that, wanting to stay in that kind of primitive lifestyle. Maybe we
should have said, `No, come join us. Be citizens along with the
rest of us.'''
   Reagan misspoke. All American Indians were made full U.S.
citizens by an act of Congress in 1924.
   Suzan Harjo, executive director of the National Congress of
American Indians, said she found the remark about ``humoring'' the
Indians ``particularly insulting.''
   Gregory Frazier, president of the Denver-based National Urban
Indian Council, said, ``I'm a fan of the president, but the
president is a little bit removed from the reality of American
Indians.''
   Reagan volunteered his comments when he was asked by a student
if he would meet with three Indians visiting Moscow under the
auspices of the militant American Indian Movement. They went to the
summit city to call attention to the problems of American Indians.
   ``We have provided millions of acres of land for what are called
preservations _ or the reservations, I should say,'' Reagan said.
   ``They, from the beginning, announced that they wanted to
maintain their way of life, as they had always lived there in the
desert and the plains and so forth. And we set up these
reservations so they could, and have a Bureau of Indian Affairs to
help take care of them.''
   Though many Indians leave the reservations, many stay, the
president noted.
   The 1980 census found 1.37 million Indians, among whom 332,000
were living on 260 reservations.
   ``We've done everything we can to meet their demands as to what
they _ how they want to live,'' Reagan said.
   Campbell said, ``He appears not to know that Indians are
citizens.
   ``He must have been learning from these old celluloid Westerns
of the 1930s he used to act in,'' the congressman said.
   ``There's no question that American Indians don't want to lose
their traditions. But I don't know any Indians who want to be
primitive.''
   Harjo said, ``I thought his notion of having granted Indians
millions of acres of land was astonishing ... There was no grant
involved; his ancestors weren't dragging any land behind them when
they came to this country.
   ``He has headed the worst administration for Indians since the
days of outright warfare and extermination,'' she said, because of
``consistent efforts by this administration to undo legal,
long-standing rights and wipe out programs that meet our needs.''
   Indians leave reservations for better jobs and education ``and
politics,'' Frazier said. ``Life can be very hard on a reservation
if you're part of the `Out' party.''
   But, ``Many Indians don't have the choice to move off the
reservation'' because they have no job skills that mainstream
society will pay for, Frazier said.
   American Indians are among the poorest, worst-off of Americans.
A government study noted that the 1980 census found 12 percent of
all Americans living in poverty, but poverty among Indians affected
22 percent of those living off the reservation and 41 percent of
Indians living on reservations. Unemployment on reservations
frequently exceeds 60 percent and can reach 80 percent.
   Young Indian adults commit suicide at a rate six times their
counterparts in mainstream society.
   Campbell noted that government policy had tried to dissolve
tribes and force Indians to join mainstream culture as small
farmers in 1887-1934, then turned around and tried to maintain
tribes and tribal governments, but then flipped again to
``termination'' of tribes in the Eisenhower administration in the
1950s and flopped back to ``government-to-government'' policy in
subsequent administrations, a policy Reagan has affirmed.
   As for AIM and its three members in Moscow, Campbell said,
``People in AIM do not speak for all Indians. They speak for only a
small minority.''
</TEXT>
