<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AcidLeak     06-01 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Acid Leak,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fumes Overcome 38 After Acid Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NILES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noxious fumes from an acid leak at a factory
forced an evacuation of more than 130 residents and sent at least
38 people to a hospital for treatment, authorities said.
   Many of those treated at Pawating Hospital were players and
spectators at softball fields near the National-Standard wire and
cable plant where the leak occurred about 6:15 p.m. Tuesday,
nursing supervisor Mary Ann Weaver said.
   Hydrochloric acid and another acid were mixed in a storage tank,
causing the tank to rupture and the acids to form a puddle on the
plant floor, said Dennis Sexton, a dispatcher with the Berrien
County Sheriff's Department.
   The leak was contained with no fire or explosion, he said.
   Residents within three miles of the plant on Niles's northeast
side were ordered evacuated, but they returned when the area was
declared safe within three hours, Mayor Larry Clymer said.
   At least 130 people were sheltered temporarily at Ballard
Elementary School, about six miles from the plant on the west side
of the southwestern Michigan city of 15,000, school Superintendent
John Huffman said.
</TEXT>
