<HEAD>Names in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Chairman and best-selling author Lee
Iacocca is back with another autobiography, this time revealing
that he once considered taking over General Motors but decided ``it
might be easier to buy Greece.''
   ``Talking Straight'' arrives in bookstores today. The initial
printing is 750,000; booksellers can only hope it measures up to
``Iacocca: An Autobiography,'' which has sold 2.6 million hardcover
copies and 3.5 million paperbacks worldwide.
   In the new book, Iacocca writes that last spring, automobile
dealer Victor Potamkin and Allied-Signal chairman Ed Hennessy
approached him separately to suggest an unsolicited takeover of the
industry behemoth, General Motors Corp.
   At first, Iacocca wrote, he dismissed the idea. But talks
continued, and Iacocca even met secretly with investment banker
Felix Rohatyn, consulted a takeover lawyer and investigated
financing before dropping the proposal.
   ``I concluded that it might be easier to buy Greece,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arpeggio of acclaimed pianists, including Van
Cliburn and Vladimir Feltsman, on Thursday will help Steinway &
Sons celebrate its 500,000th piano in a gala Carnegie Hall concert.
   Others scheduled to perform at the event, which also marks
Steinway's 135th birthday, include Lazar Berman and Alexis
Weissenberg. The company announced that Vladimir Horowitz also has
accepted an invitation to the concert, but it was uncertain whether
he would perform.
   The company recently built its 500,000th piano, a 9-foot concert
grand in a specially designed case that includes the names of the
832 pianists and 90 ensembles on Steinway's artist roster.
   Proceeds from the auction of the landmark piano and ticket sales
will go to the newly established Steinway Foundation, a nonprofit
organization that will sponsor new piano works and help create
performance opportunities for pianists.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KEWANEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first couple may be first in
etiquette as well, as they became the only two people to appear for
the second straight year on a list of America's 10 best-mannered
people.
   Among those appearing with President Reagan and his wife, Nancy,
on the list announced Tuesday by manners maven Marjabelle Stewart
were actor Jimmy Stewart; Sam M. Walton, founder of Wal-Mart
Stores; and singer Dolly Parton.
   Reagan appeared on the list for the fourth consecutive year.
   ``There is such a warmth about that man,'' said Mrs. Stewart.
``People say, `Isn't he wonderful under all this stress.'''
   Mrs. Reagan demonstrates ``real first-lady manners ... and
people have fallen in love with her,'' she said.
   Celebrities are judged on public and private behavior, said Mrs.
Stewart, who queries about 70 journalists, television-crew members,
make-up artists, chauffeurs and maitre d's who have frequent
contact with famous people.
   Rounding out the top 10 were Ann Buchwald, wife of columnist Art
Buchwald; musician Lionel Richie; sports broadcaster Frank Gifford;
talk show host Johnny Carson; and Hugh Sidey, Washington
contributing editor for Time magazine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dame Joan Sutherland delivered a triumphant
performance at the Royal Opera and said with a big smile, ``I'm
elated,'' after a standing ovation for her title role in Gaetano
Donizetti's ``Anna Bolena.''
   The audience tossed bouquets onto the stage, cheered, shouted
bravos and even whistled their appreciation during Monday's show.
The 61-year-old soprano then swept out of the stage door and sat in
her car for an hour, signing programs thrust through a window by
fans.
   ``Her voice is not as great as it used to be, but there is no
lady of her age singing like that,'' said Arthur Jacobs, a British
critic and musicologist.
   All six performances of the opera through June 22 are sold out.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Billy Graham is calling for prayers for
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program, saying
``whether it works or not hangs in the balance.''
   Preaching to 1,700 church and lay leaders in London on Tuesday,
the 69-year-old minister spoke of his visit to Moscow next week for
celebrations to mark the 1,000th anniversary of the Russian
Orthodox Church.
   ``You can't turn around a great nation like the Soviet Union in
a year or two. It's going to take a generation. Whether it works or
not hangs in the balance, and so they need prayer,'' he said.
   Gorbachev, whose program of perestroika, or restructuring, calls
for major economic and governmental reforms, is meeting in Moscow
this week with President Reagan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roselle Como, wife of singer Perry Como, is
recovering from quadruple bypass coronary surgery that she
underwent at the Heart Center at Duke Hospital on May 26.
   She is expected to be discharged Friday, the hospital said.
   The Comos had been in Durham to attend the 15th annual Duke's
Children Classic, of which Como is the honorary chairman, when Mrs.
Como suffered some chest discomfort. Tests revealed she had
coronary disease and angina pectoris, doctors said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Brooklyn Dodgers pitcher Ralph Branca is
leading an effort to help destitute former baseball players, some
of whom have drug and alcohol problems and ``only get one strike
and they're out.''
   About 56,000 books of baseball cards, valued at $500,000 or
more, were contributed by Procter & Gamble Co. on Tuesday to the
Baseball Alumni Team, a fund headed by Branca. Among those helping
out at the ceremony were former stars Don Drysdale and Rusty Staub.
   Branca said the fund, which last year spent between $325,000 and
$350,000, already has helped 64 former major leaguers, minor
leaguers or umpires, many of whom had financial problems stemming
from illness.
   ``Everyone who's played the game has a great deal of pride,''
said Branca. ``A lot of people won't step forward to say they need
help. We hope this can help give them a decent life.''
</TEXT>
