<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SummitCity Bjt   06-01 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit City, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Wire: A Miracle _ Ronald Reagan Puts Danish Ham on Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunny skies, a warm breeze, temperatures around 80
and the lilacs in full bloom: Moscow could hardly be lovelier. And
Ronald Reagan has made it nicer than usual for Muscovites.
   Reagan's legendary good luck and a crash cleanup by Soviet work
crews combined to put the prettiest possible face on this otherwise
seedy capital for the superpower summit.
   Even the city's notorious ``pookh,'' the cotton-wool summer
scourge that falls from the city's silver poplar trees, fills the
air and covers the ground like snow, has cooperated. It is having
either a late season or a light one.
   Yuri Somov, an architect and would-be artist, was displaying his
favorite painting on a downtown street when three Americans
approached. One asked how much he'd take for his painting, a
stylized Russian Orthodox church scene. When he discovered their
nationality, however, he insisted he couldn't sell his favorite
work but wanted to give it to the American president.
   ``To Mr. Ronald Reagan, with profound respect,'' he wrote on the
back, and signed his name. The painting found its way to Reagan's
White House staff.
   It was typical of the outpouring of goodwill that has greeted
the swarm of Americans and other foreigners, mostly journalists,
who have descended on Moscow for the meetings between Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Reagan.
   A 25-year-old woman standing at the edge of Red Square who
identified herself as Olga said Moscow streets ``look prettier
because they cleaned everything up for this summit.''
   ``If only it would stay this way,'' she said.
   It won't, although the constant hosing down and sweeping of the
streets is not extraordinary here. Street sweepers are undeterred
even by Moscow's frequent rainy days, but poor grading and
practically nonexistent drainage ensure that the streets have
almost perpetual puddles in summer. Dirt becomes mud only to be
redistributed by the next storm or water truck.
   Some Americans, particularly those who visited Moscow when
relations were more strained and its people more suspicious of
foreigners, have been surprised by Muscovites approaching them on
the street just to practice their English or exchange pleasantries.
   On the Arbat, the pedestrian mall in the restored historic
district that Reagan visited shortly after arriving Sunday, one
artist displayed a mural depicting familiar Moscow monuments, and
in the middle was a cherubic babe holding American and Soviet flags.
   The artist, who called himself Vladimir Britikov-Cambridge, told
a reporter: ``Ronald is one of us. He's an artist.''
   But if the summit has brought out a friendly comraderie in a
society where people often pass on the street without acknowledging
each other, it also has meant some inconvenience.
   Authorities announced before Reagan arrived that people without
residence permits would not be allowed to come into the city this
week, effectively banning an estimated 3 million visitors from
outside the capital who crowd in on any given day to stay with
relatives, shop, sell home-produced goods or search for
hard-to-find commodities.
   Permanent residents who live near summit sites have been pleased
to discover rarely found goods on store shelves that have been
barren most of the winter.
   One shopper refused to believe that an ordinary shop was selling
Danish canned ham, a rarity in the best of times, even in the
hard-currency berioska stores set up for foreigners.
   Cars without Moscow plates and those that police inspectors fear
might break down and clutter the streets have been stopped at
roadblocks set up at the city limits.
   But if the stringent controls have cut down on traffic volume,
the extraordinary enthusiasm of the foot police assigned to seal
off much of the city center has snarled the remaining traffic in a
city which hardly has enough cars to stage a respectable rush hour.
   More than one driver has exercised his newfound freedom of
expression to give policemen a candid opinion of a system that
leads innocent motorists into a trap where all vehicles, trucks and
buses included, must stop and turn around in the street to escape
horrendous tieups.
   A Moscow taxi driver who spent 20 minutes to drive less than
three miles grumbled to his American passenger, ``Your president
comes, and then when I want to go this way, I have to go the
opposite way instead.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Putzel is the AP bureau chief in Moscow.
</TEXT>
