<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-SovietHeartland Bjt   06-01 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Soviet Heartland, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In the Peoria of the Soviet Heartland, the Summit Is a Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAROSLAVL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing a wide smile, the local
Communist Party chief put his arm around an American visitor and
steered him into his paneled office to watch the latest TV report
on the Moscow summit.
   ``May these sunny May days at the Kremlin mean that a new page
has been turned in the history between our countries,'' Igor A.
Tolstoukhov said at one point Tuesday.
   In Volgograd, Olga V. Sovelyova picked her way through a thick
crowd when she heard there was an American nearby, removed her
sunglasses and extended her hand.
   ``I want to congratulate you on the ratification of the
medium-range missile treaty by your Senate,'' said the plump
41-year-old Russian woman. ``Things are looking up for relations
between us.''
   For a reporter on a 1,900-mile swing through the Russian
heartland, the hopes inspired by the meeting between President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev are immediately
apparent because Soviets readily express them.
   ``I just wanted to say that we want to be friends with you,''
said a shy teen-aged girl in Stavropol who then left a bookstore on
Karl Marx Prospekt that among other things sells posters condemning
U.S. militarism.
   If there is a Peoria in the Soviet Union, the Moscow summit
appears to be playing well there.
   That's the case even if the hopes it inspires are tempered by
memories of past swings in superpower relations and the political
fact that Reagan will be out of office in January.
   For most Soviets, the Ronald Reagan who once joked about bombing
their country has been replaced by a wiser, more sober statesman
who has joined with their country's leader in seeking tighter
U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``He has changed,'' said Tolstoukhov, 49, party chief for a
region the size of Holland centered around the ancient city of
Yaroslavl, 150 miles north of Moscow. ``But after all, he was once
a Democrat who became a Republican.''
   In interviews, many people credited recent changes in the Soviet
Union itself for bringing Reagan to the capital of the socialist
nation he once called an ``evil empire.''
   ``As Mikhail Sergeyevich (Gorbachev) said, `It is better to once
see than to hear 100 times,''' Tolstoukhov said. ``We hope he will
sense the hospitality of our Russian people and their desire for
peace.''
   Gennady P. Starostin, mayor of Stavropol, said: ``We are all
people and we all live on the same tiny planet. All of us want to
live longer and better. The only place we should be competing is at
the stadium.''
   Among some Soviets, however, the hopes are twinned with
suspicions fueled in part by incomplete knowledge about how the
U.S. political system functions.
   A collective farmer in the village of Beshpagir, 25 miles from
Stavropol, thought the lengthy debate over medium-range nuclear
treaty meant the United States was backing out on its commitment.
   ``Your president signed it: why isn't that enough?'' said the
sunburned man standing outside his cottage. ``Don't you trust us?''
   But the man in his 40s who gave his name only as Vassily is an
exception. Most Soviets spoke wistfully of the high-water marks in
U.S.-Soviet relations _ the wartime alliance against Nazi Germany,
the Soyuz-Apollo flight, the detente of the 1970s.
   Mrs. Sovelyova was among them. A guide at the monument to the
World War II battle of Stalingrad, now called Volgograd, she
gestured to the stone pillars that commemorate the Red Army
soldiers who died in battle.
   ``We were once in a common cause,'' she said. ``Let us work
together to reinforce peace on our beautiful green planet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
