<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-CouncilSeats     06-01 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Council Seats,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LA Council Debates Which Way To Sit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council couldn't agree whether members
should face each other or the public, but unanimously decided to
study the matter.
   The councilors on Tuesday considered doing away with their
decades-old semicircular seating arrangement, which allows them to
face each other rather than the public during meetings.
   The current ``horseshoe ... certainly gives the appearance that
council members are not listening,'' said Councilwoman Joan Milke
Flores.
   Councilman Nate Holden said he thought the change would be a
misuse of taxpayers' money and ``nothing more than a
headline-grabber.''
   Councilman Joel Wachs wasn't sure a rearrangement was a good
idea.
   ``I think it's worked well this way, and I don't think I would
like to see it changed,'' Wachs said.
   The Council voted 11-0 to order a study of whether changing the
seating would violate regulations that govern the council chamber,
which is designated a historical landmark.
</TEXT>
