<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SoldierofFortune 1stLd-Writethru a0848 06-01 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soldier of Fortune, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0848,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Contract Murderer Sentenced to 40 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with two grafs to CORRECT sequence and length
of Savage's various prison terms. Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``Savage,
39...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of soliciting a murder
contract through Soldier of Fortune magazine has been sentenced to
a 40-year prison term.
   Richard Michael Savage received the maximum prison term for the
crime from U.S. District Judge James DeAnda on Monday.
   Savage is already serving a 40-year term in a Florida federal
prison for arranging the beating death of the former assistant city
manager of West Palm Beach, Fla. The latest sentence would follow
that term and a consecutive 25-year sentence in a federal prison in
Arkansas on a conviction for attempted murder-for-hire and
threatening a witness.
   Savage, 39, was convicted April 6 on charges he masterminded the
bungled bombing of Dana Free's home in October 1985. Savage of
Knoxville, Tenn., ran a ``gun for hire'' advertisement in Soldier
of Fortune magazine in June 1985.
   Alice V. Brado, a terminally ill Colorado widow, pleaded guilty
to paying Savage $20,000 to kill Free, her former business partner.
Ms. Brado, who later died in prison, said she wanted Free dead
because he bilked her out of her life savings of $300,000.
   Free was not at his Houston area home at the time of the
bombing. He also escaped two previous attempts to bomb his car in
Atlanta.
   Savage was tried in Brownsville after DeAnda ruled the defendant
could not get a fair trial in Houston because of publicity from an
unrelated civil suit against Soldier of Fortune. In that case, a
federal jury awarded $9.4 million to the family of a woman killed
after an ad ran in the magazine.
</TEXT>
