<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Briefs     06-01 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Briefs,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says he plans to become an
after-dinner and luncheon speaker afer he leaves office and that
he'll try to convince the American people to rescind the two-term
limits on presidents.
   The 22nd Amendment, which prescribes that limit, was ratified by
the states in 1951.
   ``It was an interference with the democratic rights of the
people,'' he told students at Moscow State University on Tuesday
during a question and answer session. ``The people should be
allowed to vote for who they wanted to vote for as many times as
they want to vote for them.''
   The reply, which drew applause, was in answer to a question of
whether Reagan would like a third term.
   The president explained that a tradition of two-term presidents
had grown up since George Washington refused a third tirm because
he didn't want to foster a monarchy. He said the amendment passed
because of ``the atmosphere of the time.''
   ``I think it was kind of a revenge against Franklin Delano
Roosevelt who was elected four times,'' Reagan told the students.
   He said when he leaves office he'll travel around the mashed
potato circuit ``and try to convince the people of our country that
they should wipe out that amendment to the Constitution.'' The
president said, ``I can't do this while I'm in office because it'll
look as if I'm selfishly doing it for myself.''
   Reagan said that on the speaking circuit he'll tell ``about a
few things that I didn't get done in government, but urging the
people to tell the Congress they wanted them done.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan's fondness for astrology became an
abstract point of ridicule during the president's meeting Tuesday
with intellectuals.
   Film director Elem Klimov made no direct reference to Mrs.
Reagan's reliance on stargazers during his remarks to Reagan, but
he noted that ``our'' astrologers had predicted this would be the
century of Russia.
   He suggested with a smile that perhaps U.S. and Soviet
astrologers ``should follow the new fashion for conferences'' and
get together to exchange predictions.
   The president had no visible response to Klimov's remarks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baskin-Robbins is coming to Moscow.
   Barney Brown, vice president of the Glendale, Calif.-based ice
cream manufacturer, said Tuesday the company has signed a franchise
agreement to sell its 31 flavors at the Hote Rossiya, across from
the Kremlin.
   The Soviets will operate the concession with Baskin-Robbins
providing the equipment and the ingredients, Brown said. The store
is scheduled to open July 1, about a month after hordes of
Americans who were here for the summit leave.
   Most Soviet citizens, who are frequently seen licking ice cream
brought from street vendors, probably will not be able to buy the
product at first because it will be sold only for hard currency.
But Brown said the company eventually hopes to work out an
arrangement to sell the ice cream for rubbles.
