<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ZeroTolerance     06-01 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seized Research Ship Allowed to Sail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The research ship Atlantis II, seized under the
federal zero-tolerance drug policy, was allowed to set sail for
Oregon but must keep authorities posted on its whereabouts.
   The ship, which took part in the exploration of the wreck of the
Titanic, left its moorage here Tuesday, said Mike Fleming,
spokesman for the U.S. Customs Service in Los Angeles.
   Atlantis II remains under ``constructive seizure,'' which means
that ship officials must report the craft's position to customs
officials at least once a week, said Capt. Gary Chiljean.
   Chiljean, who was not the captain when the seizure took place,
said Monday the release of the 210-foot vessel was based in part on
an agreement that ``this would never happen again.''
   The ship, worth an estimated $30 million, is now bound for
exploration off the Oregon coast. The stop in San Diego was a
planned one for overhaul of equipment, Chiljean said, and the ship
remains on schedule.
   Customs officials seized Atlantis II on May 18 after finding a
tiny bit of marijuana and some residue in a pipe owned by a crew
member.
   The ship was returning with a Scripps Institution of
Oceanography vessel from an exploration off the coast of South
America.
   The seizure was one of the most publicized of the zero-tolerance
program, a federal crackdown in which officials are confiscating
boats or vehicles for discovery of any amount of drugs.
   Protest of the policy, including a congressional attack on it
last week, led to a Coast Guard decision to use more discretion in
deciding whether to seize vessels. Ships outside the 12-mile
territorial limit will be taken only if intent to smuggle is
determined.
</TEXT>
