<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NJSenate Bjt   06-01 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NJ Senate, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lautenberg Vs. Dawkins: Resume Against Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans believe Peter Dawkins, a Heisman
Trophy winner, Rhodes scholar and war hero, is the star-quality
candidate who can unseat Democratic U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg.
   Lautenberg, a rags-to-riches business pioneer seeking a second
six-year term, warns that he won't give up his seat without a big
fight.
   With that battle well under way, Lautenberg, 64, and Dawkins,
50, say they are confident of victory. They are prepared to spend
$7 million or more apiece to get it.
   The two are crisscrossing the state in anticipation of Tuesday's
primary election.
   Dawkins faces no GOP challenger. Lautenberg faces nominal
opposition from two little-known Democrats: Elnardo J. Webster, a
40-year-old state Corrections Department recreation official who
contends the senator is out of touch with constituents, and Harold
J. Young, who is running as a ``conservative-radical.''
   Nationally, the Republicans have targeted Lautenberg as one of
the Senate's most vulnerable incumbents. President Reagan spoke at
a Dawkins fund-raiser in March that took in $300,000. New Jersey's
popular GOP governor, Thomas H. Kean, is chairing Dawkins' campaign.
   Lautenberg's bid is led by the equally popular Sen. Bill
Bradley, the state's Democratic senior senator. Lautenberg has
raised nearly $4 million and has tried to get the best campaign
help money can buy.
   In a way, Bradley is part of Lautenberg's problem. Since taking
office in 1982, Lautenberg has worked to emerge from the shadow of
his nationally known colleague, a former National Basketball
Association star and like Dawkins a Rhodes scholar.
   Part of Dawkins' strategy has been to subtly stress his
similarities to Bradley.
   The message has been clear: by electing Dawkins, New Jersey _
the brunt of garbage-dump and gangster jokes _ could be the only
state to boast two Rhodes scholars as senators.
   Dawkins has begun to sell himself as a natural senator. He was
captain of his West Point football team, decorated as a paratrooper
in Vietnam and named the youngest general in Army history. Along
the way, he studied at Oxford and earned a Ph.D. from Princeton.
   Dawkins left the Army in 1983 to join the Shearson-Lehman
brokerage house in New York. He resigned last year to become a
full-time candidate, and moved from New York City to the exclusive
New Jersey suburb of Rumson.
   Dawkins has a larger-than-than life presence, augmented by
piercing eyes, a Steve Canyon jaw and a broadcaster's voice.
   ``When he walks in a room, heads turn. People know he's there,''
said Campaign Manager Doug Goodyear.
   Lautenberg's camp says its candidate also has a remarkable
background, and two things Dawkins doesn't have: a proven
legislative record and a long-term connection with New Jersey.
   ``The Lautenberg story is very compelling,'' asserted Paul
Begala, spokesman for the senator's campaign.
   As he did in his 1982 upset of Republican Sen. Millicent
Fenwick, Lautenberg _ affable, white-haired and with a noticable
gap in his front teeth _ is stressing his roots as the son of poor
immigrants, raised in the textile center of Paterson.
   He attended Columbia University on the GI Bill, and helped to
found the worldwide Automatic Data Processing Corp. En route, he
amassed a personal fortune topping $25 million, and became an
international philanthropist.
   Lautenberg is running on his record, greatly enhanced when
Democrats took control of the Senate last year. Then an obscure
freshman, Lautenberg was elevated to chair subcommittees on
transportation and the environment, two meat-and-potatoes issues in
New Jersey politics.
   For Dawkins, the goal is to convince voters that his remarkable
resume qualifies him to be a better senator.
   According to Goodyear, Dawkins will assert that Lautenberg has
``a record of no achievement, no accomplishment ... lackluster
performance.''
   Begala countered, ``Frank Lautenberg's motto is `New Jersey
first.' The other guy's is, `Me first.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
