<HEAD>Eugene McCarthy To Help Build Alternative Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Eugene J. McCarthy will run a
third time for the presidency this year to help establish an
alternative voice in American politics, according to the party
backing his bid.
   The Consumer Party said Tuesday the former Minnesota congressman
and senator planned a 1 p.m. EDT announcement today outside
Independence Hall.
   ``We think there's a need for a permanent third force in
American politics, one that can speak for consumer interests,
rather than corporate interests,'' party spokesman Darcy Richardson
said.
   Neither the party nor McCarthy expect the 72-year-old elder
statesman of anti-establishment politics to win the Oval Office
this year, Richardson said.
   ``It would be nice to pull off a miracle, but we're building a
party that we hope can be an effective third party,'' he said.
   Sharon Varallo, a spokeswoman for McCarthy, said Tuesday she
could not confirm or deny that McCarthy would become a candidate
for the 21-year-old Philadelphia-based party. There was no answer
at McCarthy's home telephone number Tuesday night.
   McCarthy ran as a Democrat in 1968 and as an independent in 1976.
