<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoodyBeach     06-01 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moody Beach,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beach Ban Not Enforced As Summer Season Starts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLS, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The beach season's start brought an
onslaught of sunbathers to one of Maine's few sandy beaches but
none of the turmoil expected from a ruling that limited access to
the seashore in accordance with 17th century Puritan law.
   But an attorney for homeowners along the cherished beach in
southern Maine warned Tuesday that vacationers who relax on the
wrong patch of sand could wind up in court.
   At issue is mile-long Moody Beach, which a Superior Court judge
ruled in September is in effect private. The judge agreed with 30
homeowners that the beach between the high and low tide marks is
limited to fishing, bird hunting and boating based on a 1648
ordinance.
   The homeowners argued that sunbathers occupy the beach in front
of their homes _ property which they say is deeded to them _ and
make noise and leave behind trash.
   Justice William S. Brodrick's decision has been appealed to the
state Supreme Court, which is expected to rule in September. The
high court's decision also could affect some of the remaining 35
miles of sandy beaches along Maine's 3,500 miles of coastline.
   Meantime, Wells police Chief William Zackular says he will make
no trespassing arrests at the beach this summer. He said he was
instructed by the offices of the York County district attorney and
state attorney general to withhold enforcing the court decision
until the Supreme Court rules.
   But Sidney St. F. Thaxter, an attorney for the homeowners,
believes the town must enforce the decision pending the outcome of
the appeal.
   ``It's always been a private beach,'' Thaxter said. ``The judge
says it's a private beach and ... the public isn't allowed to be
there.''
   Thaxter said the chief's actions violate the order, and he
suggested that the town is ``encouraging the use of the property.''
He added that the police should at least come up with a solution
more equitable to the homeowners if the ruling is not going to be
enforced.
   If that fails, Thaxter said he would consider suing beachgoers
for civil trespass.
   ``The homeowners want to live in peace with the town and the
people that live there, but they're tired of being abused,'' he
said.
   Zackular countered that he has increased patrols at the beach
and is considering adding lifeguards to keep an eye on sunbathers.
   ``Near as I can tell the vast majority of the Moody Beach people
are happy with it,'' the chief said. ``They're happy with the
increased enforcement. ... There are just a few people who haven't
been pleased.''
   The police department received no complaints of trespassing
during the Memorial Day weekend, Zackular said.
   But some homeowners found weekend beachgoers annoying.
   ``I feel so sorry for my grandchildren because during the summer
there's absolutely no place to play,'' said Dorothy Jones, 68, a
plaintiff in the lawsuit. ``And it isn't even safe to run down
there and play _ with all those strangers _ in this day and age.''
</TEXT>
