<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Sharansky     06-01 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Sharansky,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharansky Calls Summit `A Show,' Glasnost `New Set of Instructions'
^With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet emgire Natan Sharansky called the
summit between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
``a show,'' and said the Kremlin policy of glasnost is simply a
``new set of instructions.''
   However, this week's meeting in Moscow ``brings more attention
to the case of dissidents and what's really happening in the Soviet
Union,'' Sharansky said at a news conference Tuesday to promote his
book, ``Fear No Evil,'' at the American Booksellers Association
convention.
   Sharansky spent nine years in Soviet labor camps after being
charged in March 1977 with espionage and treason. He staged a
hunger strike in 1982, and led other protests to allow Jews to
leave the Soviet Union.
   Sharansky, who now lives in Israel, was granted an exit visa in
1986, 13 years after he first applied to leave the Soviet Union.
   He said Tuesday that the summit was ``a show'' intended to
display only the good side of life in the Soviet Union.
   He said the success of Reagan's visit will depend on whether the
summit is used to put additional pressure on Moscow to improve its
human rights posture. Reagan met with dissidents Monday, and spoke
on human rights.
   Sharansky said that glasnost, the Russian word for Gorbachev's
policy of increased openness, is merely a means of improving that
country's image.
   ``The fundamentals of this system _ nothing has changed,'' he
said. ``Glasnost is simply (a) new set of instructions. ... It's
not that people are allowed to exercise more freedoms and do what
they want to do.''
   Sharansky said that economic sanctions linked to liberalizing
the system are the best way to win human rights for the Soviet
people.
</TEXT>
