<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica     06-01 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clergymen Urge Non-Violent Resistance To Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of South African clergymen
has pledged to organize anti-government protests and called for
increased non-violent resistance to apartheid in apparent violation
of government restrictions.
   The decision was made at an emergency conference _ the largest
and most broadly based of its type _ that ended Tuesday with a
church service at the Regina Mundi Cathedral in Soweto,
Johannesburg's largest black township.
   ``We are determined we are going to obey God whatever the
cost,'' Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu told a mostly-black crowd
of 1,200 during the service.
   Tutu then ripped symbolic gags from the mouths of black and
white youths on the podium, took up a wooden cross and carried it
back and forth down the cathedral's center aisle.
   The audience sang an African hymn, then held hands and swayed
together, singing the American civil rights song, ``We Shall
Overcome.'' Security force vehicles, including a tear-gas truck,
lined the street outside.
   More than 200 religious leaders representing more than 30 church
groups assembled Monday in Johannesburg to consider new tactics to
oppose the white minority government's racial policies.
   They ended the two-day convocation with a decision to mobilize
support for a three-day national protest planned next week by black
trade unions.
   They also said that, on June 12, they would start a campaign for
the release of political prisoners.
   The campaign is to end July 18th _ the 70th birthday of jailed
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African
Council of Churches, said the clergymen's plans might be regarded
by some as civil disobedience.
   ``We are not trying to undermine authority or advocate
anarchy,'' he said. ``We are distinguishing between two different
kinds of authority'' _ that between God and man.
   The government has recently banned numerous groups such as
unions and newspapers from conducting political activity.
   Anti-apartheid factions in the church, which was not initially
included in the ban, have begun to take up the struggle where these
groups left off.
   The Rev. Allan Boesak, mixed-race leader of the World Alliance
of Reformed Churches, said he had hoped the statement adopted by
the convocation would have been stronger, calling for more protests
and direct confrontation with the government.
   ``It will take time. But we are moving away from a theology of
protest to a life of protest and resistance,'' Boesak said.
   On the church podium were about 45 of the clergymen who attended
the convocation, including Tutu and Boesak.
   ``What this convocation wants to say is that the church of Jesus
Christ has no choice but to stand up for the poor and weak and
oppressed in this country,'' said Boesak. ``We say to the South
African government ... we must be more obedient to God than to
you.''
   During the convocation, workshops were held to discuss a range
of anti-apartheid tactics, including ``non-cooperation and
non-collaboration'' with the government.
   The agenda suggested that targets of civil disobedience could
include tax payments, military service and racially oriented laws
such as those mandating segregated residential areas.
   The convocation was sponsored by the South African Council of
Churches, which includes major Protestant denominations active in
the fight for black rights. Also participating were the Roman
Catholic Church and a number of independent African churches.
   Organizers said political conditions in the country have
worsened since leading clergymen decided in early February to
organize the convocation.
   They cited the effective bannings of 17 anti-apartheid
organizations, the closure of two opposition newspapers and pending
legislation to restrict labor unions and opposition political
groups.
</TEXT>
