<HEAD>Don Ameche Turns 80 But Shuns Publicity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Don Ameche, who won an Oscar for his
role as an oldster given another shot at being a youngster in the
movie ``Cocoon,'' has turned 80 but isn't looking for anyone to
draw attention to the fact.
   ``He has rejected any attention on his birthday,'' said
publicist Nick Stevens in turning down an interview request.
   Ameche finished ``Cocoon II'' in Florida on Saturday and
returned to his Los Angeles-area home. How he spent his birthday,
which was Tuesday, was not disclosed.
   The 1985 film ``Cocoon'' was Ameche's 50th screen appearance.
During his heydey as a 20th Century Fox leading man in the 1930s
and '40s, Ameche was a utility star who was equally popular in
musicals, comedies and dramas.
   Previously, his greatest fame stemmed from the title role in
``The Story of Alexander Graham Bell.''
