<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoEarthquake     06-01 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Earthquake,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reported Earthquake Was Really Strip Mine Blast, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weekend tremor labeled as an earthquake
was a strip-mine blast, a geologist says.
   Michael Hansen of the Ohio Department of Natural Resources
Division of Geological Survey said the blast at 12:18 p.m. Saturday
was labeled an earthquake by the National Earthquake Information
Center and state officials based on information on seismographs.
   ``It was picked up on a number of seismographs ... as far west
as St. Louis,'' Hansen said Tuesday.
   The blast registered 3.5 on the Richter scale of ground movement
and was centered near the southeastern Ohio community of Gaysport.
   ``Usually, we can tell the difference between a quarry blast and
an earthquake on the seismograph,'' Hansen said. But he said in
this case the seismographic waves appeared to be those of an
earthquake.
   Because Hansen remained suspicious, he checked with mining
companies Tuesday and learned one had set off a blast precisely at
the time the ground waves were recorded.
   ``We were not able to find very many people who felt the
earthquake,'' Hansen said. ``That was kind of strange, too.''
   Hansen said earthquakes have been reported in that portion of
the state most recently in 1953.
</TEXT>
