<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Crocodile' Beats `Rambo' in Sequel Battle, `Willow' Slipping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Crocodile Dundee II,'' starring Australia's
wonder down under, Paul Hogan, was moviegoers' favorite at the
nation's box offices, outmuscling ``Rambo III'' in a battle of
sequels last weekend.
   ``Willow,'' George Lucas' $55 million medieval fantasy, drooped
to third after making its debut as No. 1 the previous weekend.
   Ticket sales for ``Dundee'' and ``Rambo'' totaled $50 million in
the first six days of release, while ``Willow'' sales were down 10
percent last weekend to $7.5 million.
   Audiences during the four-day Memorial Day weekend paid more
than $29 million to see ``Crocodile Dundee II'' and $21 million to
``Rambo III,'' in which Sylvester Stallone takes on communists in
Afghanistan.
   ``Willow,'' which cost $55 million to make, brought in $8.3
million in its opening weekend and $18.6 million since its release.
   ``Some think `Willow' is fading and some think $18 million is
great,'' said John Krier of Exhibitor Relations Co., which surveys
box office performance. ``We'll have to see.''
   In fourth place was the Sean Penn-Robert Duvall street gang film
``Colors,'' with $2.43 million in receipts, followed by
``Beetlejuice'' with $2.41 million after nine weeks of release.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Crocodile Dundee II,'' Paramount, $29.21 million, 2,837
screens, $8,622 per screen, $29.21 million, one week, n-a.
   2. ``Rambo III,'' Tri-Star, $21.2 million, 2,562 screens, $6,536
per screen, $21.2 million, one week, $60 million.
   3. ``Willow,'' MGM-UA, $7.55 million, 1,030 screens, $7,336 per
screen, $18.61 million, two weeks, $55 million.
   4. ``Colors,'' Orion, $2.43 million, 1,322 screens, $1,839 per
screen, $37.90 million, seven weeks, $12 million.
   5. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $2.41 million, 1,432 screens,
$1,689 per screen, $61.91 million, nine weeks, $20 million.
   6. ``Friday the 13th Part VII - The New Blood,'' Paramount,
$1.89 million, 1,546 screens, $1,266 per screen, $15.86 million,
three weeks, n-a.
   7. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $1.12 million, 734 screens, $1,534
per screen, $75.49 million, 24 weeks, $17 million.
   8. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney, $1.01 million, 732
screens, $1,380 per screen, $119.55 million, 23 weeks, $21 million.
