<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-01 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Stocks Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground against the Japanese yen
in Tokyo today, while stock prices surged following an overnight
advance on Wall Street.
   After opening higher at 125.23 yen, the dollar climbed further,
closing at 125.35 yen, up a strong 0.55 yen from Tuesday's finish.
   ``The dollar held steady between 125.10 and 125.37 yen
throughout the day in mixed trading,'' said a foreign exchange
dealer with a major Tokyo commercial bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   There were active selling orders from export-related industries
but the dollar was supported by buying by financial organizations,
he said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 193.60 points Tuesday, added another
287.21 points, or 1.04 percent, closing the day's trading at
27,703.91.
   Share prices rose almost across the board, encouraged by
Tuesday's rise on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial
average gained 74.68 points and rose about the 2,000-point level,
traders said.
   Wall Street's rally prompted Tokyo investors to erase their
worries about the possibility of a hike in the U.S. discount rate,
an analyst said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at a heavy 2.5 billion
shares, up from 1.7 billion shares on Tuesday. It was the heaviest
volume this year, and near the market's record of 2.83 billion
shares set in March last year.
   Prominent among winners were steels, constructions and
chemicals. Drugs, electricals and automobiles also gained ground.
</TEXT>
