<DOCNO> AP880601-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ethiopia-Mengistu 1stLd-Writethru a0479 06-01 0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Mengistu, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0479,0904</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Leader Denies State Is Using Food As A Weapon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Mengistu promising to allow more U.N.
personnel into the north to ensure flow of aid, INSERT two grafs
after 12th graf, `Mengistu ... against us.'' Picks up 13th graf
pvs, ` Rebels of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam
denies his government is using food as a weapon in northern
provinces where secessionist insurgencies and crop failures
threaten the lives of 3.2 million people.
   For the first time, the Ethiopian leader also accused Arab
countries of backing the rebel movement. He claimed the Moslem
nations want to consolidate their control of the Red Sea.
   During Tuesday's six-hour news conference, Mengistu's first with
foreign reporters in two years, he also called for better relations
with Washington.
   The moustachioed Marxist leader spoke with unprecedented candor
on numerous other issues, gesticulating with passion, occasionally
smiling and laughing.
   Mengistu denied his government is using food as a weapon in the
north, where the war and a government counteroffensive have
jeopardized a massive Western-financed relief effort for millions
of people facing starvation in Eritrea and Tigre provinces.
   ``How is it possible, how is it imaginable that a government
which came to power by the will of the people ... can be accused of
using food as a weapon,'' Mengistu said. ``We revolutionaries do
not live for ourselves, we live for others.''
   In early April, the government ordered all foreign relief
workers out of Eritrea and Tigre for security reasons.
   The International Red Cross at first said it was defying the
order to recall its 25 or so workers, citing a ``humanitarian
responsibility for the fate of some 5 million people'' in the two
drought-stricken provinces.
   When the government insisted that the Red Cross workers leave
the areas, the agency locked up its supplies and trucks and left.
   On May 22, Ethiopia gave the Red Cross 15 days to hand over the
food.
   Red Cross officials denied earlier requests because they said
they must be present to supervise the food's distribution. In the
past, there have been allegations that food destined for starving
farmers has fed Ethiopian troops.
   Mengistu said the rebels are using the food issue ``to elicit
international sympathy and support for them to promote their
propaganda activities against us.''
   On Sunday, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said
Mengistu had promised when the two met two days earlier to allow
the United Nations to expand its role in the north to ensure the
continued flow of aid.
   The chief U.N. representative in Ethiopia, Michael Priestley,
said Mengistu had promised ``in principle'' to allow more U.N.
personnel into the north and to permit them to move outside
government-held towns.
   Rebels of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front have been
fighting for 27 years in Africa's oldest civil war and have won
major victories this year with the capture of several towns.
   Mengistu, who is in his mid-40s, made no reference to a younger
insurgency by rebels of the Tigrean People's Liberation Front, who
have been fighting for 14 years.
   During the conference, Mengistu said unspecified Arab nations
were backing the Eritrean group.
   Rebels ``have embarked on a project of convincing the Arab world
of an alleged oppression of the Moslems in Ethiopia in order to
invoke the sympathy of the Arabs,'' he said.
   He said Arabs were helping the rebels in order to ``keep
Ethiopia from the riches of the Red Sea.''
   Ethiopia's ports of Assab and Massawa, both in Eritrea, are the
only Red Sea ports not controlled by Arab states. Ethiopia would be
landlocked without them.
   In the past, Mengistu has always said Western nations supported
the rebel movement.
   On Tuesday, Mengistu said the rebels also had won support from
leftist countries, which diplomats identified as Cuba and the
Soviet Union. About 2,500 Cuban troops stationed in Ethiopia have
refused to fight in the north.
   Mengistu defended his country's Marxist revolution of September
1974, calling it ``human and democratic'' and claiming it had
improved the lives of the country's 42 million people.
   He warned that relations with the United States would be hurt if
Congress decides to stop annual imports of 20,000 tons of Ethiopian
coffee, a move it is debating.
   Still, Mengistu said he hopes for better ties with America: ``We
have always pushed for better relations with the United States and
I hope the United States will reciprocate ... Once upon a time we
were good friends.''
   Western diplomats were puzzled by Mengistu's conciliatory
attitude.
   They pointed out that Ethiopia at the last minute caused Chester
Crocker, U.S. assistant secretary of state for African affairs, to
cancel a visit in January when Ethiopia announced he would not be
meeting Mengistu.
   In February, Crocker said he believed Ethiopia was not serious
about improving relations with the United States.
   Once-warm U.S. relations with this East African country
deteriorated after the 1974 revolution in which Mengistu and a
clique of fellow army officers overthrew Emperor Haile Selassie.
   The United States continued to arm the new military government
until Somalia invaded Ethiopia in 1977.
   In a dramatic superpower flip-flop, the Soviets started backing
Ethiopia and the United States switched to Somalia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
