<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Anti-US     06-01 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Anti-US,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kim Dae-jung Warns U.S. To Change Policies In Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung today
criticized American interference in Korean politics and said only
drastic changes in U.S. policy can stop a wave of anti-American
sentiment in South Korea.
   He said South Koreans resent U.S. support for this country's
past authoritarian regimes and Washington's demand that Korean
markets be opened to U.S. imports. Kim said the United States
should not try to influence or control events in South Korea.
   ``First of all, the United States should act up to our
expectation for democratization if it wants to restore sincere ties
here,'' he told the Seoul Foreign Correspondents Club.
   The opposition leader criticized U.S. requests for South Korea
to increase its contribution to the costs of keeping about 42,000
U.S. troops in the country under a mutual defense pact.
   The United States has also been pressing for greater access to
South Korean markets to help reduce Seoul's $10 billion trade
surplus with Washington. Korean farmers strongly oppose any moves
to open domestic markets for fear of hurting their business.
   Radical students have staged a series of protests over the past
two weeks to demand the overthrow of President Roh Tae-woo and the
removal of American troops. The protests have turned violent.
Radicals have attacked U.S. diplomatic buildings and fought police.
   Kim said the recent protests reflected public dismay over U.S.
policies. ``There would be no more anti-U.S sentiment as long as it
remains the patron of democracy and meets the wishes of the Korean
people,'' he said.
   Government officials and other political leaders say anti-U.S.
sentiment is confined to a tiny radical minority and most South
Koreans are pro-American.
   Kim predicted that the Olympic Games in Seoul that begin in
September will lead to ties with the Soviet Union and China and
help South Korea end its heavy dependence on the United States. But
he ruled out drastic changes in South Korea's relations with the
United States in trade and other areas.
   South Korea has no formal ties with communist nations because of
its rivalry with communist North Korea. The Soviet and Chinese
decisions to attend the Olympics are expected to lead to ties.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics because the
International Olympic Committee has rejected its demand to co-host
the Games.
   Kim expressed disatisfaction with ``foot-dragging'' reforms
proposed by the government and charged it with being ``insincere in
liquidating the evil legacy of the previous government.''
   Roh defeated Kim and other opposition candidates in the Dec. 16
presidential elections.
   Kim said today that the United States helped Roh win by inviting
him to Washington before the elections, giving the impression he
was endorsed by the United States.
   He said South Korea's democratic development would be ensured by
the political neutrality of the armed forces, which he said have
been used to ``maintain the dictatorial regimes in power.''
   ``I firmly believe the great bulk of the military opposed
intervention in politics ... even though it still maintains
considerable influence.''
</TEXT>
