<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     06-01 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb In Beirut On Anniversary Of Karami Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded in west Beirut today,
where streets were nearly empty because Moslems went on strike to
mark the first anniversary of the assassination of Prime Minister
Rashid Karami.
   Police reported no injuries.
   A police spokesman said a white Mercedes-Benz packed with 44
pounds of explosives went off at 8:20 a.m. in the Bir Hassan
district.
   ``The explosion shattered windows, but no casualties were
reported, apparently because the streets were empty because of the
strike,'' the spokesman said. He cannot be named under standing
regulations.
   Banks, schools, shops, government offices, gasoline stations and
other businesses closed in west Beirut and other Moslem areas.
   Karami, a Sunni Moslem who was close to Syria, was killed last
June 1 when a bomb exploded aboard a military helicopter that was
flying him from north Lebanon to Beirut.
   Syrian-backed Moslem leaders have blamed the assassination on
Israel and the right-wing Lebanese Forces, the Christians' main
militia.
   Both have denied involvement. An official investigation into
Karami's assassination has made no progress.
   Today's car bombing was the third in Lebanon this year. By
police count, 89 people were killed and 189 wounded in the earlier
bombings.
   Sixty-nine people were killed and 111 wounded April 23 in the
northern port city of Tripoli, Karami's predominantly Sunni Moslem
hometown, when a pickup truck packed with explosives went off in a
crowded vegetable market.
   A car rigged with 220 pounds of TNT exploded in Christian east
Beirut Monday, killing 20 people and wounding 78.
   The Lebanese Forces blamed Syria for Monday's bombing. The blast
came four days after 2,400 Syrian troops moved into Beirut's
southern slums to end three weeks of bloody fighting between rival
Shiite Moslem militias in which nearly 300 people were killed and
1,000 wounded.
   The Christians are at odds with Syria, the main power broker in
this country that has been embroiled in civil strife since 1975.
   Christian President Amin Gemayel torpedoed a Syrian-brokered
peace treaty in December 1985, claiming it stripped Christians of
their traditional power.
   The Syrians control west Beirut, most of the city's southern
slums and Lebanon's eastern and northern provinces. The Christians
refuse to let the Syrians into their enclave north of Beirut.
   Police said Syrian officers supervised an exchange of prisoners
between the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the
pro-Syrian Amal militia in south Beirut during the night.
   Police reported that Hezbollah released 120 Amal men, while Amal
freed 31 men it had captured.
</TEXT>
