<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolViolence     06-01 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Violence,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Who Assault Teachers Will Be Expelled, City Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students who assault teachers will be expelled
and some classrooms will be get panic-button-like alarms under
sweeping security measures announced in response to a series of
attacks against teachers.
   The security plan also will include use of metal detectors,
electromagnetic locks, and more police in certain schools, Mayor
Edward I. Koch said Tuesday after meeting with schools Chancellor
Richard R. Green and other officials.
   In addition, Koch said, the officials agreed to ask the state
Legislature to upgrade the crime of assaulting a teacher or other
public official from a misdemeanor to a felony punishable by more
than a year in prison.
   Six teachers have been attacked during the past 1{ weeks.
   On Tuesday, a 27-year-old teacher was shot in the leg as she
left a school in the Bronx after dismissing her class, police said.
The bullet grazed her right thigh, and she was treated at a
hospital and released. The shot was fired by one of two men who
were arguing nearby. The shooter was not believed to be a student,
police said.
   Also Tuesday, a 31-year-old teacher was punched in the face by a
15-year-old student in a special education class at a Manhattan
high school, police said. The student was arrested and charged with
third-degree assault and then released, said Officer Peter
O'Donnell, a police spokesman.
   ``The notion you have a right to free education is assumed,''
Green said. ``Students who violate that right by assaulting
teachers or any other school personnel will forfeit that right for
the rest of the school year.''
   He said students who engage in anything ``beyond a normal fight
will find themselves without a public education in New York City.''
   Until now, abusive students were suspended or transferred to
other schools. The city was researching whether it needs action by
the Legislature to permit expulsions, the mayor said.
   The recent outbreak of school violence included a baseball-bat
attack on one teacher and another who was burned when she picked up
a huge firecracker tossed into her classroom.
   Frank Sabrino, a Board of Education spokesman, said that from
last July 1 to April 30, there were 969 reported assaults in the
city's schools, 198 on teachers.
   The police patrols will be instituted at the 200 schools with
the highest number of serious incidents, officials said.
   Koch said metal detectors will be put in some schools on a test
basis and identification cards will be issued for everyone in the
school system. In addition, electromagnetic locks will be installed
so that a signal will sound when outside school doors are left
open, and teachers will be able to push a button in the classroom
that will let the security office listen in.
</TEXT>
