<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Storm     06-01 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Storm,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Killed In Hurricane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hurricane swept across parts of
Bangladesh for two days this week, killing at least six people,
injuring hundreds more and destroying thousands of homes, officials
and news reports said today.
   A government official at Gaibandha, 124 miles north of Dhaka,
said three people were killed and 170 injured when the storm hit
the area on Monday and Tuesday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at least
1,500 houses, mostly made of mud and straw, were blown away. Crops
over a wide area were damaged.
   Newspapers said at least three other people were killed in other
parts of the country. Hundreds of others were reported injured, the
Bangladesh Times newspaper said.
   The storm followed floods in northern areas of the country,
caused by the Brahmaputra river bursting its banks.
   The government says at least 13 people have been killed in the
floods but local newspapers put the figure at more than 50.
   Floods and heavy rain are common in Bangladesh at this time of
year, when the annual monsoon begins.
</TEXT>
