<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Morocco-Algeria     06-01 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Morocco-Algeria,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Countries To Open Frontiers, Do Away With Visas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morocco and Algeria, which re-established
diplomatic ties last month, have done away with visa requirements
and plan to establish air, sea, rail and telecommunications links,
according to a joint announcement.
   Beginning Sunday, Moroccans and Algerians will be able to cross
into each others' countries with a valid passport. Four frontier
posts _ two in each country _ are being set up for that purpose,
the statement said.
   The announcement came late Tuesday at the close of a one-day
visit here by Algerian Interior Minister Hedi Khediri, who met with
his Moroccan counterpart Driss Basri.
   It said a mixed committee would study how best to facilitate the
passage of goods and people and re-establish air, sea, rail and
telecommunication links. The report is to be submitted by July 5.
   The two North African countries, at odds for 12 years over the
Western Sahara territory, re-established diplomatic relations on
May 17.
   They broke diplomatic ties in 1976 after Algeria recognized the
Saharan Democratic Arab Republic set up by Polisario Front
guerrillas seeking independence for the Western Sahara.
   The Western Sahara was annexed by Morocco in 1975. Algeria
harbors and arms the guerrillas.
   The establishment of relations between Algeria and Morocco and
the bid to remove barriers comes amid preparations for the Arab
summit meeting in Algiers starting June 7.
   A ``mini-summit'' of the five North African leaders is to be
held on the sidelines of the Arab summit, according to Algerian
officials. It will be the first such gathering of Algeria, Morocco,
Tunisia, Mauritania and Libya since they became independent of
European colonial rule.
   They all seek a united Maghreb, or North Africa.
</TEXT>
