<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark-Politics     06-01 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark-Politics,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schlueter Gets Chance To Form New Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Prime Minister Poul Schlueter
prepared to form a minority government after talks on a majority
coalition broke down, Denmark's public radio said.
   Schlueter was appointed as chief negotiator 10 days ago with the
task of putting together a government program that could win
approval from a majority in the Folketing, the 179-seat parliament.
   But the Social Democrats, Denmark's biggest party, and
Schlueter's Conservatives failed to close the gap between them on
economic and defense policy.
   Schlueter, who headed a center-right government until the
inconclusive election of May 10, now has support from a majority of
the eight parties to try to form a new minority coalition.
   After 20 days of political jockeying all attempts to build a
majority government appeared doomed.
   The election was called following a parliamentary row over a
toughening of Denmark's peacetime ban on nuclear arms which
provoked strong objections from its NATO allies.
   Analyists predicted Tuesday that the most likely outcome would
be a coalition of Conservatives, Liberals and Social Liberals
commanding a total of 67 seats.
   But the 10-seat Social-Liberals, who hold the balance of power
in the new parliament as they did in the previous one, had not
decided whether to join a new Schlueter administration.
   The Social Democrats and the allied far-left Socialist People's
Party together have 79 seats. Efforts to form a majority coalition
between them and the Social-Liberals failed earlier.
</TEXT>
