<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Summit-AllegedNazi 1stLd-Writethru a0435 06-01 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Alleged Nazi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Accuses Soviets of Smear Campaign Over Nazi Allegations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new to update with U.S. Embassy official comment;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, A student xxx.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Embassy official accused the Soviets today
of engaging in a ``smear campaign'' by charging that a dissident
who met with President Reagan was a Nazi war criminal.
   The allegations against Nikolai Rozhko, described by a U.S.
official as an American-born man living in the western Soviet
Union, surfaced in Soviet state-run media Tuesday.
   The embassy official, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified, said the Soviets disliked Rozhko because he is
campaigning to emigrate, and ``is a focal point for others who want
to leave.''
   The Soviet charges are part of a ``smear campaign to pressure
him to cease his activities,'' said the official.
   A student questioning Reagan at the president's session at
Moscow State University was swift to grill the U.S. leader on why
he invited the German ``Polizei,'' or Gestapo, to his meeting.
   The president replied that he knew nothing about such charges.
Nor did White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater when asked about
Rozhko later at a news conference.
   But Soviet spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov reiterated charges by
the state news agency TASS that Rozhko was a war criminal who began
collaborating with the Nazi police in 1942.
   Rozhko ``participated in the killing of Soviet partisans and the
arrests and tortures of civilians (maybe Jews too?),'' TASS said.
   It reported that Rozhko was sentenced to death by firing squad
by a military tribunal in 1944, but that the sentence was later
commuted to 20 years' imprisonment and Rozhko was released on
parole in 1955 by a government decree.
   It gave no further background on the charges.
   A U.S. source who asked not to be identified said Rozhko lives
in Grozdno, in the western province of Byelorussia, a region of the
Soviet Union that suffered greatly after the Nazis invaded in 1941.
   Millions were killed in the occupied Soviet Union and many
thousands of others jailed or executed on charges of collaborating
with the Nazis, a charge that is viewed extremely negatively by a
Soviet public constantly reminded of the nation's suffering in
World War II.
   Gerasimov said Soviet journalists who attended Reagan's
reception for the dissidents _ which was criticized by Soviet
officials _ turned up the background on Rozhko by looking at Soviet
records.
   They ``were rather curious and looked into the dossier of the
invited,'' Gerasimov explained.
   ``They found out that one of them in fact was a policeman
sharing in the occupation of our country by Germany ... so he was a
former Nazi agent and a war criminal,'' Gerasimov said.
   The U.S. official, who asked not to be identified, said Rozhko
was born in the United States and came to the Soviet Union as a
child with his parents. He has been trying to emigrate for the past
20 years, but the Soviets have denied him permission to leave.
   The source suggested that Soviet authorities have charged before
that Rozhko had a Nazi background, but never presented firm proof
nor implied that his history blocked his emigration.
   ``The Soviet government never once gave us one shred of evidence
of his Nazi activities,'' the official said. ``This was not an
issue (on Rozhko's emigration) until the Soviets brought it up this
week.''
   The official said he was speaking without direct access to
Rozhko's file and could not give precise details on the man's
background, but believed that he has a brother living in California.
   The official said he had the impression that Rozhko had served
time in a Soviet jail, but he did not know on what charges.
   Reagan's meeting with the refuseniks, unlike all other events in
his program, was reported with negative comment by the Soviet media.
   The Communist party daily Pravda and government newspaper
Izvestia on Tuesday criticized Reagan's meeting. Referring to a
speech Reagan delivered to the dissidents on Monday, Pravda noted
he had said ``it's time'' for more Kremlin reform.
   ``Indeed, it's time. Time to stop speculating on the problems of
human rights using this serious question as an easy reason for
self-advertisement and politicizing,'' Pravda said.
   Izvestia criticized Alexander Ogorodnikov, a religious activist
at the meeting, Lev Timofeyev, a campaigner for press freedom,
Rozhko and Abe Stolar, a 73-year-old American who has campaigned
since 1975 for his family to emigrate from the Soviet Union.
   Like Rozhko, Stolar was brought to the Soviet Union as a child
by his parents.
</TEXT>
