<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Plane, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Says His Soviet Flyover Not A Political Statement, But A
Mistake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CLARIFY that Summer passed into Soviet
territory on Saturday and Sunday. PICKS up 9th graf pvs, ```The
weather ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German pilot says bad weather
caused him to fly his small plane over Soviet territory over the
weekend and that his jaunt into Russian airspace was a mistake, not
a political statement.
   Andreas Sommer said he blundered across the border in bad
weather Saturday in a single-engine Cessna 150 and did it again on
Sunday.
   Sommer said he didn't know that Saturday marked the first
anniversary of a flight by Mathias Rust, who stunned the world by
flying a light plane through Soviet air defenses to Red Square.
   Rust now is serving a four-year prison term in Moscow.
   Sommer's flight caused a diplomatic flurry, particularly because
of suspicions the incursion had something to do with the Moscow
summit between President Reagan and Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He said he hopes the summit ``brings peace and detente,'' but
his vacation flight had nothing to do with it.
   In Oslo, Foreign Ministry spokesman Lasse Seim said the plane
crossed the Soviet border while on a 100-mile flight from Ivalo,
Finland, to Kirkenes on Norway's Barents Sea coast.
   He said it went deeper into Soviet territory when it returned to
Ivalo on Sunday, staying in Soviet airspace for as long as 30
minutes.
   Sommer, a part-time Hamburg bus driver with 23 years as an
amateur pilot, said he passed into Soviet territory both days while
flying in a cloud cover at 1,000 feet.
   He said he said he first learned that he had strayed into Soviet
territory on Sunday when Norwegian air controllers warned him:
``You are on Soviet territory. Return.''
   ``The weather at the time was so bad I was prepared to land any
place, but there were only lakes and forests and I decided to
return to Finland immediately,'' Sommer told a reporter for the
Aftonbladet newspaper.
   Sommer said he saw no Soviet aircraft scrambling to intercept
him and had no contact with Soviet air controllers.
   Matti Autio, of the Finnish Border Patrol, told The Associated
Press that Sommer was questioned after landing on Sunday for
deviating from his flight path, but was not detained.
   The Norwegian national news agency NTB quoted Soviet Embassy
official Valery Nesteruchkin in Oslo as calling the overflight a
``bad joke.''
   Seim said Norway contacted Soviet authorities on Sunday, and
``we have the impression that they followed the plane. They knew
about it.''
   The Aftenposten newspaper speculated that the Soviets may have
refrained from shooting at the plane because of the Moscow summit.
   Seim said the Soviet Border Commission asked for a meeting with
the Norwegians on Monday, when they handed over a formal protest.
   Rust was 19 at the time he made the flight. On Sept. 4, 1987, he
was found guilty by a Moscow court of illegal entry into the Soviet
Union, violating international flight regulations and malicious
hooliganism. He was sentenced to four years in a labor camp, but
now is being held in a Moscow prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
