<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-01 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flooding Hits Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy thunderstorms roared across parts of Texas and Oklahoma
early today, dumping heavy rainfall across a vast area and
triggering flash flooding in at least 10 Texas counties.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued into the morning hours from
western Iowa and Nebraska across Kansas, eastern Colorado, Oklahoma
and north-central through south-central Texas. Rain was scattered
from the northern half of the Pacific Coast into eastern Washington
and the Idaho Panhandle.
   Local flood warnings were posted in northern Texas, where heavy
rain caused flooding and closed low-lying streets elsewhere.
Overflowing creeks and streams left Highway 377 near Comanche under
about 14 feet of water.
   Flash flooding was widespread in 10 counties, including the
Dallas-Fort Worth area, and forecasters warned that other parts of
Texas could be in store for flooding later today as the storm
system that triggered the drenching rain moved northeastward.
   As almost 7 inches of rain fell in sections of Texas from late
Tuesday through early today, flash flood watches were posted in the
Hill Country and north-central Texas, as well as in western and
central Oklahoma.
   One person died Tuesday in a weather-related three-vehicle
accident on a rain-slickened street in Amarillo. In Caldwell,
thunderstorms produced hail and winds gusting to more than 50 mph,
downing trees and power lines.
   In Cape Hatteras, N.C., a high of 91 degrees Tuesday set a
record for May 31 and marked the city's first 90-degree day for the
month of May in 115 years of record-keeping. The previous record
high for the month was 88 degrees on May 30, 1881, and May 25, 1962.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across the
upper half and ports of the lower half of the Mississippi Valley,
the eastern half of Texas, Oklahoma, the central Plains and eastern
South Dakota; and showers over New Jersey, Pennsylvania, southern
New York state and southern Florida, as well as the northern
Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 50s in northern
Maine; the 60s and 70s over the remainder of New England and
northern New York state; the 60s from the northern Rockies across
the northern and central Pacific coast; the 90s in the desert
Southwest and southwest Texas; and the upper 80s and the 90s from
central Florida across the Virginias, and from southern Wisconsin
and southern lower Michigan across the central Gulf Coast and into
the lower Mississippi Valley.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Butte, Mont., to 79 degrees at Key West, Fla., and
Laredo, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 fair; Boston 67 partly cloudy; Buffalo 63
fair; Charleston, S.C. 66 fair; Cincinnati 62 hazy; Cleveland 63
fair; Detroit 68 fair; Miami 77 fair; New York 69 fair;
Philadelphia 67 fair; Pittsburgh 65 fair; Portland, Maine 53 partly
cloudy; Washington 73 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 65 cloudy; Chicago 71 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
65 thunderstorms; Denver 46 fair; Des Moines 70 fair; Indianapolis
67 fair; Kansas City 69 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71 cloudy;
