<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Laos-US     06-01 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laos-US,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laos Strongly Rejects U.S. Charges On Narcotics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laos has rejected American charges that
officials of that Communist nation may be involved in drug
trafficking.
   Laos' official radio said Harriet Isom, charge d'affaires of the
U.S. Embassy in Vientiane, was presented with a letter that said
the charges affected Laos' ``honor, dignity and prestige.''
   The letter was quoted Tuesday in a broadcast by domestic state
radio, a text of which was obtained from a Western embassy in
Bangkok today.
   On May 11, a State Department spokeswoman said there were
numerous reports that government and military officials of the Lao
People's Democratic Republic were involved in the drug trade.
   The spokeswoman, Phyllis Oakley, said the department had
submitted a report to Congress on March 1 stating that opium
cultivation and heroin production in Laos had increased
considerably in the past two years and the trend was likely to be
irreversible.
   The letter said Laos was ``extremely surprised to learn this as
relations between Laos and the United States have been further
improved another step, that is, the Lao side has done its utmost in
searching for the missing Americans (from the Vietnam war) while
the United States has also provided humanitarian assistance for the
people in the area affected by the natural disasters.''
   The letter said that after the Communist government came to
power in 1975, it had to deal with the consequences of the Vietnam
War, including opium, marijuana and heroin addiction under the
former regime.
   ``The Lao government has been trying to eliminate opium
cultivation, provide medical treatment for drug addicts and reduce
their number and come close to achieving an addiction-free
society,'' it said.
   U.S. narcotics officials estimate that 150-300 metric tons of
opium were produced in Laos in 1987, mostly by hill people for whom
it is an economic mainstay. The United States has no narcotics
control program in Laos, as it does in the other two countries that
also are part of the major drug-producing ``Golden Triangle'' _
Thailand and Burma.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
