<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ToxicLeak     06-01 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Leak,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acid Spill Causes Toxic Gas Leak; More Than 1,000 Flee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NILES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An acid spill at a factory released toxic
fumes into the air, forcing the evacuation of up to 2,000 residents
and sending 70 people to the hospital for treatment, authorities
said today.
   The leak occurred around 6:15 p.m. Tuesday at a
National-Standard wire and cable plant, and police evacuated people
living within three miles of the plant, said police dispatcher
Russell York.
   The area was declared safe about 9:15 p.m., and residents were
allowed to return, said Mayor Larry Clymer. Between 1,000 and 2,000
people live in the affected area in the southwestern Michigan city
of 15,000, according to York.
   Seventy people were treated for exposure to the fumes at
Pewating Hospital but none was admitted overnight, said nursing
supervisor Mary Ann Weaver.
   Many were players and spectators at softball fields near the
plant, Weaver said. Two of those treated were police officers, York
said.
   At least 130 people were sheltered temporarily at Ballard
Elementary School, school Superintendent John Huffman said.
   The accident apparently occurred after hydrochloric acid and
another acid were mixed in a storage tank, causing the tank to
rupture and the acids to form a puddle on the plant floor, said
Dennis Sexton, a dispatcher for the Berrien County Sheriff's
Department.
</TEXT>
