<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-01 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in Europe early today after a Japanese financial
official said the currency's recent rise could be short-lived.
   Gold bullion, underpinned by speculative buying of platinum,
leveled off in Europe at the higher price of $457.
   After rising in New York late Tuesday on the back of firmer U.S.
interest rates, the dollar opened steady in Europe today, then
dropped after Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told reporters
he thought a sustained rise in the dollar was unlikely.
   Traders said the remark heightened speculation that central
banks of the world's seven major industrialized nations would
intervene in the market to brake the dollar.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.7225 West German marks, down from 1.7292
   _1.4355 Swiss francs, down from 1.4437
   _5.8055 French francs, down from 5.8215
   _1.9328 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9333
   _1,280.50 Italian lire, up from 1,279.95
   _1.2330 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2357.
   The dollar advanced on the British pound, which dropped to
$1.8320 from $1.8385.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 125.23 Japanese yen, up from
124.80 yen on Tuesday. In later London trading today, the dollar
slipped to 125.15 yen.
   Gold bullion settled at higher levels in Europe after rising in
tandem with platinum. Heavy speculative buying by Japanese
investors pushed platinum to a high of $670 an ounce in Tokyo
overnight, before easing to $620 in London.
   At midmorning, London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended
gold price of $457 a troy ounce, down from an opening bid of
$458.30 but up from Tuesday's late rate of $454.80.
   Gold also was bid at $457 in Zurich, up from $455.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $458.55, up
from $455.80.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.75 a troy ounce,
up from $6.65.
</TEXT>
