<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Netherlands-TrainCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0561 06-01 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Netherlands-Train Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Killed, 20 Injured In Train Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with 20 injured, new details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train slammed today into
the back of a gravel-laden freight train on a main line in
southwestern Netherlands, killing two people and injuring 20, a
Dutch railway spokesman said.
   The cause of the collision, the country's worst in nearly six
years, was not immediately known, said spokesman Hans Meijer.
   One of the dead was believed to be the passenger train's
engineer, Meijer said. The other had not been identified.
   Two of the injured passengers were in serious condition, said
Meijer.
   The accident occurred at about 10:40 a.m. when a four-car
passenger train slammed into the stationary freight train, Meijer
said in a telephone interview from the railway's head office in
this central Dutch city.
   The passenger train, whose speed could not immediately be
established, was on its way from Roosendaal, a major junction 60
miles south of Amsterdam, to Vlissingen in the province of Zeeland,
Meijer said.
   Visibility was good at the site of the accident between the
stations of Rilland-Bath and Krabbendijke, where the double-track
Roosendaal-Vlissingen main line runs in a slight bend, he said.
   ``We haven't been able to establish why the gravel train was
standing still at that particular point, and why the engineer of
the passenger train didn't see it, or whether the signals failed,''
Meijer said.
   The Roosendaal-Vlissingen line is equipped with automatic
signals.
   Both tracks were blocked by the wreckage of both trains, Meijer
said, adding that the damage to the line and the overhead power
lines was considerable.
   Fatal train collisions are rare on the technically advanced
Dutch railway network, which is one of the busiest in the world.
   The last serious train accident occurred in December 1982, when
three passengers were killed in a collision near the port city of
Rotterdam.
</TEXT>
