<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-SovietJews 1stLd-Writethru a0465 06-01 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Soviet Jews, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number of Soviet Jewish Dropouts Reaches Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs to UPDATE with figures from Geneva group.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Soviet Jewish emigrants who
decided against coming to Israel reached a record high in May, when
more than 90 percent chose to settle elsewhere, a Soviet Jewish
activist told the Israeli newsagency Itim.
   Chaim Chessler, head of the Public Council for Soviet Jewry, was
quoted as saying Tuesday that soon no Soviet Jewish emigrants will
come to Israel unless they are flown via Bucharest, Romania,
instead of Vienna, Austria, where they are free to immigrate to
other Western countries.
   Israeli officials are embarrassed by the high dropout figure
because of their 20-year-long battle for the right of Soviet Jews
to emigrate on the grounds that Israel is their homeland.
   Israeli leaders claim 400,000 Soviet Jews want to settle in
Israel. But less than 20 percent of those who leave the Soviet
Union actually settle here.
   Chessler said that of the 1,169 Jews who left the Soviet Union
in May, just 110 came to Israel, a drop of nearly 7 percent from
April.
   Of the 4,695 Soviet Jews who have emigrated so far this year, 18
percent have settled in Israel, he added.
   Meanwhile, in Geneva, the Intergovernmental Committee for
Migration announced that Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union
through Vienna, Austria, reached a new seven-year high in May, when
1,145 Jews arrived at that city's transit center.
   May marked the fourth straight month of rising Jewish emigration
through Vienna, bringing the total for 1988 to 4,547 Soviet Jews
arriving there, the committee said.
   The figure was the highest since April 1981, when 1,155 Jews
left the Soviet Union through the Austrian capital.
   More than 250,000 Jews have found new homes since the committee
began its resettlement program in 1971.
   The committee did not include figures for the number of Soviet
Jews coming through Bucharest. Shmuel Binsky of the Public Council
on Soviet Jewry in Jerusalem said 24 Jews emigrated through
Bucharest in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Summit-Gorbachev-Glance     06-01 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Gorbachev-Glance,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev News Conference At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here at a glance are some of the key points raised
by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev during his news conference
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S.-SOVIET RELATIONS AND ARMS CONTROL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev noted that developments have become possible ``due to
realism'' but that it is ``not an easy process at all.''
   The 24-page document agreed at this meeting lays ``bricks so to
say for the building of our future relationship. It is a sign for
movement into the 21st century.''
   The exchange of ratification documents on the intermediate-range
weapons treaty ``turned the Moscow meeting into a watershed
political event in the Soviet-American dialogue and in world
politics as a whole.''
   Yet he said it is not easy to make progress on strategic arms,
calling negotiations on this issue ``the most complex task we
confronted in post-war politics.'' ``Step by step, we are moving
towards a treaty.''
   But he strongly criticized the contrary attitude that he said
had led to last-minute difficulties on agreeing the text of the
joint statement. ``I believe that we have missed a chance to take
an important step forward toward civilized relations,'' he said.
   He added however, that ``even though not everything has been
achieved as we would have wanted it, we will not make any dramatic
conclusions.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HUMAN RIGHTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev said ``there has been some progress in this sense,''
using wording that suggested resolution of some individual cases.
But he strongly criticized what he called ``propaganda gambits''
and ``all sorts of spectacles, all sorts of shows'' in apparent
allusion to Reagan's meeting Monday with dissidents and refuseniks.
   ``I'm not filled with admiration for this part of the visit,''
Gorbachev added.
   He noted that Reagan had had a chance to get to know Soviet
people and emphasized that the president, asked on Tuesday whether
he still stuck to his March 1983 view of the Svoiet Union as an
``evil empire,'' had said he did not.
   ``He said no and he said this within the walls of the Kremlin,
right in the heart of the evil empire,'' Gorbachev said. ``We take
note of this.''
   Reagan's ``evil empire'' comment sparked a torrent of vicious
comment when it was made, leading to an escalation in Soviet
attacks that culminated in comparision between Reagan and Adolf
Hitler in the deep freeze that followed the shooting down of the
Korean Air liner in September 1983 and the breaking off of arms
talks in Geneva in November that year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REGIONAL CONFLICTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On the Middle East, Gorbachev said for the first time that as
soon as an international conference on the region is convened, ``we
are prepared to address ourselves to regularizing relations with
Israel,'' severed in 1967.
   In general, Gorbachev said ``real possibilities have appeared
for solving regional problems,'' but gave no specifics.
   He cited the Afghanistan agreement as an example of what could
be achieved if the superpowers worked together with warring parties
to solve the conflicts, but noted that if Soviet forces now come
under attack from rebels as they withdraw, ``we shall react
accordingly and appropriately. That should be absolutely clear.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JACKSON-VANIK AMENDMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   After talking about what he called the contrary attitude of the
United States on some issues, Gorbachev singled out economic
relations.
   ``Authoritative parts of American business circles would like to
do business. They are faced with intimidation and all sorts of
restrictions,'' Gorbachev said.
   Alluding to the Jackson-Vanik amendment, he said, ``There is
indeed a most unfavored nation status with regard to the treatment
of the Soviet Union.''
   ``Why should the dead drag on the coattails of the living? One
is physically dead, the other is politically dead. The amendment
was passed in totally different circumstances a decade ago. We
should base our policies on present-day realities.''
   The amendment, passed by Congress in 1974, requires that any
communist nation give assurance of free emigration to be entitled
to most-favored-nation trade status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
