<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Newman,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deli Owner Testifies In Lawsuit Against Paul Newman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deli owner testified he was promised
part ownership of actor Paul Newman's food company in exchange for
promoting the products.
   Julius Gold claimed Tuesday that he was to receive a 1@12th
interest in Newman's Salad King Inc. and any spinoff corporations
for helping develop and sell Newman's Own salad dressing, spaghetti
sauce, lemonade and popcorn.
   Newman took copious notes on the opening day of testimony in the
Westport deli owner's suit. The actor sat beside author, longtime
friend and business partner A.E. Hotchner.
   Gold testified about taste tests and bottling discussions. At a
meeting in 1982, he said, the possibility of payment for his
efforts was discussed.
   The jury must decide whether Newman and the other defendants,
Hotchner and food distributor David Kalman, owe Gold a share in the
business.
   Newman's attorneys deny Gold's claims.
   It was not immediately known if Newman would take the stand.
   Since 1982, Newman's Own has donated all of its more than $15
million in profit to charity and helped create a camp for seriously
ill children.
