<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HandwritingAnalysis     06-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Handwriting Analysis,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Reluctantly Approves of Handwriting Analysis of Jurors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa's Court of Appeals has reluctantly
allowed prosecutors to use handwriting analysis in selecting jurors
but warned of a possible ``chilling effect.''
   ``Citizens may shy away from jury service if they know part of
serving is to have a determination made from their handwriting that
they are such things as `sexually frustrated' or `not a hugger,'''
the court said Tuesday.
   Despite its worries, the court refused to order a new trial in a
burglary case in which handwriting analysis was used in picking
jurors. The defendant, Merle LeRoy Knerr, had claimed that
prosecutors had gained an unfair advantage.
   In refusing to order a new trial, the court said it is ``a
recognized practice for an attorney to make investigations of
prospective jurors.''
   To warrant a new trial, it must be shown that prosecutors took
part in ``systematic and intentional exclusion of an identifiable
eligible group,'' the court said.
   At the same time, the court said of handwriting analysis,
``After reviewing the information presented by the expert we find
it to be of very minimal benefit to the jury selection process.''
   The appellate court also noted that it's already tough to get
citizens to accept jury duty.
   ``We have concern that the knowledge such procedures are used to
uncover information on jurors could have a chilling effect on
citizens' response to the call for jury service,'' the court said.
   ``Additionally, because of the number of persons employed in the
county attorney's office there is the possibility of inadvertent
disclosure.''
</TEXT>
