<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SommelierAward     06-01 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sommelier Award,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Named Best Sommelier Of French Wines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Lawrence Stone said today he won the
second international competition for best sommelier in French wine
and spirits by using his creativity to defeat a Frenchman.
   ``The judgment was very close, but I clearly won,'' he said of
the two-day competition, which ended Monday night. ``Over the two
days there were many opportunities to make mistakes and I made
less.''
   Frenchman Philippe Faure-Brac placed second and Japan's Mitsuo
Kogai of the Prince Hotels in Tokyo placed third.
   The competition, decided by a panel of international judges, was
organized by the International Association of Masters in French
Gastronomy and the Union of French Wine Stewards.
   It included tests of technical knowledge of French wines and
vineyards, blind taste tests and harmony between wines and dishes.
   Stone, 36, has been sommelier since 1984 at the Four Seasons
Olympic Hotel in Seattle. He was named best sommelier in French
wine and spirits in the United States in 1986 and three times has
received the Wine Spectator Award of Excellence.
   Stone said being creative helped him win.
   ``In the marriage of food and wine (category), you have to be
especially imaginative and relaxed and deal with the panel like you
were dealing with customers ... find new ideas, new combinations of
food and wine,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   ``The judges don't want to be bored. They want to be surprised.''
   Asked about winning over a Frenchman, he said, ``I think the
French are finding that surprising and maybe disappointing.''
   Stone said he had no one favorite wine.
   ``It's like saying one prefers just one kind of music. You can't
restrict yourself.'' California wines ``are in the top caliber,''
he said, adding that Washington state ``has some great Cabernets.''
   But choosing one wine, ``would be like a father who has a
favorite child.''
</TEXT>
