<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     06-01 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Extremists Launch Wave Of Arson, Bombings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists bombed a
government building, torched trains and forced shops to close in
southern and central Sri Lanka today to disrupt provincial
elections, authorities said.
   The government ordered police to shoot anyone causing a
disturbance.
   At least five people were injured when a bomb exploded in a
government building at Nuwara Eliya town, 64 miles east of Colombo,
according to officials in the capital who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   There were no other reports of casualties. However, offficials
said the explosions and fires damaged three trains bound for
Colombo, halting or delaying some rail service.
   Reports reaching the capital said government buildings and buses
were set ablaze in several towns in southern and central Sri Lanka.
In some places, extremists disrupted water, electricity and
communication lines, the officials said.
   State-run radio made special announcements that police and
security forces had been ordered to shoot anyone causing
disturbances.
   In Colombo, several shopkeepers closed their stores after
posters were shoved under their doors warning that they would be
attacked by Sinhalese Liberation Front members if they conducted
business.
   Police said posters also had appeared in southern Sri Lanka
stating that the front had ordered residents to stay at home
beginning this afternoon. Police and other authorities said the
front was trying to disrupt Thursday's voting.
   The front has opposed the elections, which are part of a peace
plan aimed at ending the nearly five-year Tamil separatist
insurgency on the island.
   A general manager for the railway department, G.P.S.
Weerasooriya, said fires broke out on two trains approaching
Colombo. He said the fires disrupted rail service to outlying areas.
   S. Ayupala, a police official in Panadura town, said front
members exploded a bomb on another train and removed railway ties
and spikes from the tracks.
   Residents in three of Sri Lanka's nine provinces went to the
polls April 28 to chose district councils in voting won by the
governing United National Party. The western and central provinces
vote Thursday for members of local government councils and the
southern province votes June 9. Dates for polls in the
Tamil-dominated northern and eastern provinces have not been
announced.
   The Sinhalese front says the Indian-brokered peace accord signed
in July gives too many concessions to the Tamils, who form 18
percent of the country's 16 million people.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population. The Sinhalese
front has threatened to kill anyone who supports the peace plan.
   Tamil rebels launched their separatist struggle in 1983,
claiming discrimination by the Sinhalese.
   The peace plan calls for the formation of district councils to
give additional powers to the provinces, and in effect gives the
Tamils more control. The Tamil rebels renounced the pact last year,
saying it did not go far enough.
</TEXT>
