<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HistoricFlight     06-01 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Historic Flight,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aviation Buffs Mark Kingsford-Smith Flight to Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son and widow of a pilot who made an
early flight across the Pacific joined 200 aviation buffs in
marking the journey's 60th anniversary.
   The dinner Tuesday was in honor of the 1928 flight by Sir
Charles Kingsford-Smith and a three-man crew. The four made the
10-day trip from Oakland to Brisbane, Australia, in a Fokker
Trimotor dubbed the Southern Cross.
   Kingsford-Smith ``made a significant contribution to the
progress of aviation,'' said Australian consul David Rutter,
chairman of the event at the Oakland Hilton Hotel.
   Dignitaries marking the anniversary in Australia took part in
the celebration via ham radio.
   Kingsford-Smith disappeared over the Bay of Bengal on a later
flight from Britain to Australia. His son, Charles Kingsford-Smith
Jr., was 2 at the time.
   Ten years ago, the younger Kingsford-Smith retraced his father's
flight.
   ``I never got to know my father as a man, so I wanted to get
some insight into what it was like for him,'' he said. ``I felt
like I grasped what the flight was like for my father and his crew,
but I think I'll leave the 100th anniversary flight to my kids.''
   ``I can't believe it's been 60 years,'' said the former Lady
Mary Kingsford-Smith, now Mrs. Frank Noldin. ``I think it's
fabulous that this much interest has been shown in the flight.''
</TEXT>
