<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia     06-01 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslav Communist Party Ends Conference With Upbeat Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party ended a
three-day conference by issuing an upbeat statement on the nation's
economic crisis that failed to criticize party leaders, as
delegates had demanded.
   ``The party is capable of seeking and finding a way out of the
political and economic crisis,'' said a 38-page document issued
Tuesday at the end of the conference, according to the official
Tanjug news agency.
   The statement also directed ``competent institutions and organs
to complete the reform of the economic system, based on strong
orientation toward market economy, by the end of the year,'' the
news agency said.
   At least four delegates, among 40 who objected to the final
text, said it failed to single out party leaders responsible for
the economic crisis.
   ``We have discussed one thing for three days and put down a
different thing in this document,'' one delegate, Predrag
Zivanovic, said.
   Many of the 800 delegates at the conference had accused the
party leadership of bungling and demanded their resignation. Some
delegates said the failure to solve economic problems was
destroying public trust in the party.
   Yugoslavia launched on Saturday its latest economic austerity
program designed to cope with a foreign debt of $21 billion,
Europe's highest annual inflation at 170 percent and an
unemployment rate of 15 percent.
   Economic problems have caused increasing social and labor
unrest. Last year there were more than 1,500 strikes involving more
than 300,000 workers who protested low and declining standards of
living.
   ``Young people are reluctant to join the Communist Party because
they have no confidence in our organization,'' Metka Tekavcic, a
Slovenian delegate, declared during one debate at the conference.
   Fewer than 10 percent of Yugoslavia's 23 million people belong
to the party and the number has been declining rapidly.
   In the opening speech of the conference on Sunday, party chief
Bosko Krunic rejected calls for a multiparty system. He also
predicted there will be new ``social upheavals'' once the austerity
measures, which include sharp price rises and wage controls, begin
to affect the nation.
   The measures were recommended by the International Monetary Fund.
   Some delegates also called for an extraordinary party congress,
but Ivan Brigic, a Presidium member, said such a conngress would
imply ``doubt that the plans of this party conference will be
materialized,'' the news agency said.
   He said the Central Commmittee alone will determine the leaders
responsible for the economic crisis if there is no improvement by
year's end.
   Before the document was adopted, Drasko Milicevic, a
representative of Serbia said it has ``too many words, too many
`one should,' `one needs,' `one must' ... the words we have all
become tired of.'' He demanded ``a drastic reduction'' of the text
to two or three pages _ ``with clear tasks.''
</TEXT>
