<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ObscenityLaw     06-01 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obscenity Law,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Videotape Retailers, Anti-Porn Group Head For Showdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Videotape retailers plan to use private
detectives and a boycott threat to strike back at a group that says
it will picket their stores in support of stricter anti-obscenity
laws taking effect today.
   The Minnesota Cleanup Project plans to protest at about 50
stores throughout the state Saturday to urge enforcement, said
Robert P. Heinrich, director of the anti-pornography organization.
   The amended law specifically includes videotapes in its
definition of materials that may be banned as obscene.
   David Ballstadt, president of a firm that runs 10 videotape
stores in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area, said store operators would
retaliate by hiring detectives and tracing protesters' license
plates to find where they are employed.
   Letters will be sent to the employers telling them their
products will be boycotted because of their employees' activities,
he said.
   ``If these people think they can walk around and express their
freedoms, which they have a right to do, they're going to have to
pay a price, just as we have to,'' Ballstadt said.
   At issue are amendments approved by the 1988 Legislature to
bring the state's law into conformity with obscenity rulings of the
U.S. Supreme Court.
   ``The changes technically are not that great, but they do
provide some tools for prosecutors to use,'' said state Solicitor
General Norm Coleman.
   The previous law provided only for civil penalties; the new law
provides for criminal penalties, he said. Conviction on a first
offense carries up to one year in prison, a $3,000 fine or both.
Subsequent convictions carry a prison term of up to two years, a
fine of up to $10,000 or both.
   Heinrich, whose group is an affiliate of the Berean League, a
conservative Christian lobbying organization, said, ``Anything on
film or video is more enticing than a still picture, and this
material is readily available to children of all ages and people of
all ages.''
   The protesters, Heinrich said, will picket ``major hard-core
pornography outlets'' that have refused to remove what the group
considers obscene materials from their shelves.
</TEXT>
