<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Church     06-01 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Church,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church of England Drops Commentary Linked to Cleric's Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of England is dropping the traditional
anonymous commentary from its next clerical directory because of
the suicide of a theologian who used it to lambast Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie, officials said today.
   The Church Commissioners and the Central Board of Finance, which
together oversee church investments and assets, said the commentary
was ``no longer a viable option.''
   Oxford University canon Gareth Bennett, 68, was found dead Dec.
7, five days after publication of his preface in the 1987-88
edition of the directory.
   The essay accused Runcie of being indecisive and overly liberal.
Although the article was unsigned, suspicion quickly fell on
Bennett because of his stature as a leader of the church's
conservative wing.
   It was widely interpreted as the opening shot in a campaign to
pressure Runcie into retirement and to block any attempt to replace
him with a liberal.
   Bennett was found dead in the garage of his home with a hose
leading into his car from the exhaust. Church officials later
confirmed that he wrote the preface.
   The Church Commissioners and Central Board of Finance said they
considered the possibility of publishing a signed commentary in
Crockford's Clerical Directory, but decided against it.
   The essay will be dropped from the 1989-90 edition of
Crockford's, the official biannual list of Anglican clergy, but no
decision has been made on whether to eliminate it permanently, a
joint statement said.
</TEXT>
