<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Protest,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Enraged Workers Break Into Ministry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of enraged Israeli workers broke into
the Finance Ministry today, smashing windows and clashing with
police who fired tear gas to disperse the crowd, police said.
   A Jerusalem police spokesman said five policemen were injured
slightly and four demonstrators were detained.
   Israel army radio said 15 workers were injured by tear gas
inhalation and several ministry officials were injured by broken
glass.
   The violence started when 400 workers from Beit Shemesh Engines,
the nation's largest producer of airplane engines, demonstrated
near the ministry to protest the breakdown of talks on compensation
for 260 workers laid off from their jobs.
   ``The workers did not obey our orders and overturned a police
barrier, lightly injuring five officers,'' Lt. Alex Lapidot said.
``Then several dozen broke into the ministry, smashing windows and
plants.''
   Israel radio said the workers set a fire outside the building,
then used a garbage can to force open the door and vandalize the
ministry.
   Lapidot said police fired tear gas grenades to break up the
clash. The radio said paramilitary border police and mounted police
were also called in.
   ``We do not fear tear gas,'' Moshe Levy, head of the workers'
committee, shouted through a megaphone as he led the workers to
another protest in front of Israel's nearby parliament building.
   No further violence was reported.
   The ministry's deputy director, Victor Medina, told Israel radio
the demands of the workers were ``highly exaggerated'' and could
not be met.
   Ministry spokesman Yitzhak Feinberg would not disclose specific
details of the labor talks.
</TEXT>
