<2ND_LINE>PM-Forgotten Passenger,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Hours Pass Before Car Crash Victim Is Discovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OVIEDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of an automobile passenger thrown
30 feet from a wreck went undiscovered for six hours because the
driver didn't remember that someone had been riding with him, says
a man who helped the motorist.
   Peter John Finch, 34, of Chuluota died early Tuesday after being
thrown against Albert Vest's house from a car that drifted off the
road and hit a fence, the Florida Highway Patrol said. The body
cleared 10-foot weeds, police said.
   Vest said no one in the Vest family heard the accident, but they
did hear driver James Albritton of Chuluota knock on the door
following the wreck.
   Albritton, 31, was in shock and did not remember if anyone had
been riding with him, Vest said.
   Vest said he and troopers searched around the car for evidence
or passengers and found none. He said they did not think to look by
the house because it was so far from the car. About 5:30 a.m., Vest
went to bed.
   Three hours later, he and some neighbors walked over to look at
the car and the damaged fence, he said. They looked toward the
house and saw Finch's body.
   A Highway Patrol spokeswoman said Albritton remembers nothing of
the accident. He was listed in stable condition at Winter Park
Memorial Hospital.
</TEXT>
