<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DisneyMonkey     06-01 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disney Monkey,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Monkey Born at Disney Headed for Program to Aid Disabled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first monkey born at a breeding colony
started by Walt Disney World has begun a three-year stay with a
family to help train the animal to assist handicapped people with
household tasks.
   ``We've been waiting two years for this,'' said Shirley Koehler
when Disney World officials Tuesday gave her Rusty, a 6-week-old
capuchin monkey. ``I can honestly say it's just like having my
first child. It's that exciting.''
   Disney started a colony of 63 monkeys in January and hopes to
produce 25 monkeys a year for a program called Helping Hands:
Simian Aides for the Disabled.
   By living with Koehler and her husband, Rusty will learn to
trust humans; the Koehlers, in effect, will be Rusty's foster
parents. Then Rusty will go to Boston University School of Medicine
for six more months of training.
   The Koehlers are not disabled.
   Eventually, Rusty will learn to take food from a refrigerator
and place it in front of its owner, put a Thermos in a holder, open
its lid and put in a straw.
   The animal will also learn to clean up spills and bring a
quadriplegic a mouth stick, which is used to type and turn book
pages.
   The program was started 10 years ago by Mary Joan Willard, a
behavioral scientist at Boston University. Seven monkeys from other
breeding programs have been placed with quadriplegics and 11 more
are in training.
   Nearly 70 more are in foster homes across the United States.
</TEXT>
