<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-RegionalConflicts     06-01 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Regional Conflicts,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Threatens Action in Afghanistan, Hints At Mideast
Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev today
condemned rebel attacks on Soviet troops withdrawing from
Afghanistan and said it ``should be absolutely clear'' that his
forces would respond to any further assaults.
   He also told a televised news conference at the close of his
summit talks with President Reagan that the Soviet Union will
consider restoring diplomatic relations with Israel as soon as an
international conference on the Middle East is convened.
   Gorbachev indicated, however, that disagreements over
Palestinian representation and other issues still block agreement
on calling an international conference. The Kremlin severed
relations with Israel in 1967 over Israel's six-day war against its
Arab neighbors.
   At separate post-summit news conferences, Reagan and Gorbachev
both cited the agreement on a Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan as
an example of how the superpowers can help settle regional
conflicts by working with parties that are directly involved.
   But Gorbachev noted Afghan rebel attacks on Soviet troops and
the embassy in Kabul, including one attack near Kandahar on Tuesday
in which several Soviet soldiers died.
   If Soviet forces come under attack as they withdraw, ``we shall
react accordingly and appropriately,'' Gorbachev said. ``That
should be absolutely clear.''
   A senior U.S. official, speaking only on condition that he not
be identified, said Gorbachev clearly meant that his army would
return fire if attacked by Moslem rebels battling the Soviet-backed
government in Kabul.
   This official said Gorbachev complained to Reagan during their
summit talks about the attacks on withdrawing Soviet troops.
   At the same time, however, Soviet chief of staff Marshal Sergei
Akhromeyev outlined details of the schedule for withdrawal of an
estimated 115,000 troops from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   The Soviets recently disclosed that 311 of their soldiers were
missing in action there. President Reagan told a Moscow State
University students Tuesday that the United States was willing to
assist efforts to find the missing troops.
   Gorbachev said today that American and Pakistani authorities had
been contacted and that ``we shall do all we can to return these
people to their homes.''
   On the Middle East, Gorbachev said ``there has been a drawing
closer of our positions'' with superpower agreement on the need for
an international conference. Problems of Palestinian representation
and an agenda are still to be resolved, he said.
   ``We've given the Americans several years of opportunity to go
it alone'' in the Middle East, Gorbachev said. ``They saw that they
couldn't.''
   Gorbachev told reporters that ``real possibilities have appeared
for solving regional problems,'' but neither he nor Reagan
discussed details of their discussions on Central America, southern
Africa, Cambodia and Korea.
</TEXT>
