<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Brite--NameChange     06-01 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite--Name Change,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wilbur Jimbob Rogers Won't Be On Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If C. Rabon Martin wants to run for a seat
on a state regulatory agency, he can't do it under the name Wilbur
Jimbob Rogers.
   Martin said Judge Robert Caldwell dismissed his request for a
name change Tuesday because he was leery of ``sanctioning this
statewide big political joke.''
   Martin, an attorney and candidate for the Corporation
Commission, which regulates state utilities and the oil and gas
industry, said the judge also expressed concern that the ``intent
of it is to be confusing to the voter.''
   ``He thought it would be a bad idea for me professionally,''
Martin said.
   Martin said while his action may help establish ``parameters for
buffoonery,'' it was a ``joke that also has a moral. The intent is
to kick people in the pants and say, `Think before you vote.' ''
   In a May 11 court petition, Martin said he wanted the change
``as a measure of the degree of respect and regard ... for
Oklahoma's political heritage.''
   He said he selected Wilbur in honor of Wilbur Wright, a former
state labor commissioner often cited as an example of the political
value of a famous name.
   Martin liked Jimbob for its ``basic down-home appeal,'' and
thought ``anyone named Rogers has always been able to get elected
to anything in Oklahoma,'' where the humorist Will Rogers was born.
   He said he would have changed his name back to C. Rabon Martin
after the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
