<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     06-01 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30 Die In Clashes Between Soldiers And Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 30 people were killed in
clashes between government troops and communist rebels in the past
five days, including six soldiers who were ambushed south of
Manila, the military said today.
   In another incident, 10 armed men believed to be rebels abducted
a vice mayor and killed a village leader in Ilocos Norte, military
officials in the northern province said today.
   They said the body of Rudy Balbag, chief of the Dadaor village
was found today near the house where he and Vice Mayor Willie Gaces
of nearby Bangui town were abducted the night before.
   Lt. Col. Romeo Acop, Philippine Constabulary provincial
commander, said the two men were attending a funeral wake in Dadaor
when heavily armed men arrived Tuesday. The armed men dined with
Balbag and Gaces, then bound them and took them away, Acop said.
   The latest clash between government forces and the communist New
People's Army occurred Tuesday when guerrillas killed six soldiers
in a mountain village in Laguna province, 35 miles southeast of
Manila, a military report said.
   The report said the soldiers were on foot patrol when a 40-man
rebel band, waiting in ambush, open fired. The rebels withdrew
after a brief firefight.
   On Samar island, 400 miles southeast of Manila, soldiers killed
three guerrillas during a skirmish Tuesday near the town of
Salcedo, a Philippine Constabulary report said.
   In another incident, Philippine Constabulary soldiers gunned
down two members of a 70-man insurgent force Tuesday in the town of
Bansud in Oriental Mindoro province, 130 miles south of Manila.
   On Mindanao island, government troops on Tuesday killed six
rebels in repulsing an attack by 100 guerrillas in the town of
Valencia in Bukidnon province, 550 miles southeast of Manila, said
Philippine army chief Brig. Gen. Mariano Adelem.
   He said the rebels attacked an army detachment in Valencia but
fled after government reinforcements arrived. There were no
casualties on the government side, Adalem added.
   Maj. Laureano Palanas, spokesman of the military's Southern
Command, said communist rebels killed two militiamen and a civilian
Saturday in a village outside Tangub city in Misamis Occidental
province, 490 miles southeast of Manila. Palanas said the three
were on their way to report on a rebel attack on their village when
they were killed.
   In a nearby village, another rebel force killed three civilians
and three militiamen, Palanas said. He said four rebels were killed
by soldiers.
   The rebel army, the armed wing of the outlawed Communist Party
of the Philippines, has been waging a 19-year insurgency to
establish a Marxist state.
</TEXT>
