<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DeadFish     06-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dead Fish,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fish, Seal Deaths Blamed On Waste Polluting North Sea Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government minister today called for
international action to reduce pollution in the North Sea and
Baltic Sea after thousands of fish and hundreds of seals were
reported dead along their shores.
   Environment Minister Klaus Toepfer told a special Parliament
committee meeting that action to reduce the dumping of wastes was
needed because of ``strong suspicions'' it threatened sea life.
   During the meeting, the opposition Greens Party demanded the
government immediately ban ships from getting rid of chemical and
other wastes at sea.
   About 50 dead seals have been found on West German shorelines in
the past month, while about 300 have been discovered along
Denmark's coasts, Toepfer said.
   He said biologists checking the dead seals discovered they were
suffering from a virus that caused their deaths. Experts last
weekend said pneumonia was the ``final cause'' of death.
   Thousands of tons of fish meanwhile died from a blanket of
yellow sea algae in the North Sea, Toepfer said.
   The algae, up to 10 feet thick in some places, spread from the
coasts of Norway and Sweden and now threatens Denmark, Danish
officials said.
   West German reports have said the fish were dying from slime
from the algae, which coated their gills and prevented them from
breathing.
   Experts blamed nitrates from agricultural fertilizers and
phosphorus from sewage and industrial pollution for the dramatic
growth of the algae.
   In Norway, fish farmers were advised to kill their fish. Resort
owners in western Denmark fear news of the algae may ruin the
summer tourist season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
