<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoldierofFortune     06-01 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier of Fortune,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Contract Murderer Sentenced to 40 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man paid $20,000 to carry out a
murder arranged through an ad in Soldier of Fortune magazine has
been sentenced to the maximum 40 years in prison for the bungled
grenade bombing three years ago.
   Richard Michael Savage, 39, of Knoxville, Tenn., was convicted
April 6 on charges of soliciting a murder contract in the bombing
of Dana Free's Houston-area home. Free was not at home at the time
of the bombing.
   Savage, who offered no defense at trial, ran a ``gun for hire''
advertisement in Soldier of Fortune in 1985.
   A teminally ill Colorado widow pleaded guilty to paying Savage
$20,000 to kill Free, her former business partner. Alice V. Brado,
who later died in prison, said Free bilked her out of her life
savings of $300,000.
   U.S. District Judge James DeAnda sentenced Savage on Monday.
   ``I think that he deserved to get the maximum in this type of
case,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Gary Cobe.
   Savage already is serving a 40-year term in federal prison for
arranging the beating death of the former assistant city manager of
West Palm Beach, Fla.
   He also has been sentenced to 25 years in prison in an unrelated
case for attempted murder-for-hire and threatening a witness.
   In an unrelated lawsuit against Soldier of Fortune, a federal
jury in Houston awarded $9.4 million earlier this year to the
family of a woman killed by a man hired through the magazine.
</TEXT>
