<HEAD>Reagan News Conference At A Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights from President
Reagan's news conference following his summit talks with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>EMIGRATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Avoiding any direct criticism of Gorbachev, the president said
Soviet emigration barriers may arise from the Kremlin's being
``bound in by bureaucracy'' rather than a willful Soviet policy of
preventing Jews from leaving the country. He said Gorbachev has
been cooperative when injustices were brought to his attention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>ARMS CONTROL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Reagan held out hope for agreement before he leaves office next
January on a treaty reducing U.S. and Soviet arsenals of long-range
strategic nuclear weapons by 50 percent. But the president said
he'd refuse to give negotiators in Geneva any deadlines because
``that is not the way to get a good treaty.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>SUMMIT MEETING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The president refused to commit himself to a fifth summit
meeting with Gorbachev, but did not rule out the possibility that
it might be held, even if a weapons treaty is not ready for
signing. ``Something else may come up,'' he said. ``No one can say,
`No, there will be no need for another summit'.''
