<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NearCollision     06-01 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Near Collision,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Says Evidence Lacking in Near Collision Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines says there's no doubt one
of its aircraft was endangered by a small plane flying in
restricted airspace, but a federal official says he has only the
co-pilot's word as evidence.
   According to the airline, the close call occurred Monday at
about 7,000 feet and five miles southeast of Cleveland Hopkins
International Airport, the destination of Flight 283 from Boston.
The DC-9 was carrying 79 people.
   The co-pilot told Continental officials he had finished making
some notes, looked up and saw a small aircraft ``coming right at
us,'' said airline spokesman Bruce E. Hicks.
   The pilot swerved to avoid the plane. A flight attendant hurled
to the floor suffered bruises.
   Hicks said the co-pilot, whom he refused to identify, described
the small plane as a Piper Aztec or Seminole.
   ``The first officer (co-pilot), the captain, vice president of
flight operations and president (of Continental) are all
dumbfounded that there is apparently a question as to the details
of the incident,'' Hicks said Tuesday.
   The Federal Aviation Administration and the National
Transportation Safety Board are investigating the airline's report,
but an FAA official said, ``We can't even confirm there were two
planes.''
   Dennis Ragle, air traffic control manager for the FAA at
Hopkins, said, ``There is no tangible evidence there was another
plane, other than what the (co-pilot) said. The only thing we
really have is that a Continental co-pilot said there was a plane.''
   Ragle said that four air traffic controllers were unable to spot
the second plane on radar after the report. He said radar was
effective at that altitude and that ``it is not really explainable
that we don't see the target (the second plane).''
   ``If there was another airplane, it would have been in violation
of several federal aviation regulations,'' he said.
   A Continental spokesman, Ned Walker, said small planes could be
missed by radar if they are not using transponders, which give
radar observers specific information.
</TEXT>
