<1ST_LINE>r p PM-McMillan-Moynihan     06-01 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-McMillan-Moynihan,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moynihan Opponent Officially Enters Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Robert McMillan, a lawyer who
lost his only other bid for elective office 24 years ago, today
officially opened his campaign to unseat Democratic U.S. Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
   McMillan, 55, emerged only after several prominent Republicans,
including U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani and Ronald Lauder, former
U.S. ambassador to Austria, refused to challenge the popular
two-term senator.
   ``I have been blessed with a wonderful and loving family; I live
in a beautiful home, and I have been successful in business,''
McMillan said in a statement. ``Now it is time to pay back the
American system that has been so good to me.''
   McMillan conceded that he faces an ``uphill battle'' against
Moynihan, but said he has ``one thing in my favor, the issues.''
   ``For too long, the Democratic senator from New York has chosen
to ignore the problems that confront the average family in this
state,'' he said.
   McMillan pledged to make acid rain, day care for working
families, garbage disposal and an anti-drug campaign among his top
domestic policy interests. In foreign affairs, McMillan said that
he would stand behind Israel and that the United States should
battle communism by improving the economies of developing nations.
   McMillan is an attorney in a Garden City, N.Y., firm. His only
previous attempt at elective office came in 1964, when he was
easily defeated in a special election for a New York City Council
seat.
   McMillan will be trying to overcome statewide obscurity much in
the same way fellow Republican Alfonse D'Amato did when the former
Hempstead town supervisor captured New York's other senatorial seat
in 1980.
   D'Amato's victory was among the few bright spots in more than a
decade of often lopsided defeats for Republicans seeking statewide
office in New York, where registered Democrats outnumber
Republicans by about 1 million.
   Many times, Republicans have had trouble just finding candidates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
