<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp     06-01 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. General Says Iran Building New Silkworm Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS CORONADO IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran is about
to complete a major new Silkworm missile complex in the Strait of
Hormuz, the top U.S. military commander for the Middle East said
today.
   Iran, despite recent losses in a sea battle with the U.S. Navy,
is ``not out of the game,'' said Gen. George B. Crist, chief of the
U.S. Central Command, which has administrative responsibility for
the region.
   The Iranians have been ``very circumspect and careful,'' Crist
said, ``but I don't get any feeling that the Iranians have run up a
white flag or that sort of thing ... I would not say they have
given up their thoughts about trying to get to us.''
   Crist said a major Silkworm missile complex was under
construction at Kuhestak, overlooking the central part of the
Strait of Hormuz, the gateway to the Persian Gulf. Silkworms fired
from there with a range of 50-60 miles would ``cover the entire
strait,'' he said.
   The four-star Marine general spoke to members of a Pentagon news
media pool aboard the Coronado, the navy's flagship in the gulf.
   He said the super-sophisticated ``Aegis'' missile cruiser
Vincennes, which arrived in the gulf during last week, was deployed
partly because of the new Silkworm facility.
   The 9,400-ton ship's long-range air surveillance and weapons
systems represents ``a quantum leap forward in our ability to
handle that threat,'' Crist said.
   The Kuhestak missile site is a fixed installation as opposed to
the mobile launcher used by Iran in the past. It could be
operational by late summer, he said.
   Iran was suspected of having mobile Silkworm sites in the Faw
Peninsula in the northern gulf and the Strait of Hormuz. Crist's
comments indicated more missiles could be positioned at the new
site.
   The Silkworm is a Chinese version of the 30-year-old Soviet Styx
missile. Subsonic and crude by modern standards, it nevertheless
can be devastating to ships.
   On April 18, U.S. forces destroyed two Iranian offshore
platforms, sank a patrol boat and crippled two frigates in a series
of gulf battles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
