<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoatCapsizes     06-01 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boat Capsizes,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Plan No Charges in Fatal Boating Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COFFEEVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said no charges will be
filed in a Memorial Day boating accident in which seven people died.
   Yalobush County Coroner Stanley True said Tuesday the sheriff's
office found no foul play in the drowning of six young women and
the man who tried to rescue them. The coroner ruled the deaths
accidental.
   Robert Armstrong, who was operating the 16-foot flat-bottomed
fishing boat Monday, acknowledged the boat was overloaded. He said
the boat's occupants were on a slow ``joy ride,'' splashing each
other when the vessel capsized.
   Armstrong swam to shore. Another occupant of the boat clung to
the boat and was rescued by a fisherman.
   Witnesses told the Sheriff's Department the boat was about 30
yards from the shore of the 25-acre lake when the accident
occurred. The bodies were recovered in eight to 10 feet of water.
</TEXT>
