<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-GorbachevText 1stAdd   06-01 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorbachev Text, 1st Add,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: a treaty. ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   I feel that we have now approached a situation where we should
note that here too, insofar as the hot trouble spots (on the)
planet are concerned, real possibilities have appeared for solving
these regional problems, for untying _ unraveling these knots _
these tight knots on the basis of political approaches, on the
basis of a balance of interests.
   In substance, we have noted today that first there is
Afghanistan, then secondly there is the processes concerning the
Middle East. There is some joining closer together of positions and
a maturing of understanding that there is a need to resolve the
problem on the basis of an international conference. ...
   Then there is the problem of Campuchia, thanks to the
initiatives taken by Viet Nam and Campuchia of late. That problem
too is now becoming one which can be _ which does lend itself to
solutions very soon. There are processes under way in Latin-Central
America, in southern Africa, solutions are possible. ...
   I have always emphasized and I emphasize this in my
conversations with the president, as with all other Americans, we
should not _ we must not lose our chance. And in this connection, I
said outright to the president that the signing of the agreement on
Afghanistan is a precedent which goes far beyond the limits of that
problem alone, because it is the first case, first example, where
the United States and the Soviet Union, together with those
directly involved in the conflict, signed an agreement which opens
up an avenue for a political solution of that problem. ...
   In questions concerning human rights, humanitarian issues, there
has been some progress in this sense. I posed the question in my
talks with the president. I said there are facts relating to this
sphere, individual cases, which do appear. We've always been giving
attentive consideration to them, and we shall continue to do so.
... The more I think over this situation, the more I come to the
conclusion that I can see that the American administration does not
have a real understanding of the real situation insofar as human
rights are concerned. They just don't know about the processes in
the sphere of democracy and democratization in this country. ...
   So I suggested to the president, let's organize, within the
framework of inter-parliamentary exchange, a permanent seminar
which would gather together members of our parliaments,
representatives of political circles, public circles, and they
should then exchange information and assessments. ...
   The president _ somebody asked the president whether he still
considered the Soviet Union to be an ``evil empire.'' He said no,
and he said that within the walls of the Kremlin, next to the
czar's gun, right in the heart of that ``evil empire.'' We take
note of that. As the ancient Greeks say, everything flows,
everything changes. Everything is in a state of flux. ...
   Today, when we were able to see that you cannot resolve any of
the world's problems through military means _ where we came more
and more to the conclusion that they have to be resolved
politically, by political means on the basis of a balance of
interest, on the basis of respect for the social choice. And
whether we want to or not, we must all learn to live in peace in
this real world of ours. ...
   And proceeding ... from the fact that there is an understanding
_ in fact, that there are lessons which we have drawn from the
events in the past years, we suggested, let us then make a
statement to that effect _ a joint statement to that effect. Here
is the draft that I suggested to the president:
   ``Both of us proceeding from an awareness of the obtaining
realities in the present day world believe that no problems in
dispute are insoluble and that they should not be resolved by
military means, that peaceful co-existence is something that we
resolve as a universal principle of international relations, and
that the equality of all states, non-interference in domestic
affairs, and freedom of socio-political choice should be recognized
as inalienable and mandatory for all.''
   I gave the president both the Russian and English text. He read
it and he said, ``I like it.'' But when today we met in order to
finalize the text of the joint statement it turned out that not
everybody likes it among those who surround the president, that
kind of a statement. And that's what we were debating this morning.
...
   We were not able either to agree on the subject of talks on
conventional arms in Europe. ...
   Now I'm thinking, there's so much talk that we should not move
forward to 50 percent cuts in strategic arms unless we address
ourselves to reductions in conventional arms and armaments in
Europe. But as soon as we try to suggest some _ make some real
proposals, in order to get that process under way, we immediately
come up against some kind of incomprehensible maneuvers and
attempts to deviate from that _ from the issue. When everybody
voiced concern over the fact that the Warsaw Treaty supposedly has
a preponderance, we said, ``OK, let's exchange data, let's exchange
data.'' The other side immediately tried to dodge the issue. ...
   The Americans did not accept our bold plan, three-phase plan for
eliminating asymmetry and disbalances in Europe aimed at building a
structure of non-offensive arms and armed forces, with a
considerably lower level of arms. We feel that we've missed a good
chance to impart some good dynamics, both to relations between the
two most powerful military groups, and thereby to promote
international security as a whole. ...
</TEXT>
