<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ClothingFraud     06-01 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clothing Fraud,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former N.J. Legislator Sentenced To Probation in Bribery Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former New Jersey legislator who said he
was trying to save his clothing business has been placed on three
years' probation for paying $17,300 in bribes to secure $7.2
million in federal contracts.
   Joseph Chinnici, who served 16 years as a legislator before
retiring in January, also was ordered by U.S. District Judge Thomas
O'Neill Jr. on Tuesday to perform 300 hours of community service.
   Chinnici, 68, pleaded guilty in January to conspiracy and making
false statements.
   His Major Coat Co. of Bridgeton, N.J., which also had pleaded
guilty, received contracts worth more than $75 million from the
Defense Personnel Support Center in Philadelphia.
   More than two dozen individuals and companies already have
pleaded guilty to involvement in the conspiracy at the center,
which supplies clothes and other items to U.S. military personnel
throughout the world.
   ``In my heart, I know that everything I have done was done to
save my business and the jobs of the many people it employs,''
Chinnici said in a statement issued after his sentencing.
   He could have received up to 10 years in prison and a $500,000
fine. He and his company have paid more than $400,000 in
restitution.
   O'Neill ignored the request of Assistant U.S. Attorney Lee
Dobkin that Chinnici be sent to jail as a deterrent to others.
   The judge cited Chinnici's public service record and said his
disgrace, the burden on his family and the virtual destruction of
his business were punishment enough.
</TEXT>
