<DOCNO> AP880601-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0473 06-01 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Tells Bush It's Too Soon to Say No Tax Hike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 13 grafs with Frenzel, Bush comments, picking
up in 4th graf pvs, ``I've pledged; deletes grafs 11-13 pvs, Also
attending ... on inflation, and deletes last 3 grafs pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With George Bush looking on, a
Republican member of a bipartisan deficit-reduction commission said
today the panel would not be swayed from doing its job by Bush's
declaration that he would oppose any tax increase.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn., said he thought such comments were
premature.
   Frenzel, who is here at Bush's vacation retreat for the second
of two days of talks on economic issues, told reporters, ``We are
not going to get involved in any presidential campaigns.''
   Bush, the all-but-certain Republican presidential nominee, said
Tuesday that he would ignore what he said was a likely
recommendation from the National Economic Commission for a tax
increase to reduce the budget deficit.
   During a picture-taking session today on the porch of the vice
president's seaside home, Frenzel was asked if he felt Bush's
remarks would inhibit his own work on the commission.
   ``I took an oath to work on the commission and to do it well,''
Frenzel said.
   At that point, Bush interrupted, saying, ``I hope the commission
will listen a little bit to the American people in this election. I
think that's what an election is all about. The commission can take
an objective look at (taxes) and do whatever it wants. But I'd be
more persuaded by what Americans say.''
   Former deputy Treasury secretary Richard Darman, one of a
half-dozen private economists here for the talks, said taxes were
``off the table and nobody has raised it yet.''
   Bush was asked to comment on Democratic charges that his call
for closing the budget deficit with a modified freeze on spending
and with no new taxes was not realistic.
   Bush said: ``It is not surprising the Democrats would say that.
All they want to do is spend and tax. There is no change I can see
or hear out on the campaign that would lead you to believe anything
other than that on the Democratic side.''
   One day earlier, Bush, who touts himself as a would-be
``education president,'' said local taxes may have to go up if his
call for better schools is heeded.
   ``They may have to,'' Bush said Tuesday. ``Ninety-three percent
of the money for education comes from sources other than the
federal government. If it's taxes, that's where it has to be.''
   Bush's comments came as he repeated his oft-stated opposition to
a federal tax increase.
   ``I've pledged no tax increase and I'm going to stay with it,
period,'' Bush said.
   The vice president, speaking after meeting with a group of
private economists, also cautioned the Federal Reserve Board
against clamping down too tightly on credit in the name of fighting
inflation.
   ``I'm not hypercritical of the Fed, but I don't want to see
action taken that's going to shut down economic growth in this
country,'' Bush said.
   The deficit-reduction panel, formed earlier this year, plans to
submit its recommendations to Congress on Dec. 21. In addition to
members appointed by the Reagan administration and by both parties
in Congress, the panel will have two members named by whoever wins
the election in November.
   ``It seems to me that the commission might well come up with a
tax increase. And I'll be saying, `Wait a minute. I've taken my
case to the American people to hold the line on taxes.'''
   Bush has proposed eliminating the budget deficit with what he
calls a ``flexible freeze'' on spending. All programs, except
Social Security benefits, would be held at 1989 levels plus
inflation. Increases in one area would have to be offset by
decreases in another.
   The vice president holds a second day of talks today with the
same group of economic advisers. Among them is Martin S. Feldstein,
a Harvard economist who quit his job as President Reagan's chief
economist in 1985 when his advocacy of a tax increase to reduce the
budget deficit ran afoul of the administration's stance against
general tax increases.
   Bush said that during his meeting Tuesday with the economic
advisers, ``there was an expression of hoping that Fed policy would
not be too tight.''
   ``I think watching for signs of inflation is fine,'' Bush said.
``But as a word of caution, I wouldn't want to see them step over
some boundary that would ratchet down, tighten down, the economic
growth.''
   The nation is in its 65th month of economic expansion, a
peacetime record. An economic downturn before the election could
spell big troubles for Republicans' election prospects, most
economic and political consultants agree.
   The Bush campaign has been having some economic problems of its
own lately _ a shortage of cash.
   Two months ago, Bush aides reported that they only had $4
million left to spend before the Republican convention. Aide Robert
Teeter said Tuesday that the amount has now dwindled to just under
$1.5 million.
   The vice president said over the weekend that the squeeze may
mean some curtailing of campaign travel in the weeks ahead.
   The Bush campaign has had no trouble raising money, but it is
close to bumping up against the pre-convention federal spending
limit of $27 million.
   The campaign has raised $29.5 million, of which about $2.5 is
not subject to the ceiling.
</TEXT>
