<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan-Journalist     06-01 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Journalist,2nd Ld-Writethru,a0586,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed Italian Journalist To Be Freed By Afghan Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with conflicting reports on time
Italian was held. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Biloslavo had ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian journalist jailed in Afghanistan has been
pardoned and will be released shortly, the Foreign Ministry
announced today.
   President Najib of Afghanistan assured an Italian envoy at a
Kabul meeting today that he signed a decree to pardon Fausto
Biloslavo, the ministry said, adding that the journalist is
expected to be freed by Thursday.
   Biloslavo, who worked for the tiny Albatross news agency, was
captured last year after entering Afghanistan from Pakistan with
Moslem guerrillas. He was convicted in March of espionage and
sentenced to seven years in prison.
   There have been conflicting reports on when he entered
Afghanistan and the date of his arrest. Earlier reports from
Afghanistan said he was detained in July, but his news agency and
the Foreign Ministry said today he was captured in mid-November.
   Biloslavo had shared a jail cell with French photojournalist
Alain Guillo, who was freed last Saturday after nine months
imprisonment in Afghanistan.
   The Italian envoy, Bruno Bottai, secretary general of the
Foreign Ministry, went to Afghanistan with a message from Italian
President Francesco Cossiga asking Biloslavo's release on
humanitarian grounds, the ministry said.
</TEXT>
