<TEXT>
   May 31
   Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch on New Jersey's takeover of the
Jersey City public schools because of ``managerial bankruptcy'':
   The underlying cause of Jersey City's education impoverishment?
In a word: politics. ...
   The victims of the politicization of Jersey City's schools are,
of course, the children, 85 percent of them black or Hispanic. Only
one in four of them is able to pass a basic proficiency
examination, compared with 80 percent of students throughout the
state.
   It is no wonder that little learning occurs in a system so
heavily infected by boss politics.
   Under the reform law championed by Republican Gov. Thomas H.
Kean, the state will have five years to set the system aright,
assuming that its takeover survives legal challenge in the first
place.
   How much the state can accomplish is debatable, but if it at
least can free local education management from the paralyzing grip
of local cronyism, it will have helped.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 27
   Westerly (R.I.) Sun on Israel and peace in the Middle East:
   President Reagan hit the nail smack on the head when he made a
point of lauding Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres for backing
United States efforts to get Middle East peace negotiations going
again.
   If Israel's Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir felt the smack, good;
if he modifies his opposition to the peace plan because of the
smack, so much the better.
   Shamir has consistently spurned the plan, refusing to consider
any variant of the ``land for peace'' formula on which hope for a
settlement rests.
   A principled stance, perhaps _ but one lacking any sign of
reasoned flexibility. ...
   Reagan rightly, if only by implication, took him to task.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 27
   The (Portland) Oregonian on a Mars mission:
   Mikhail Gorbachev ... made headlines with his proposal for a
joint Soviet-U.S. unmanned flight to Mars.
   It conjures up an attractive idea of the two superpowers using
their scientific skill cooperatively instead of competitively to
achieve another giant leap for mankind.
   The trick would be to organize the project so that suspicions
didn't complicate an already difficult mission. ...
   One nation's secret equipment could be enclosed in a sealed box
that could be plugged into the other nation's spaceship.
   Or each country could send its own payload separately from
Earth, to work cooperatively on Mars.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 31
   Fort Lauderdale (Fla.) Sun-Sentinel on U.S. efforts to oust
Noriega:
   A clumsy political exercise has come to an embarrassing end.
There will be new episodes but, for now, Reagan administration
efforts to oust Gen. Manuel Noriega from power in Panama are over.
   One can only hope that the administration's Central American
strategists, if there are any, will use the respite to regroup and
try to formulate a coherent policy to deal with the man who has
outmaneuvered them at every turn.
   What began months ago with blustery assertions by White House
officials that Noriega was packing his bags turned into an
escalating series of rejected U.S. concessions and ended with the
intended deportee more firmly entrenched than ever. ...
   Small wonder that the kindest thing that diplomatic analysts
from other governments in Central America and Europe can say about
U.S. policy in Panama is that it has been inconsistent and
incompetent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 26
   The Brunswick (Ga.) News on House Speaker Jim Wright:
   The concern voiced over Speaker Jim Wright's alleged breaches of
House ethics rules is no mere teapot tempest, as he would have us
believe.
   Though some of his conservative opponents have been muttering
about this for some time, and would love to catch him out, the
dispute cannot be shrugged off as a political vendetta.
   Any such characterization went out the window when Common Cause,
which has a solid reputation for probity and often takes a liberal
stance on public questions, called for an ethics committee inquiry.
   Wright's sour claim that Common Cause was a ``handmaiden'' for
conservatives out to get him is not credible.
   The speakership is a powerful position. The person who occupies
it can do a lot for and against members of the House.
   But the ethics committee, if formally asked to investigate, will
have an overriding responsibility to do so. And if Wright is
blameless, an investigation reaching this conclusion would serve
his interests as well as those of the House and the electorate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 31
   Tulsa (Okla.) World on drug abuse:
   Cocaine has lost is charm for affluent yuppies. That means drug
use is down, right?
   Wrong.
   What used to be the recreational drug of the rich has become a
highly dangerous street drug used by the unemployed poor. That's
not particularly startling news, but it could have an effect few
have considered.
   More and more of the wealthy are realizing the danger of cocaine
and have stopped using it as a ``party drug.''
   The message that cocaine is dangerous and addictive is getting
through to the middle class. But, that same message is not making
it to the inner city.
   Although it might not be as visible as it once was, cocaine ...
remains a big problem.
   Writing it off as a plague of the inner city poor will not make
it go away.
</TEXT>
