<HEAD>UNDATED: go away.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 25
   The Hudson Dispatch, Union City, N.J., on plastic gun
legislation:
   The Senate Judiciary Committee took a reasonable, necessary and
courageous stand in unanimously approving legislation that would
ban plastic guns and any other firearms that elude metal detectors
and X-ray machines.
   There are some groups in this nation who are fearful that any
restriction on handguns, even those made of plastic, will somehow
abridge their rights to bear arms.
   Hunters, law-abiding target-shooters and responsible citizens
who arm themselves for their own defense hardly need to argue for
armor-piercing bullets or undetectable pistols.
   We hope that the willingness of congressional leaders to take a
stand ... despite threats of political retaliation at the polls,
will lead to a candid and courageous review of a whole series of
gun-control regulations.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 26
   Chillicothe (Ohio) Gazette on President Reagan's veto of the
trade bill:
   President Reagan's veto of a major trade bill ... came as no
surprise. He has been critical ... of a provision that would
require companies to give employees 60 days' notice of plant
closings and large-scale layoffs.
   And also not surprising is the alternative provision floated as
a trial balloon by his aides: The President would sign a bill that
had a voluntary plant closing provision.
   Wait. Let's get this straight.
   Corporations, which in the past have thrown workers on the
street with but a few hours of notice, endangering their lives,
their benefits and their futures, should change their ways because
Congress asks them to?
   Executives armed with golden parachutes have yet to pick up on
the basic immorality of sudden plant closings and the turmoil they
create. Will they do more than laugh at the toothless provision the
president proposes for trade legislation?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 31
   The Buffalo (N.Y.) News on legalization of drugs:
   A recent poll listed drug addiction as the nation's most
important problem, and hardly a day goes by without news of
drug-related crime or the corrosive effects of drug abuse on our
society.
   Thus it comes as a shock to hear people actually proposing to
legalize heroin, cocaine and marijuana.
   The mayors of Washington, Baltimore and Minneapolis and several
congressmen declare that the war on drugs has failed and the United
States should consider legalizing drugs and treating addiction as a
health, not a crime, problem.
   Then addicts would not have to steal to get drugs, they argue,
and the drug traffic, with all its corrupting influences, would
fade away.
   There is a certain superficial appeal to this argument, which
cites the example of Prohibition and the crime connected with it.
But it is a desperate ``solution'' that only underlines how
desperate the drug problem is. ...
   The move to legalize drugs is a well-meaning but misdirected
effort.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 31
   The Register of Orange County, Calif., on the economy:
   Seven months ago economic doomsayers said the Oct. 19 stock
market crash would plunge the nation into a recession, possibly a
depression. It didn't happen.
   Last week the government revised upward its figures for economic
growth for the first quarter of this year, to 3.9 percent.
   So now guess what the doomsayers are chirping? That the economy
is growing too fast, and that the growth will spark a new round of
inflation and interest hikes. ...
   Contrary to the doomsayers' predictions, we continue to enjoy
strong economic growth with low inflation because we continue to
make it easier for companies to produce goods. ...
   Unfortunately, we'll be lucky just to maintain the status quo.
   Protectionism (which induces distortions that actually hurt our
companies in the end) is in the air, next year will probably being
higher taxes no matter who is elected president ... and the Federal
Reserve, itself spooked by the doomsayers' inflation scare, has
begun tightening the money supply.
   This in turn, may dampen growth, and could even give us a
recession.
   When will Americans realize that government is the cause of our
economic problems, not their solution?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   Green Bay (Wis.) Press-Gazette on a cheese museum in New York:
   They have opened the Museum of Cheese in Rome, N.Y.
   That's right, New York _ not Wisconsin _ has an official,
$425,000 museum where visitors can see how cheese is made, sample
it and learn about its history and economic impact.
   Some in New York state _ big city types, mainly _ made fun of
the museum.
   ``But God likes cheese. He made it rain and that gives the cows
more to eat and that means more milk and that means more cheese. As
long as God is on our side, we're satisfied,'' said Carl Eilenberg,
Rome's mayor.
   Well, we aren't satisfied. After all, God and everyone else
knows that there are two types of cheese _ Wisconsin cheese, which
is the real stuff, and other cheese, which isn't.
   How did this happen? Where was the governor? The Legislature?
Why did no one notice that our heritage was being stolen?
   A cheese museum outside of Wisconsin? The shame of it!
</TEXT>
