<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0472 06-01 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Jackson Rates VP Consideration; Bush Firm on Tax
Pledge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis, Bush comments in top 10 grafs, picking
up in 2nd graf pvs, Jackson with; deletes last 6 grafs pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis said today that ``of
course'' rival candidate Jesse Jackson deserves consideration for
the No. 2 spot but added that he's not ready to make a choice with
the last batch of primaries coming up next Tuesday.
   Republican George Bush, meanwhile, looked on outside his Maine
summer home as a GOP member of a bipartisan deficit-reduction
commission said the panel would not be swayed from doing its job by
Bush's declaration that he would oppose any tax increase.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn., said he thought such comments, which
Bush reiterated one day earlier, were premature.
   Bush retorted: ``I hope the commission will listen a little bit
to the American people in this election. I think that's what an
election is all about. The commission can take an objective look at
(taxes) and do whatever it wants. But I'd be more persuaded by what
Americans say.''
   Frenzel was among a group of economists and others meeting with
Bush Tuesday and today.
   Dukakis, in Boston, called for expanded college opportunities
for Americans and proposed a new national student loan program that
would rely on payroll deductions for repayment.
   After the speech, Dukakis said that ``of course'' Jackson
deserved consideration for the vice presidency, but he answered
with a blunt ``No'' when asked if Jackson deserved special
consideration because of his success during this year's primary
elections.
   ``He's somebody who's done a remarkable job, has great gifts and
great strengths,'' Dukakis said when asked if Jackson was qualified
for a spot on the ticket. ``I respect and admire him a lot.''
   Dukakis said he had not given any thought to picking a running
mate and would not do so until after the final primaries June 7.
   The biggest of those primaries will be in California, and both
Dukakis and Jackson were flying to that state late today for
final-weekend campaigning.
   Jackson, with virtually no chance of overtaking Dukakis in the
national delegate race, is focusing increasingly on the Democratic
National Convention in July and the clout he expects to wield there.
   ``I do not foresee confrontation,'' Jackson said Tuesday as he
campaigned in New Jersey. But he added that his supporters may take
their issues to the full convention if they feel slighted by party
platform writers.
   ``There's room to take one's case to the floor,'' Jackson said.
   He also said he has ``earned consideration'' for the No. 2 spot
on the ticket, although he won't say whether he's interested in it.
   Dukakis has been discouraging discussion of possible running
mates. ``I can tell you I have not spent two minutes of my time on
the subject,'' he told reporters after a Baltimore fund-raiser
Tuesday night.
   As for any claims Jackson might have, the front-runner said:
``He himself said he thought it was the nominee's responsibility to
pick a running mate, and I agree with that.''
   Jackson is continuing to fire up crowds, even as he tacitly
concedes that his presidential bid is all but finished.
   ``When our hope is alive, we push back mountains and remove
ceilings,'' he told a crowd at a shopping center in Willingboro,
N.J. on Tuesday night. ``On our way to the White House, there are
no more impossible dreams.''
   Jackson was campaigning in New Jersey this morning, then leaving
for California.
   Dukakis, for his part, was mapping out his post-primary
strategy. His aides are indicating he'll plunge directly into his
fall campaign after the final round of primaries on Tuesday in
California, New Jersey, Montana and New Mexico.
   Those contests are expected to give the Massachusetts governor a
mathematical lock on the nomination. Rather than taking a
traditional pre-convention break, however, the Dukakis ampaign will
hit the road again.
   ``We want to spend a good part of June out there in America,
traveling, telling people who Mike Dukakis is and why he would be a
good president,'' said Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   The Massachusetts governor was spending most of today on state
business, then flying to California tonight for two days of
campaigning.
   Bush was still at his summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine, where
he has been holding strategy sessions since last week. On Tuesday
he met with economists, including Martin Feldstein, the former
chairman of the president's Council of Economic Advisers.
   Bush said after the meeting that he would reject any call for a
federal tax hike, even if one is called for by a blue-ribbon
bipartisan commission now working on ways to bring down the
enormous federal deficit.
   ``I'll be saying, wait a minute, I've taken my case to the
American people to hold the line on taxes,'' the vice president
said. However, he said that in order to carry out his education
policies, local school taxes might have to be raised.
</TEXT>
