<1ST_LINE>r p PM-HandsomeCandidate     06-01 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Handsome Candidate,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Claim Candidate Using Good Looks To Win Votes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A candidate for Sonoma County
supervisor whose handsome, square-jawed face appears smiling on
campaign posters has angered some women who claim he is using his
looks to win election.
   Tim Smith, 37, was the object of a demonstration Tuesday by
placard-carrying women protesting the ``glitzification'' of county
politics.
   ``He'd look better standing next to Vanna White than he does
running for office,'' said Bebek McGee, leader of the demonstration
downtown.
   She claims Smith spends too much money and time wooing female
voters between 18 and 35 with his glossy, lavishly illustrated
brochures showing the blond, blue-eyed candidate.
   ``You don't vote for someone because you think he's a hunk,''
McGee said.
   Smith, who was an aide to U.S. Rep. Doug Bosco, said he is
amused by the criticism. ``Whose picture was I supposed to put on
my signs?'' he asked.
   Neither of Smith's rivals in the non-partisan race is pictured
on campaign posters in the county, where issues such as sewage
treatment plans and building permits typically stir political
passions.
   The most recent polls show Smith running a close third in his
district behind Eric Anderson and Jack Healy, candidates shorter on
looks and money.
   Men tend to back Healy, 62, a Santa Rosa councilman more
development-oriented than his two rivals, according to the polls.
</TEXT>
