<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--ArianeLaunch     06-01 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ariane Launch,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstration Launch of Ariane 4 Set for June 10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ariane 4 rocket, expected to become Europe's
workhorse for commercial launches, will be launched for the first
time on June 10, authorities announced Wednesday.
   The trial launch without payload is intended to demonstrate the
rocket's readiness for operational flights starting in late 1988,
said a joint statement by the European Space Agency and
Arianespace, the agency's commercial arm.
   The rocket will be launched from the agency's base in Kourou,
French Guiana.
   Ariane 4 is the most powerful of the Ariane series of European
launchers. Technicians can vary the number of solid or liquid fuel
booster rockets and adapt the upper portion of the launcher
according to the payload.
   Arianespace plans to build and launch 70 Ariane 4s.
</TEXT>
