<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Shrine     06-01 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Shrine,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Deification of Slain Soldier Was Constitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's armed forces did not violate the
Constitution when a slain soldier was made a Shinto god against the
wishes of his Christian widow, the Supreme Court ruled Wednesday.
   Yasuko Nakaya lost a 15-year battle when the nation's highest
court reversed lower court decisions upholding her complaint. She
said the Self Defense Forces had violated her constitutional
freedom of religion by deifying her husband at a Shinto shrine.
   Her husband, 1st Lt. Takafumi Nakaya, was killed in a traffic
accident while serving in the Ground Self Defense Forces in January
1968. Mrs. Nakaya, then 34 and a member of the United Church of
Christ in Japan, laid her husband's ashes to rest at Shinai Church
in Yamaguchi. He was not a Christian.
   Four years after his death, Nakaya was enshrined and deified.
His widow filed her suit the next year, in 1973.
   In her legal action, the first individual lawsuit contesting the
government on an issue involving religion, Mrs. Nakaya also sought
$8,000 in compensation from the government for her mental anguish.
   ``I have long suspected that the Supreme Court was an
institution obsequious to the powerful. Today, I'm sorry to see
that the court is,'' Mrs. Nakaya told reporters after the decision.
   Takako Doi, leader of the major opposition Japan Socialist
Party, told the same news conference: ``I would call the ruling a
compromise by the guardian of the constitution made in favor of the
government's way of thinking.
   ``I feel like we're being driven back to the past,'' Mrs. Doi
said.
   Mrs. Nakaya has said she filed the suit to challenge the
possible revival of the militarism that revolved around Japan's
traditional Shintoism before and during World War II.
   Before 1945, soldiers killed in action or while on duty were
automatically given the status of gods and their names were
inscribed in Shinto shrines.
   The practice was discontinued under the new constitution, which
guarantees freedom of religion and was written under U.S. guidance
after Japan's defeat. But soldiers killed on duty are sometimes
enshrined at the request of the association of retired Self Defense
Forces members, called ``taiyukai.''
   In its 14-1 vote Wednesday, the Supreme Court said the armed
forces were not directly involved in the case of Lt. Nakaya and
that the ``taiyukai'' had him enshrined. The lower courts had ruled
that the armed forces had a direct role in the enshrinement.
   Shintoism is said to have emerged at the dawn of Japanese
history and crystalized as a religious system during the Nara
period in the eighth century.
   As the state religion before 1945, it stressed the divinity of
the emperor and the worship of nature, ancestors and ancient
heroes. The military used Shinto shrines and ceremonies to promote
nationalism among the Japanese.
   The Rev. Mototsugu Ogata, chief guardian of the Gokoku Shrine in
Yamaguchi, said in a telephone interview, ``Lt. Nakaya is one of a
total of 52,099 enshrined in a big, tall sacred mirror at this
shrine ... established in 1941. They are mostly those killed in
World War II.''
   Like the others, Nakaya's name has been written in a sacred list
as ``mikoto Takafumi Nakaya,'' said the Shinto priest. ``Mikoto''
is the Shinto term for god or deity.
   The religion respects several types of deities, including
ancestral gods, gods revered for virtues, gods revered for their
works and gods whose wrath is to be feared.
   Shintoism, a religion of ceremony rather than dogma, coexists in
Japan with Buddhism, the other major religion. The exact number of
adherents is not known, and many Japanese practice both religions.
There are also about 1 million Christians among the 122 million
Japanese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Rebels     06-01 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe-Rebels,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Rapists and Killers Among Rebels Seeking Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rapists, killers and robbers were among
113 rebels who surrendered under an amnesty that guarantees
immunity from prosecution, police said Wednesday.
   Officials said the amnesty was a success and they believe
virtually all the rebels turned themselves in by the deadline at
midnight Tuesday.
   ``I cannot think of any dissidents still remaining in the
bush,'' Wednesday's Harare Herald newspaper quoted Home Minister
Moven Mahachi as saying.
   Mahachi said intelligence estimates were that 100 to 120 rebels
were at large before President Robert Mugabe announced the amnesty
April 19.
   Among those granted amnesty is Morgan Sango, who was Zimbabwe's
most wanted man and called himself Gayigusu _ ``Grind the Bush'' in
the Ndebele language.
   Sango, in his 30s, fought as a guerrilla in the seven-year war
that transformed the white-governed British colony of Rhodesia into
black-governed Zimbabwe on April 18, 1980.
   He deserted from the army in 1982 after Joshua Nkomo, the former
opposition leader, was fired from a coalition government for
allegedly plotting a coup against Mugabe.
   Most of the rebels were loyal to Nkomo's Zimbabwe African
People's Union (Patriotic Front), whose power base is the minority
Ndebele tribe. Mugabe's ruling Zimbabwe African National Union
(Patriotic Front) is strongest in his dominant Shona tribe.
   As a dissident gang leader roaming the rolling bush country of
Matabeleland province in western Zimbabwe, the Ndebele homeland,
Sango was blamed for a wave of murder, robbery and rape.
   He is alleged to have led the gang that axed 16 white
missionaries and family members to death six months ago, including
five children and five women, on two Pentecostal communal farms
near Bulawayo, the Matabeleland provincial capital.
   Like the others who surrendered under the amnesty, Sango is
immune from prosecution that almost certainly would have cost him
his life. The government has promised a rehabilitation program to
ease them bak into society.
   Mugabe offered the amnesty, the first since independence, after
he and Nkomo signed an agreement Dec. 23 to merge their political
parties.
   An amnesty Britain offered under a cease-fire before
independence was accepted by about 50,000 guerrillas loyal to
either Nkomo and Mugabe, some of whom were among the 113 who turned
themselves in this time.
   ``Smelling Blood'' Mavovonka led the last gang of 12 men to
surrender hours before the deadline. He told reporters in the Nkayi
district of northern Matabeleland:
   ``We went out to the bush because of misunderstandings. Our
leaders have now seen that what they were doing was wrong and they
have corrected their mistakes. That's why we are here.''
   Mahachi, the home minister, said last week the amnesty would not
be extended and rebels refusing it would be hunted down and killed.
   ``I am sure the amnesty is 100 percent successful,'' he said
Tuesday. ``There may be one or two or three still outstanding. The
problem is that we were not certain of the total number, but the
number which we have received is about what we expected it to be.''
</TEXT>
