<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     06-01 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes In Lebanon On Anniversary of Karami's
Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded in Moslem west Beirut
on Wednesday on the first anniversary of Prime Minister Rashid
Karami's assassination. Police said there were no casualties.
   The car bombing, the first in west Beirut this year, was
reported at 8:20 a.m. in the Bir Hassan district during a strike to
mark Karami's assassination. A police spokesman said the stolen
white Mercedes-Benz was loaded with 44 pounds of TNT.
   ``The explosion shattered glass in the area but no casualties
were reported, apparently because the streets were empty because of
the strike,'' said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity according to regulations.
   Banks, schools, shops, government offices, gas stations and
other businesses closed in west Beirut and other Moslem cities in
accordance with the strike call.
   Karami, a Syrian-backed Sunni Moslem politician, was 65 when he
was killed June 1, 1987 by a bomb explosion aboard a Lebanese army
helicopter that was flying him from north Lebanon to Beirut.
   Pro-Syrian Moslem leaders have accused Israel and the Lebanese
Forces alliance of rightist Christian militias of assassinating
Karami.
   The Jewish state and the command of the Christian militia denied
involvement. An official investigation has issued no finding.
   The explosion on Wednesday was the third car bombing in Lebanon
this year. On April 23, Karami's hometown of Tripoli was rocked by
a powerful car bomb explosion that killed 69 people and wounded 111.
   A blue Volvo car rigged with 220 pounds of TNT exploded in
Christian east Beirut on Monday, killing 20 people and wounding 78.
   The Lebanese Forces blamed Syria for Monday's attack, which came
four days after 2,400 Syrian troops deployed in Beirut's southern
slums to end three weeks of fighting between rival Shiite Moslem
militias that killed nearly 300 people and wounded 1,000.
   The Christians are at loggerheads with Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon. Syria controls west Beirut, most of the city's
southern suburbs and the nation's eastern and northern provinces.
   The police spokesman said Syrian officers supervised overnight a
swap of prisoners between the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of
God, and the pro-Syrian Amal, Arabic of hope.
   He said Hezbollah released 120 members of Amal captured during
the 21 days of clashes in south Beirut and Amal freed 31
Hezbollahis.
</TEXT>
