<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Jews     06-01 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Jews,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Emigration From Soviet Reaches Seven-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached a
new seven-year high in May with 1,145 Jews allowed to leave, the
agency helping them resettle said Wednesday.
   May marked the fourth straight month of rising Jewish
emigration, bringing the total for 1988 to 4,547 Soviet Jews
arriving at the Vienna, Austria, transit center, according to the
Intergovernmental Committee for Migration.
   But the number going to Israel has declined, with only 97 of the
May arrivals resettling there, committee spokeswoman Regina
Boucault said. In April, 1,077 Soviet Jews emigrated and 162 went
to Israel.
   The May figure was the highest since April 1981, when 1,155 Jews
left the Soviet Union.
   More than 250,000 Jews have found new homes since the
Intergovernmental Committee for Migration resettlement program
began in 1971. In the early years, most proceeded to Israel but
recently the number has declined sharply.
   The committee did not include figures for the number of Soviet
Jews coming through Bucharest, Rumania. Shmuel Binsky of the Public
Council on Soviet Jewry in Jerusalem said 24 Jews emigrated through
Bucharest in May.
   In Jerusalem, a Soviet Jewish activist told the news agency Itim
that the number of Soviet Jewish emigrants who decided against
coming to Israel reached a record high in May, when more than 90
percent chose to settle elsewhere.
   Chaim Chessler, head of the Public Council for Soviet Jewry, was
quoted as saying on Tuesday that soon no Soviet Jewish emigrants
will come to Israel unless they are flown via Bucharest instead of
Vienna, where they are free to immigrate to other Western countries.
   Israeli officials are embarrassed by the high dropout figure
because of their 20-year-long battle for the right of Soviet Jews
to emigrate on the grounds that Israel is their homeland.
   Israeli leaders claim 400,000 Soviet Jews want to settle in
Israel. But less than 20 percent of those who leave the Soviet
Union actually settle there.
   Chessler said that of the 1,169 Jews who left the Soviet Union
for Vienna and Bucharest in May, just 110 came to Israel, a drop of
nearly 7 percent from April.
</TEXT>
