<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-GorbachevText 2ndAdd   06-01 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorbachev Text, 2nd Add,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: a whole. ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Before concluding my statement, let me just share with you one
general impression _ and if I did not mention this, I would not be
honest with you or truthful, if I omitted to say this: It is my
impression ... there is a lot of contradictions in the American
position. ... Now, let me explain where I see this contrariness. On
the one hand, we have a joint statement that there should be no
war, that war is inadmissible, we are engaged in a businesslike
dialogue about arms reductions, we're talking about preferences for
political solutions. And yet, on the other hand, we keep hearing
... _ we heard words about a stake made on strength. ...
   This is to be seen in the economic ties also, where an
authoritative part _ sections of the American business circles are
in favor of cooperation, but they are faced with intimidation with
all sorts of restrictions. There is indeed a most unfavored nation
treatment in respect to the Soviet Union. We had a very intense
discussion with the president yesterday on this subject. And I
asked, ``Why should the dead hold onto the coattails of the
living?'' I mean the Jackson-Vanik Amendment. One of them's already
physically dead. The other's politically dead. ``Why should they
hang onto our coattails?'' I asked. This was _ the amendment was
passed in a totally different situation a decade ago, but in this
changed world of ours, we should think and base our policies on
present day realities. ...
   Q. You mentioned twice in your comments just a few moments ago,
you talked about missing chances, and you have also talked about
politics is the art of the possible. So I ask you with this
administration and its president, is it going to be possible to
have a treaty, to have a START (strategic arms reduction) treaty,
if the Americans insist on keeping the SDI (strategic defense
initiative) program going?
   GORBACHEV: I am sure that there still is a possibility to
achieve a treaty this year and I'm reinforced in this optimism by
the headway we have made _ Moscow and Washington have made in this
past period _ and also the exchange of views here almost around the
clock. It gives me grounds to voice such an optimistic assessment.
...
   Q. Mr. General Secretary, several times in the past few days you
were asked if there would be a fifth summit conference with
President Reagan possible in the fall, and you answered usually,
``Yes, it is possible, it is possible, but it depends on how things
go at this meeting.'' Now that this meeting is about over, do you
see enough headway _ progress _ to warrant a fifth meeting with
President Reagan in the fall?
   GORBACHEV: I link the possibility to arrive at a treaty, and
therefore, I believe, that a fifth meeting is also possible, and
that possibility is still at the very real. So, the whole thing
hinges upon that one question. ...
   Q. The Arab countries highly assess your recent words about the
Palestinians who are now waging a courageous struggle against the
Israeli occupiers. Would you tell me what you achieved in your
meetings with Mr. Reagan on the Palestine issue and on the Middle
East settlement as a whole?
   GORBACHEV: ... There is an understanding among the international
community and in the Security Council among its permanent members
that the solution should be solved along the lines of an
international conference. The content of that conference has not
yet been determined though. ...
   We cannot decide for the Arabs, how the Palestinians participate
in the international conference. Let them decide for themselves,
let the Arabs decide. What we should do, the Americans and the
Soviet Union, we should respect their decision. It's a vast Arab
world out there, and we must recognize Israel's right to security.
We must recognize the right of the Palestinian people to
self-determination. In what form? Let the Palestinians, with their
friends the Arabs, decide on that. ...
   Q. There's been a wide perception that differences over the
American SDI program have been one of the major obstacles to a
START Treaty. Have you made any progress in resolving differences
over SDI at this summit? If so, exactly what progress has been
made? And do you still continue to believe that that may be a major
obstacle in reaching a START Treaty?
   GORBACHEV: In responding to your last question I say yes, I do,
because it means destabilization and it doesn't meet normal logic
to reduce strategic offensive arms on land and to build a bridge
for such arms into outer space. Although the Americans say that
this is a purely defensive weapon, we do not think that is. ...
   Allegedly the U.S. side is ready to share its secrets with us.
And I said to the president at that time, I said, ``Permit me, Mr.
President, not to agree with you and to call in question that
statement of yours. Why? Because right now we can't even agree on
how to verify sea-based cruise missiles on two types of vessels
because you're not ready to agree. So how can we rely on your
divulging all of your secrets concerning SDI? That's just not
serious, it's beyond the framework of reality.'' ...
</TEXT>
