<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Reagan Bjt   06-01 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Reagan, Bjt,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Royalty, Bomb Squads and Swordbearers Ready for Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While police searched London's sewers for bombs
and set up barricades Wednesday, the Lord Mayor's harried staff
spruced up the 12th century Guildhall where President Reagan will
speak en route home from the Moscow summit.
   Clearly unaccustomed to the tumult surrounding U.S. presidential
visits, the mayor's spokeswoman, Carole Barbone, glanced at the
city's motto inscribed on the Guildhall _ ``Domine Dirige Nos.''
   ``It means `God Direct Us,' or the alternative version, `God
Help Us,''' she chuckled as workers strung up American flags,
lugged in potten chrysanthemums and polished the Lord Mayor's
silverware.
   Reagan arrives Thursday, the final leg of a 10-day trip that
also took him to Helsinki, Finland and Moscow.
   The president wrapped up his summit with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev on Wednesday, as both leaders stressed improved
relations between the superpowers and pledged to press forward with
their quest for a treaty their arsenals of strategic nuclear
weapons by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   During his two-day London stopover, Reagan will have afternoon
tea with Queen Elizabeth II at Buckingham Palace, hold talks with
Prime Ministers Margaret Thatcher of Britain and Noboru Takeshita
of Japan and deliver a major speech summing up his meetings with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   American tourists watching the changing of the guard at the
palace were delighted that their president was coming.
   ``We'll probably change our plans just to see him,'' said Craig
Moritz, 24, an economics graduate from Houston, Texas, who is
vacationing with his sister, Kirsten. ``It makes you feel good that
he is somewhere you are.''
   Sheila Cronin, 57, of Hopatcong, New Jersey, also planned a
second visit Thursday ``just to see what Reagan is like up front.''
   At the Guildhall on Friday, Reagan will pass along a corridor
lined with Lord Mayor Sir Greville Spratt's personal bodyguard of
pikemen and musketeers, and will be preceded by ceremonial
sword-and mace-bearers into the Great Hall to deliver his speech on
East-West relations to the Royal Institute of International Affairs.
   Six truckloads of flowers and plants have been ordered to spruce
up the austere wood-paneled rooms, including red, white and blue
carnations woven into the shapes of the Union Jack, the Stars and
Stripes and the flag of the City of London.
   The Nicaraguan Solidarity Campaign said playwright Harold Pinter
and actress Julie Christie would be among 10 celebrities near the
Guildhall during Reagan's speech, attending a silent protest
against U.S. policy in Central America.
   The Reagans will stay at Winfield House, the 35-room residence
of Ambassador Charles Price in Regent's Park.
   Part of Regent's Park and the road around it will be sealed off,
with marksmen positioned on surrounding roofs. Sewers have been
checked and even the cable access doors on lamppost bases have been
sealed with metal strips.
   The Mall, a wide boulevard leading through St. James's Park to
Buckingham Palace, was lined Wednesday with metal barricades, and
mounted police directed traffic.
</TEXT>
