<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-IraqWar     06-01 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq War,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Feint Led to Major Victory on Faw Peninsula, U.S. Observers
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi army ``set up'' Iran in April for
one of its worst military defeats with an elaborate, month-long
deception campaign of troop movements that demonstrated the growing
maturity of Iraq's forces, senior Pentagon officials say.
   Having rapidly recaptured the Faw peninsula six weeks ago in an
operation that succeeded beyond all expectation, the Iraqis since
have reclaimed another piece of their occupied territory near the
southern city of Basra with a similar surprise attack, the
officials noted.
   The victories mean it now is conceivable that Iraq can break the
stalemate in the 7{-year war with Iran, the sources continued.
   While there is no evidence that Iraq will try to invade Iran, it
appears Iraq now has the ability to ``systematically evict''
Iranian troops from its territory, the officials said.
   Such victories, when coupled with the political and economic
problems confronting Iran, may be enough to force a truce
settlement.
   The sources _ ranking defense officials with access to U.S.
intelligence data _ agreed to discuss developments in the Iran-Iraq
war during interviews conducted over the past week. The officials,
who spoke only upon condition they not be named, suggested the
administration had new reason to hope the Iran-Iraq war might wind
down _ allowing the United States to reduce its own commitment of
naval forces to the Persian Gulf.
   The sources agreed that Iraq had surprised not only Iran but
also U.S. intelligence agencies with the timing of its land
offensives. They further disclosed:
   _Iraq spent the month before the April 17 attack on the Faw
peninsula moving troops all around the country, generally toward
the north. When they were ready, the Iraqis used their superior
roads and military logistical system to send 50,000 to 60,000
troops streaming back south to Faw in one coordinated movement.
   ``They set up the Iranians masterfully,'' one official said.
``The Iranians never saw it coming.''
   ``They achieved surprise,'' a second official added. ``In the
course of this plan, they moved units around in ways that Iranian
intelligence were likely to be deceived, then reassembled these
units in a stealthy and rather sudden way. ...
   ``And they just ran over the Iranians like a steamroller running
over a cockroach. It was really something. They had expected it
(the operation) to take five days and it took them a day and a
half.''
   This source noted the Iraqi military had received ``an awfully
lot of bad press'' in the past, ``but our conclusion has been that
they've gotten steadily better. We have observed with interest the
maturation of the Iraqi armed forces as an entity.''
   _In the course of retaking the Faw peninsula, ``the Iraqis
digested real quickly the fact the Iranians really didn't fight
very well,'' one official said.
   Thus emboldened, the Iraqis set up another assault operation and
punched through Iranian lines near Basra on May 25, once again
routing Iranian forces.
   ``This was another steamroller,'' an official said. ``It took
the Iranians a couple of months to capture (this area), with 60,000
to 65,000 dead. The Iraqi army and air force recaptured it in five
hours.''
   _The Iraqis recently provided yet another example of their
willingness to become more aggressive, mounting a major air strike
against Iran's Larak Island oil terminal.
   Iraqi jet fighters have struck the terminal before. What made
the May 14 attack different, the sources said, was the willingness
of the Iraqi pilots to slow down, fly low and use heavy iron bombs
instead of guided missiles.
   The bombs pack much more explosive power than missiles like the
Exocet and the result was that Iraq ``just drilled'' several huge
oil tankers, putting them out of commission.
   _Iran appears to be suffering real recruitment problems in
convincing its youth to join the Revolutionary Guard for duty at
the front lines. The Iranians have been ``equipment-poor'' for some
time; ``now they're becoming a people-poor armed force,'' one
official said.
   _Iran is going out of its way to monitor the location of U.S.
warships and refraining from attacks on merchant vessels if Navy
ships are close enough to intervene, the sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
