<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Church     06-01 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Church,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church of England To Drop Controversial Anonymous Essay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of England said Wednesday it will drop
the traditional anonymous preface from its next directory because a
theologian committed suicide after using the last one to criticize
the archbishop of Canterbury.
   A joint statement by the Church Commissioners and the Central
Board of Finance, which oversee church investments and assets, said
the commentary was ``no longer a viable option.''
   Asked to elaborate, a spokesman cited ``a lot of publicity and
the search by the media for the author and the tragic death of
Gareth Bennett.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The preface will be dropped from the 1989-90 edition of
Crockford's Clerical Directory, the official biennial list of
Anglican clergy, but no decision has been made on whether to
eliminate it permanently, the statement said.
   ``It has only been dropped for the 1989 edition to allow us more
time to consider,'' the spokesman said. ``We shall consider the
position again later.''
   Bennett, a 68-year-old Oxford University canon, was found dead
Dec. 7, five days after the 1987-88 edition of the directory
appeared with his preface.
   It accused Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie of being
indecisive and overly influenced by liberal pressure groups, and of
surrounding himself with liberal bishops. Runcie is spiritual
leader of the church and leads the world's 70 million Anglicans,
including 3 million American Episcopalians.
   The preface attacked moves within the state church toward
ordaining women as priests, an issue it said was spreading disunity
through the Anglican communion.
   Although the article was not signed, suspicion fell on Bennett
because of his stature in the church's conservative wing, his
influential position and his academic distinction.
   Runcie, 66, often has criticized Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's conservative policies, and the preface was widely
interpreted as the beginning of a campaign to bring about his
retirement and prevent a liberal from succeeding. Bishops and
archbishops customarily retire on their 70th birthday.
   Bennett denied to colleagues and reporters that he wrote the
preface, but was found dead in the garage of his home with a hose
leading into his car from the exhaust pipe. Church officials later
confirmed he was the author.
   He did not leave a suicide note, but wrote in a diary four days
before his death: ``I should be lucky to weather this business
through without disaster.''
   A strong clue to authorship was the preface's informed criticism
of divisions among Episcopalians in the United States following
ordination of women priests there. Bennett had been a visiting
professor at the University of South Carolina since 1975.
   The Church Commissioners and Central Board of Finance said they
considered publishing a signed commentary in the next directory,
but decided against it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
