<1ST_LINE>r i BC-GorbachevText 3rdAdd   06-01 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorbachev Text, 3rd Add,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: of reality.'' ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. While 5,000 journalists have been here for the summit,
suddenly Soviet domestic politics have become rather unusual.
(Ousted Moscow Communist Party leader) Mr. Boris Yeltsin, in an
interview on television, calls for the resignation of (the
Kremlin's No. 2 man) Mr. (Yegor) Ligachev. ... How do you assess
the current political situation in the Soviet Union as we move into
the party conference period? And what is your opinion of Mr.
Yeltsin's call for Mr. Ligachev's resignation?
   GORBACHEV: ... (Comrade Yeltsin) is a member of the Central
Committee of the CPSU, after all. So what he says and what he talks
about was in fact a subject for discussion at the October plenary
meeting last year. Twenty-seven people spoke out at that meeting,
and just as you are asking me questions, he suddenly came up and
his statement, the statement he made at that meeting, was _ had not
been planned. ... The opinion of all of the 27 speakers was that
the generalizations made by Comrade Yeltsin concerning various
aspects of activity of the Central Committee, the activity of the
Secretariat, the Politburo, that opinion was wrong. And his
statement was recognized as being politically erroneous. So the
discussion was there, the decision was taken, and so Comrade
Yeltsin seems to be in disagreement with the decision taken by the
Central Committee of the Party. Well then, if that is so, we must
ask him in the Central Committee, and we shall demand that he
explain his position and what he's out for. It means that his
opinion is at a variance with the opinion of the Central Committee
of the Party.
   As for Comrade Ligachev and his retirement, that problem simply
is nonexistent, and that's all. That's what you should proceed
from, and that's the way it will be. ...
   Q. Mr. Secretary, when you were in Washington, you said to Mr.
Reagan that the Soviet Union was prepared to stop arms deliveries
to Nicaragua if the United States stopped financing the Contras.
Then later (Soviet Foreign Minister) Mr. (Eduard) Shevardnadze and
(Secretary of State) Mr. (George) Shultz discussed that issue, and
we were told that the Soviet position had changed to an agreement
to stop deliveries to Nicaragua if the United States stopped
deliveries to the whole of Central America. Can you explain to us
the reason for the change in that position, if it's correct, and
what you discussed today on Central America? Did that advance the
issue?
   GORBACHEV: Today we had a detailed discussion of this problem _
very detailed. We looked back at the history, and when we do look
back into history, we have different explanations and views. But I
suggested that we take as a starting point today's reality. The
Contadora process is with us, the Guatemala Accords. There's been
an armistice, a cease-fire. And there is some movement towards a
political settlement, and we must base ourselves on that process
and lend our support and give an opportunity to the forces opposing
each other. ...
</TEXT>
