<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Reagan Bjt   06-01 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Reagan, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Softens Criticism of Human Rights; Surprises Refuseniks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, to the surprise of some
refuseniks, said Wednesday that emigration barriers preventing
people from leaving the Soviet Union may be the result of
bureacratic snags rather than deliberate Kremlin policy.
   In a summit-finale news conference, Reagan also said that it was
General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev who changed his view of the
Kremlin as an ``evil empire.'' He said Gorbachev, his partner at
four summit meetings, was ``different than previous Soviet leaders
have been.''
   The president said he hoped to conclude a U.S.-Soviet treaty to
cut strategic nuclear arsenals by half before leaving office, but
said it was more important to get a good agreement than to meet a
January deadline.
   Winding up his first visit to the Soviet Union, Reagan answered
questions at a news conference under hot television lights in a
ballroom of the Spaso House, the American Embassy residence where
he stayed during his five-day visit here.
   Reagan refused to rule out the possibility of a fifth summit
before leaving office in eight months.
   ``Something else might come up that necessitates our getting
together and settling something other than that particular
treaty,'' Reagan said. He was referring to the Strategic Arms
Reduction Treaty (START), still being negotiated by the United
States and Soviet Union.
   ``So, no one can say, no, there will be no need for a summit,''
the president added.
   Avoiding any direct criticism of Gorbachev, Reagan said the
Soviet leadership believed that his meetings in Moscow with Soviet
dissidents, refuseniks and others constituted interference in
internal matters. The topic had been a centerpiece of his
activities here, but abruptly ended after a speech Tuesday at
Moscow State University.
   At his news conference, Reagan was asked repeatedly about his
comment a day earlier about dissidents and refuseniks, people who
have been denied visas and often lose their jobs or are otherwise
punished for merely seeking permission to leave or speaking out
against the Soviet system.
   ``I'm not blaming you; I'm blaming bureaucracy,'' Reagan had
told a Soviet questioner. ``We have the same type of thing happen
in our country...''
   Asked Wednesday if he thought the problem merely was one of
bureaucratic intransigence instead of a deliberate policy, Reagan
said, ``No, I can't say that _ it's one I don't know that much
about the system.''
   The questioner persisted, asking if he weren't ``letting Mr.
Gorbachev off a little easy on just saying it's a bureaucracy?''
   ``I just have to believe that in any government some of us do
find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy, and then sometimes you have
to stomp your foot and say, unmistakably, I want it done.
   ``And then maybe you get through with it. But I have great
confidence in his ability to do that,'' Reagan said of Gorbachev.
   However, his answer met immediate skepticism.
   Abe Stolar, a Chicago-born Jew who has been trying to get his
family out of the Soviet Union since 1975, said Reagan's answer was
``naive. Maybe that's a bad word to use, may it's just innocent.''
   Stolar said ``I personelly believe that it is Soviet policy.
None of it is accidental and none of it is purely bureaucratic.''
   Tanya Zieman, a Soviet refusenik, asked if she felt the
bureacracy was responsible, said, ``Of course not. The bureaucracy
has nothing to do with it.''
   She speculated that Reagan merely did not want to spoil some
agreement with Gorbachev on human rights.
   ``My impression was that he just didn't want to anger our side
more,'' she said. ``My feeling is as if some agreement is reached
and he does not want to hamper it by saying nasty things.''
   Zieman's family was to have been visited by Reagan until Soviet
authorities passed word that the family would never be allowed to
leave if Reagan paid a call.
   Reagan met with reporters shortly after Gorbachev.
   At the first news conference he had ever held in the Soviet
Union, the Kremlin leader noted with pleasure that Reagan had
retracted his characterization of this country as an ``evil
empire.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
