<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     06-01 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Insurgents Claim Capture of 32 Government Posts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan Moslem guerrillas said they
overran 32 government military posts around the Afghan provincial
capital of Baghlan near a major Soviet troop withdrawal route.
   The report could not be independently verified, and Western
diplomatic sources contacted Wednesday in Islamabad said they could
not confirm it.
   They said it sounded exaggerated, but they agreed it could
indicate there was heavy fighting around the city 120 miles north
of Kabul and 75 miles south of the Soviet Union.
   The Peshawar-based Mujahedeen Alliance said in a telex statement
Tuesday night that 1,500 troops and militiamen fighting for the
communist government surrendered or were captured around Baghlan
between May 22 and May 28.
   It said the insurgents captured nearly 900 automatic rifles and
machine guns and ``millions of rounds of ammunition.''
   The statement said fighting was still going at the time of the
broadcast on Tuesday. It did not say whether the fighting involved
Soviet forces or just Kabul government troops.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas say they already control the area
surrounding the southern part of the road below the mountains, but
they say they are letting the retreating Red Army pass peacefully.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and replaced
the communist government with another one. More than 100,000 troops
have been helping the Marxist government fight Moslem rebels.
   The Soviet Union signed an agreement with the United States,
Pakistan and Afghanistan last month in Geneva to withdraw its
troops, and the pullout began May 15.
</TEXT>
