<HEAD>Salvadoran President Undergoes Tests In United States Military
Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran President Jose Napolean Duarte,
admitted to Walter Reed Army Medical Center for treatment of what
he called a bleeding ulcer ``of a malignant nature,'' began tests
today to determine if his condition could be cancer.
   Duarte, 62, was taken to Walter Reed after arriving Tuesday
night at Andrews Air Force Base near Washington.
   Walter Reed spokesman Pete Esker said today that Duarte ``rested
comfortably last night and began medical evaluation and tests this
morning.
   ``He is in good spirits and his condition is stable,'' Esker
said in a short statement. ``It is not appropriate to comment
further until all his tests are completed.''
   Duarte's illness has been described by those around him as both
an ``ulcer'' and as ``a tumor.'' The Salvadoran president himself
said it was an ulcer of ``a malignant nature.''
   A physician who is an expert on stomach diseases, but who is not
associated with Duarte's care, said that it often is difficult to
determine if an illness is the result of an ulcer or is caused by a
stomach cancer.
   ``It is not at all uncommon for there to be confusion,'' said
Dr. J. Michael Hamilton of the National Cancer Institute. ``When
you look at the two things, they may be very similar.''
   Extensive tests or even surgery may be required to resolve the
question, Hamilton said.
   As he prepared to leave from Illopango military airport in El
Salvador on Tuesday, Duarte told reporters of his illness and
described himself as ``a man who fights.''
   `The designs of God are unpredictable,'' Duarte said. ``What I
have is a bleeding ulcer seven centimeters (2{ inches) long in the
stomach, of a malignant nature.
   ``The doctors have said that the prognosis is reserved until
studies are made in the United States ... I don't know what is
going to happen.''
   Asked how to interpret Duarte's description of his ulcer
presidential spokeswoman Ana Maria Ruiz wiped away tears and said:
``What do you want him to say? Cancer? He can't.'' Ulcers in
themselves are neither malignant nor benign.
   Media Communications Minister Roberto Viera, asked about the
president's statement, said Duarte has ``a large tumor'' in his
stomach. ``The doctors don't want to characterize it until they do
a biopsy,'' Viera said.
   Duarte told reporters: ``You all know me. I have been a man of
crisis, a man of battle, a man who fights. I have fought against
all the vicissitudes, against dictatorships for so many years in
search of democracy; against the country's biggest crisis; against
an earthquake, three droughts. And now God gives me this other
test.''
   He traveled to the United States aboard a U.S. Air Force C-141
transport aircraft converted into a hospital plane for the six-hour
flight to Washington.
   Duarte bid farewell at the airport to about 200 members of the
Cabinet, legislature, supreme court and diplomatic corps, clasping
many of the dignitaries in long embraces. His wife Ines, next to
him on a slightly raised platform, wiped away tears.
   The climate of the ceremony was one of barely concealed grief,
with members of Duarte's extended family weeping and rubbing
reddened eyes.
   The absence leaves Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount in
charge.
   The president, a staunch U.S. ally who is in the final year of
his five-year term, leaves a troubled country. Leftist guerrillas
are waging an 8-year-old campaign to topple the government.
   Duarte's Christian Democrats suffered a telling defeat in
legislative and municipal elections in March. The rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, won control of the
unicameral congress, which had been dominated by Duarte's party.
   The Christian Democrats are torn by infighting that has
threatened to split the organization.
   Former Cabinet Minister Julio Adolfo Rey Prendes was declared
the party presidential candidate at a convention last month. But
rival Fidel Chavez Mena, backed by a significant party sector,
challenges the validity of the nomination.
</TEXT>
