<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Calif-AIDS     06-01 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Calif-AIDS,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Say State Lacks Coordinated Plan; AIDS Measure on June 7
Ballot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fraziear is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS activist Albert Bell marched into
the governor's office and offered a handful of condoms to the
receptionist.
   ``I'd like to give these to the governor. It's the only thing
we've been offered for safety in six years,'' said Bell, a San
Diego resident who was among those calling for more action against
AIDS.
   There is growing frustration in California among the medical
community, victims' advocacy groups and AIDS patients over
government efforts they say are fractured, adrift in a leadership
vacuum and hampered by the governor's conservativism.
   Against that background, supporters of political extremist
Lyndon LaRouche have for the second time placed an AIDS initiative
on the statewide ballot that would allow medical authorities to
quarantine victims of acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Voters will decide the issue, Proposition 69, on June 7. The
first such measure was rejected overwhelmingly two years ago.
   Critics accuse Republican Gov. George Deukmejian of worrying
more about offending conservative voters than saving homosexuals
and intravenous drug users who are hit hardest by AIDS.
   Deukmejian boasts of increasing AIDS spending, up to $65 million
this fiscal year from $3.4 million four years ago and almost 50
percent more than the next four states with high AIDS caseloads
combined. He has included $75 million in AIDS funds in his 1988-89
budget proposal.
   A George Washington University study put California's AIDS
allocation for the 1987-88 fiscal year at $58 million, lower than
the governor's figure but far higher than New York's appropriation
of $16.4 million. Florida was next at $12.5 million, followed by
New Jersey at $7 million, according to the study.
   ``In the coming year, our state will continue its leadership in
the fight against this deadly disease,'' he said recently.
   The 13,106 California cases reported to the Centers for Disease
Control make up 21.5 percent of the national caseload, second in
the nation to New York's 15,729, or 25.8 percent.
   The state Office of AIDS said 58 percent of the California
victims, or 7,744 people, had died by April 30.
   Deukmejian opposes Proposition 69, but critics say he is silent
too often on AIDS issues, allowing state policies to be determined
by politics rather than public health considerations.
   The state has clamped down on graphic AIDS educational material
in the wake of protests by conservative organizations that the
material teaches promiscuity and homosexual sex.
   ``You have to make sure you do not offend people who are, in
essence, paying the bill,'' Thelma Fraziear, chief of the state
Office of AIDS, said.
   Groups professing traditional family values argue that condoms
aren't 100 percent effective and that abstinence should be promoted
as the best means of AIDS prevention.
   The California Medical Association supports the use of explicit
language to reach some audiences. But the state Republican Party
censured the San Francisco AIDS Foundation for educational
literature that Republican leaders considered obscene.
   Fraziear said AIDS, by its nature, is fraught with politics.
``We are dealing with subjects that are not generally discussed in
mixed company. ... You get a lot of built-in fears that you don't
get with other programs,'' she said.
   She characterized the state as balancing opposing interests and
insisted politics haven't interfered with the mission of education,
testing and research.
   But with health care for AIDS victims alone costing an estimated
$1 billion, and with the epidemic expected to strike 35,000 more
Californians by 1991, AIDS experts say the state isn't doing nearly
enough.
   Stan Hadden, an assistant to state Senate leader David Roberti
and a recognized AIDS expert in the Capitol, said the state's low
profile forces county health officers and volunteer groups to take
the lead.
   ``To put it bluntly, I wish we could get rid of the state Office
of AIDS and put the San Francisco County Office of AIDS in
charge,'' Hadden said. ``I think they're much more aggressive.''
</TEXT>
