<HEAD>Trial Opens In Alleged Attempt To Avenge Bedouin Couple's Family
Honor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-9 with five grafs to ADD that intended victims
alleged to include mother-in-law's sister; CORRECT defense attorney
to Don Spadaro sted Barry Roderman, and CORRECT year the couple ran
off to 1986 sted 1980.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bedouin couple invoked the honor
of their desert tribe in demanding the death of an unwanted
son-in-law, a prosecutor said today as the two went on trial of
charges of soliciting murder.
   Suad and Ghada Tarawneh of Toledo, Ohio, are accused of plotting
to kill their daughter's husband and his family and asking that
photos and body parts be sent back as proof their honor had been
restored. No one was hurt.
   Assistant State Attorney William Dimitrouleas today quoted from
secretly taped conversations he said showed the plot was serious.
   ```In Syria, he would be bones in the dirt,'' he quoted Tarawneh
as saying of his son-in-law. ```If he continues to live, he will
destroy my life.'''
   Police said Tarawneh, 46, had hired a detective to kill his
son-in-law, Mouataz Abdulsalam, his younger sister and his mother,
Mrs. Tawaneh's sister.
   The detective was secretly cooperating with authorities. The
alleged plot was broken up and the Tarawnehs, who left Jordan 18
years ago, were arrested in February on charges of conspiracy and
solicitation to commit murder.
   The Tarawnehs' daughter, Raniah, had backed out of an arranged
marriage and run off with her Syrian cousin Abdulsalam in 1986 at
age 17. The two settled in Tamarac. Tradition required the insult
be avenged, authorities said.
   Defense attorney Don Spadaro portrayed Tarawneh as a heavy
drinker and who did not necessarily mean what he said.
   ``This case involves severe family problems,'' said Spadaro.
</TEXT>
