<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Economy Bjt   06-01 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, Bjt,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Indicators Advance Another 0.2 Percent in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday its chief
economic forecasting gauge rose a modest 0.2 percent in April, an
increase analysts said signaled continued healthy economic growth
for the rest of this presidential election year.
   It marked the third consecutive monthly increase in the Commerce
Department's Index of Leading Indicators, following an identical
0.2 percent rise in March and a giant 1.5 percent February surge,
which had been the largest gain in more than two years.
   In other good news for the economy, the government reported that
orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods shot up 1.2 percent
in April to a seasonally adjusted $218.7 billion following an even
bigger 1.6 percent March increase, indicating that industrial
production will be increasing during the months ahead.
   In a third report, the Commerce Department said construction
spending rose 0.1 percent in April to an annual rate of $401.8
billion as a big increase in investment on new factories helped
offset a decline in government construction projects.
   Analysts discounted the drop in the volatile government sector
and focused instead on the strength in factory construction, which
pushed this category up a remarkable 39.1 percent higher than it
was a year ago. They said this reflected a rush by businesses to
expand operating plants to meet the heavy demand for U.S. exports.
   ``All of the reports today spell nothing but good news for the
economy in this election year,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist
for the Boston Co. ``By and large, we have got a strong expansion
in industrial America with the orders suggesting increased
production, more jobs and good income generation.''
   Economists have been busy in recent days boosting their growth
forecasts for 1988, based on the report last week that the overall
economy, as measured by the gross national product, expanded at a
robust 3.9 percent rate in the first three months of the year.
   This was far better performance than had been forecast
immediately after Oct. 19, when the record plunge in stock prices
raised fears of an imminent recession. Instead, growth has raced
ahead, pushing unemployment down to a 14-year low of 5.4 percent in
April.
   ``It has been an amazing year,'' said David Wyss, chief
financial economist at Data Resources Inc. ``The ability of the
economy to ignore the stock market crash has really surprised us.''
   Wyss said his company now was predicting the GNP would grow 3.2
percent this year, which would be the best economic performance
since a 6.8 percent surge in 1984. In each of the last two years,
GNP growth has been a more modest 2.9 percent.
   All of this should be good news for Vice President George Bush,
who hopes his presidential campaign will benefit from a feeling
among voters that the Reagan administration has done a good job
managing the economy.
   The March increase in the leading index originally was reported
as a much stronger 0.8 percent rise. However, weakness in consumer
and business borrowing pulled the index down sharply.
   But analysts said they were not concerned about the big downward
revision, which had been expected. They said if the trend toward
smaller monthly increases in the leading index continues, it might
be signaling slower growth by the end of 1988 or in early 1989, but
any such slowdown probably would not be evident until after the
Nov. 8 election.
   Many economists still believe that while 1988 will be a good
year, the country is likely to enter a recession sometime in 1989,
brought on by rising interest rates and higher inflation.
   The Federal Reserve already has made three moves in the past 2{
months to tighten credit conditions in an effort to dampen
inflationary pressures.
   Lawrence A. Hunter, deputy chief economist for the Chamber of
Commerce, blamed the Fed actions for the slower increases in the
leading index in the past two months and said the situation is
similar to mid-1984 when Fed credit-tightening brought on a period
of sluggish growth before the Fed relented and started easing
credit.
   ``Let us hope the Fed backs off again,'' he said. ``If it does,
the prospects for the U.S. economy remain basically sound.''
   The 0.2 percent April rise in the leading index reflected
increases in five individual indicators and declines in four others.
   The biggest source of strength was rise in the length of the
average workweek, followed by gains in the money supply, a drop in
initial unemployment claims, a rise in raw materials prices and an
increase in plant and equipment orders.
   The biggest negative factor was a speed-up in delivery times for
business orders, which is viewed as indicating weaker demand. Other
negative forces were a decline in stock prices, a drop in building
permits and a drop in orders for consumer goods.
   The various changes left the index at 192.2 percent of its 1967
base of 100.
</TEXT>
