<NOTE>EDS: Retransmitting a0654 to fix category code.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following are excerpts from Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's news conference on Wednesday:
   (The general secretary's remarks through an interpreter.)
   GORBACHEV: We have completed the fourth meeting, fourth in three
years between the general secretary of the CPSU (Communist Party of
the Soviet Union) and the United States president, and this alone
is not simply a matter of arithmetic. I would say that this is of
great political import to have four meetings in just three years.
It signifies the intensity of the political dialogue, and it shows
the character, the level of our relations, and I guess this in
itself is meaningful. ...
   The meeting did indeed show how important is the dialogue
between the Soviet Union and the United States, and it has
confirmed yet again how right we were in choosing the path we took
in Geneva two and a half years ago. To Reykjavik and Washington,
that path has led us to Moscow. ...
   Everybody is interested in Soviet-American relations being
switched on to a normal and healthy track. ...
   And so, I ask, why has this become possible, this intense
dialogue, this process, which is of immense importance? I think it
is due to realism. I'm speaking about realism in politics, in the
policies of the Soviet Union and of the United States of America
because it is a realistic approach, on the one side, that has
ensured the possibility of this process. ...
   The relations, which bore within them a terrible threat to the
very existence of mankind and to peace, became more positive and
acquired positive dynamism. The two most powerful nations began to
reform their relationship in their own interest and in the interest
of the world community at large. ...
   The major result is a continuation of dialogue, which now
encompasses all of the key issues of world politics, of bilateral
relations. This meeting, once again, demonstrated the fact that we
are indulging in a realistic dialogue. ...
   Also characteristic, and this you will find in the final
document ... the concept that in this dialogue of ours ... we are
laying down prerequisites, the bricks, so to say, for the building
of our future relationship. It is a sign of movement into the 21st
century.
   Now, what have we achieved specifically? I would mention the
fact that we have completed the process concerning medium- and
shorter-range missiles, and this fourth meeting gave an added
impetus to the process and we exchanged instruments of
ratification. This is not simply a formality, and let me just use a
solemn formula ... that completion of the procedures and
introduction into force of the INF (Intermediate-Range Nuclear
Forces) treaty has turned the Moscow meeting into a watershed
political event in the Soviet-American dialogue and in world
politics as a whole.
   It is not only the peoples of the Soviet Union and the United
States that can congratulate themselves, but also their allies and
the entire world public, the entire world community. It is a common
victory for reason and realism. And it has become possible because
today, on all continents, in every nation, in every country,
regardless of social choice and of other values, which each people
chooses for itself, there is a common understanding and awareness
that the world had reached the brink and that it had to be stopped,
that event had to be stopped and the door had to be opened leading
in another direction towards a nuclear free and non-violent world
and towards making international relations more healthy.
   Many made their real and substantial contribution to achieving
this major victory. And I must note these facts and also mention
the contribution of the press, even when the press posed the most
difficult questions before the negotiations, that, too, was a
necessary contribution that helped to make the dialogue more
concrete, more convincing in finding solutions, finding new
arguments in elaborating the forms of verification and control. ...
   The president and I ... have approved a joint statement. It
summarizes what _ the advances made since Washington and what has
been achieved here in Moscow. At the same time, this statement
confirms a sort of agenda for the Soviet-American dialogue for the
future. It is, in short, an important political document which
hallmarks a whole phase in our relations. The most important points
in it are those clauses which relate to the importance of building
up political dialogue between the nations, intensifying the talks
and negotiations and then I would mention further _ I would note
progress made in the sphere of disarmament. This is a very
difficult process, especially if you take the question of strategic
offensive arms. It's not an easy dialogue. ...
   I must state very firmly that step-by-step we are moving toward
a treaty on strategic offensive arms. ... I will say that if we
effectively conduct our business, and if the present administration
_ and of course, this applies to both countries _ if we act
effectively, using all of our possibilities and opportunities, we
can achieve a treaty. ...
</TEXT>
