<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Spoleto     06-01 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spoleto,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abandoned World War I Gun Battery is Stage for Medieval Drama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SULLIVAN'S ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Battery Thomson, nestled on the
shores of Sullivan's Island flanking Charleston harbor, was built
years ago for a German attack that never came.
   But on recent evenings, the World War I-era cement and stone
bunker has become the torch-lighted stage for portraying a much
older conflict: ``Wat Tyler,'' Richard Sewell's dramatic account of
a peasant revolt in 14th century England.
   Running Horse Productions of Los Angeles is staging the premiere
of the play as part of Piccolo Spoleto, a companion festival to
Charleston's Spoleto Festival U.S.A.
   The production deals with the 1381 uprising in which Tyler
marched with an army of 10,000 serfs to confront King Richard II,
then 14.
   Karl Wiedergott, who recently did a pilot for a new CBS-TV
series called ``Limited Partners,'' plays the role of Tyler. Robert
Winley is John Ball, an itinerant priest who inspired Tyler.
Richard Horvitz, who recently appeared in the movie ``Summer
School,'' plays the king.
   Of the 20 cast members, 12 are from Los Angeles and eight from
Charleston. The actors are volunteering their time for the
production.
   ``We're doing a $50,000 show for $18,000,'' said Nathan
LeGrande, one of the co-producers. ``It would cost $75,000 in L.A.''
   Cast members helped build risers for seating, helped assemble
scaffolding for light towers and spent hours in the hot sun
clearing a battery of weeds and broken glass.
   The audience is escorted through a cave-like door of the bunker
and through a hallway lined with candles. On the other side with
underbrush lining the battery, the scene takes on the aura of a
medieval castle.
   Before being taken over by the production, the battery was a
hangout for youths who live on the island where master of the
macabre Edgar Allan Poe wrote ``Annabel Lee'' and ``The Gold Bug.''
   Locals on the island of weathered beach houses have opened their
doors to the West Coast cast.
   ``We've been getting a lot of attention because it's an unusual
project as a whole,'' LeGrande said.
   Local merchants have donated food, neighbors have put up
relatives of cast members while 13 actors are living in a beach
house provided by a resident.
   For Doug MacHugh, who has appeared in a number of TV series and
has the part of Jack Straw in the play, the production is a chance
to perform away from Los Angeles.
   ``It's a new piece without the L.A. environment,'' he said. ``We
get to work with something untouched, and we get Sullivan's Island
too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
