<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ConstructionSpending     06-01 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Spending,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Factory Construction Spurs Increased Construction Spending in
April</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending advanced 0.1 percent in
April as a boom in factory construction helped offset weakness in
government projects, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
   The department said building activity rose to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $401.8 billion in April, up 1.4 percent
from a year ago.
   The April advance followed a big 1.3 percent jump in March and a
0.4 percent February increase.
   But analysts tended to discount the weak overall change and
instead focus on a big 8.8 percent rise in spending on industrial
plants, which put activity in this sector up a remarkable 39.8
percent above where it was a year ago.
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist of the National Association of
Manufacturers, said the gain reflected the boom in export sales,
which has meant plants in many industries are operating near full
capacity.
   ``Industry was trying to cut costs in 1982 and 1983 by slashing
capacity and closing down plants,'' he said. ``The growth in
construction is a reflection of increased international demand
running against a production supply that had been cut back too much
in previous years.''
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said that
while the construction figures so far this year have been strong,
he expected weakness in the months ahead in both residential and
non-residential building because of the recent increases in
interest rates.
   Government construction, after soaring 5 percent in March, fell
by 3.1 percent in April to an annual rate of $79.3 billion. But
analysts said this swing in a volatile category was not worrisome
and they predicted further gains in the months ahead based on
increased federal money for highway projects which Congress
approved last year over President Reagan's veto.
   Residential construction posted a 0.4 percent advance in April
to an annual rate of $191.9 billion. This reflected a 0.8 percent
increase in construction of single-family homes and a 1.4 percent
drop in apartment construction.
   Apartment building is now 22.2 percent below the level of a year
ago as this sector continues to be hurt by changes in the tax law
and high vacancy rates.
   Non-residential construction climbed 2.1 percent in April to an
annual rate of $94.4 billion. In addition to the big 8.8 percent
advance in industrial construction, office construction posted a
1.1 percent increase while construction of shopping centers and
other commercial buildings rose 2.9 percent.
</TEXT>
