<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParkingTheft     06-01 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parking Theft,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airport Parking Cashiers Stole Up to $2 Million, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parking cashiers at Los Angeles International
Airport skimmed as much as $2 million from customers' parking fees
by substituting low-value tickets for higher-priced ones, court
documents said.
   The cashiers obtained bogus parking tickets by rolling shopping
carts over sensors and then traded $2 stubs for those turned in by
customers who paid up to $100, according to documents unsealed
Tuesday.
   The cashiers pocketed up to $250 an hour, police said in
affidavits seeking search warrants.
   More than 30 employees of Parking Concepts Inc., which operates
the 25,000-space airport parking concession, were indicted May 19
on charges of embezzling city funds. Officials estimated that as
much as $2 million had been skimmed.
   According to the documents, new applicants for parking cashier
positions were forced to pay up to $3,000 to gain the $7-an-hour
jobs, but were assured by managers that they could make that money
back through the alleged embezzlement scheme.
   Twenty-three defendants pleaded innocent to embezzlement charges
Tuesday; preliminary hearings were scheduled for June and July.
Three others were arraigned last week; two were to enter pleas June
7.
   Deputy District Attorney Peter Berman declined comment on the
status of the remaining defendants.
   Police infiltrated Parking Concepts last June after an anonymous
tip alerted authorities to the scheme, Detective Floyd Simmons Jr.
said.
</TEXT>
