<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Journalist,1st Ld-Writethru,a0755,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Seeks Release Of Imprisoned Journalist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with radio report of Najib
approving release; pickup 3rd pvs, `Italy's Foreign ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan has responded to a humanitarian appeal
from Italy and pardoned an Italian journalist jailed for 6{ months
on charges of espionage, the Foreign Ministry announced Wednesday.
   In Kabul, the Afghan capital, President Najib said he would
consider the Italian request, Kabul television said. In a later
report, Kabul radio, monitored in Islamabad, Pakistan, said a
``decree was passed by the (Afghan) president on the release.''
   Italy's Foreign Ministry and Western diplomats in Kabul said
they expected Fausto Biloslavo, 26, to be freed by Thursday.
   Biloslavo, who worked for the tiny Trieste-based Albatross news
agency, was arrested Nov. 14 after entering Afghanistan with
anti-government guerrillas. He was convicted of espionage in March.
   Earlier reports from Kabul said he was arrested in July 1987.
   Kabul television showed Najib meeting an Italian delegation
headed by Bruno Bottai, secretary general of the Foreign Ministry.
Bottai went to Afghanistan with a message from Italian President
Francesco Cossiga asking Biloslavo's release on humanitarian
grounds.
   Biloslavo had shared a jail cell with French photojournalist
Alain Guillo, who was freed Friday after nine months imprisonment
in Afghanistan. Guillo also had been convicted of espionage after
entering Afghanistan with the guerrillas.
   Guillo, 45, was convicted Jan. 4 and sentenced to 10 years
imprisonment.
   Biloslavo was sentenced to seven years.
   Biloslavo's mother, Grazia, reached in Trieste, said she planned
to fly to Rome to await her son's return as soon as she receives
confirmation that he has been freed. ``I'm still shaken up, I can
hardly believe the news,'' she said.
</TEXT>
