<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique-Rebels     06-01 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique-Rebels,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Attack on Army Base, Says Briton Among Those Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozambique's right-wing rebels claimed
Wednesday their guerrilla forces attacked an major Mozambican army
base, tore up railway tracks and killed 28 people, including a
British military instructor.
   In a statement released in Lisbon, the rebel Mozambican National
Resistance said 16 army regulars, nine Zimbabwe support troops, two
Cuban advisers and the Briton were killed Sunday at the base at
Magude, 75 miles north of the capital of Maputo.
   In Maputo, the British Embassy said Wednesday it had no
information to corroborate the claim that a British military
instructor was killed.
   The rebel note identified the Cubans as Alexandre Gimenez and
Frederico Lopez. The Briton's name was given as Richard Thone.
   James Allan, Britain's ambassador to Mozambique, told the
national news agency AIM that his embassy had no record of anyone
named Thone and had received no first-hand report of any Briton
being killed or injured.
   Allan said a British team trains Mozambican soldiers at a base
in Zimbabwe but does not have military personnel stationed in
Mozambique, except for an attache at the embassy.
   In the rebel statement, the group denied charges by the
Mozambique's Marxist government that the rebels still receive South
African backing despite a 1984 non-aggression pact between
Mozambique and South Africa. It has claimed earlier killings of
British military instructors posted in Mozambique.
   Zimbabwe and Tanzania have sent support troops to aid the
Mozambican army in its 11-year campaign to stop the bloody bush
insurgency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-ArmsNegotiations 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Arms Negotiations, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0739,690</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts new grafs 5-6 with Rowny quotes</NOTE>
<HEAD>Summit Produced Some Marginal Advances on Arms Control Front</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th graf bgng: In a ... to UPDATE with
Rowny quotes. Picks up 6th graf pvs bgng: Besides modest ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Kremlin leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev reported progress Wednesday over two obstacles to a
strategic arms deal, but ended their fourth summit divided over the
main impediment, the U.S. Star Wars program.
   ``I would hope that before the year is out that we could
eliminate the differences that still exist,'' Reagan said. But
there seemed little prospect for any imminent breakthrough.
   After four days of intense talks, the two leaders ordered their
negotiators to return to Geneva on July 12 to work on a proposed
treaty to cut superpower nclear arsenals by 30 percent to 50
percent.
   Gorbachev told reporters ``it is still possible to sign an
agreement in this administration.'' Reagan said, ``Conversations
are still going on and they are still being discussed and I say
progress is still being made or we wouldn't be talking as we are.''
   In a 24-page joint statement, the two leaders announced
``achievement of substantial additional common ground'' on two of
the five major disputed areas on the proposed Strategic Arms
Reduction Treaty (START), ways of monitoring mobile missiles and
counting nuclear-tipped cruise missiles on warplanes.
   But U.S. arms negotiator Edward Rowny said there was ``a lot of
room'' to go in the two areas.
   And he said ``we didn`t get anywhere'' on the two biggest
obstacles to a treaty: keeping track of submarine-fired cruise
missiles and Soviet objections to Reagan's Star Wars
missile-defense program, formally known as the Strategic Defense
Inititiative.
   Besides modest progress on START, the two leaders inched ahead
on other arms control issues.
   They exchanged ratification protocols for the Intermediate-Range
Nuclear Forces treaty (INF) to eliminate medium-range nuclear
missiles, which was signed at the Washington summit last December
and ratified by the Senate last Friday and by the Soviet assembly
of presidents 17 hours later.
   During the summit, Gorbachev and Reagan also signed two lesser
arms control agreements, one requiring advance notifice of
ballistic missile tests and another to tighten verification
procedures for a 1974 treaty limiting nuclear tests to 150 kilotons.
   On the START treaties, U.S. officials said they had restated
opposition to deployment of Soviet SS-24 and SS-25 missiles.
   ``It is the position of the United States that such missiles
should be banned unless the United States and the Soviet Union can
reach agreement on provisions which provide for effective
verification and strict numerical limits on the number of nuclear
weapons carried by such missiles,'' U.S. officials said.
   U.S. officials, in a briefing paper given to reporters, said
that acceptable verification rules would require, among other
things, restricting mobile missiles to specific geographical areas,
means to assure that spy satellites can keep tabs on all such
weapons, and the right to inspect sites to investigate suspected
violations.
   The two sides remained far apart on Star Wars and how to
negotiate reductions in conventional armies.
   ``We have missed a chance to take an important step forward,''
Gorbachev told reporters.
   The Kremlin leader, who has used all four meetings with Reagan
as forums to air his opposition to Star Wars, said he had proposed
resolving the problem by exchanging data allowing mutual inspection
of facilities where technology for an anti-missile defense is
tested.
   But no strategic arms treaty is possible, he said, without an
agreement assuring that development and deployment of strategic
defenses does not violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
And a fifth summit would not be possible without a START deal, he
said.
   On the opening day of the talks, U.S. and Soviet officials said,
Gorbachev suggested to Reagan that they exchange data on
conventional arms as a means of making drastic cuts, as proposed by
the Russians in 1986.
   U.S. officials say they will not directly negotiate conventional
cuts with the Soviets, because the matter must be agreed upon by
the 33 nations taking part in the Conference on Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
   Those talks also include discussion of alleged Soviet violations
of human rights provisions of the original conference accord,
signed in Helsinki in 1975.
</TEXT>
