<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ExecutionSquad     06-01 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Execution Squad,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Seeks to Strip Citizenship from Seattle Man Accused of War
Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department moved Wednesday to
strip U.S. citizenship from a Seattle man accused of being part of
an execution squad that murdered unarmed Jews and other civilians
for the Nazis during World War II.
   Valdis Didrichsons concealed his service in the Latvian Security
Auxiliary Police in 1941 and 1942 when he entered the United States
in 1950 under the Displaced Persons Act, the government alleged in
a complaint filed in U.S. District Court in Seattle. A native of
Latvia, Didrichsons became a U.S. citizen in August 1956.
   Assisting in persecution makes a person ineligible to immigrate
to the United States and requires revocation of citizenship. The
denaturalization case against Didrichsons is the first step in a
process which could lead to deportation.
   The objective of the Arajs Kommando, as the auxiliary unit was
known, was to assist in the persecution and murder of people
considered to be racially undesirable or enemies of Nazi Germany in
occupied Latvia, said Neal Sher, director of the Justice
Department's Nazi-hunting unit, the Office of Special
Investigations.
   Didrichsons assisted in persecution, said the complaint, and
concealed his membership in the Kommando when he applied for
citizenship as well as when he entered the country.
   The Justice Department also has instituted legal proceedings
against Konrads Kalejs of Chicago and Mikelis Kirsteins of
Syracuse, N.Y., who allegedly served with Didrichsons in the
Kommando in 1941.
</TEXT>
