<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Disarmament     06-01 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Disarmament,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Speakers Call On Soviets And U.S. To Ban Nuclear Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to a special United Nations
session on disarmament on Wednesday urged the United States and the
Soviet Union to ban underground weapons tests and scrap their
nuclear arsenals.
   Speakers began addressing the special session as President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev concluded their Moscow
summit meeting with an impasse on achieving major cuts in strategic
nuclear weapons.
   But the assembly praised the superpower treaty eliminating
intermediate-range nuclear weapons as a breakthrough because it
scraps a whole class of nuclear weapons for the first time.
   Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson of Sweden called for complete
nuclear disarmament and said the use of nuclear arms could threaten
the survival of civilization.
   ``One cannot reach peace by frightening other countries,'' he
said.
   ``The United Nations could and should have a central role in the
sphere of disarmament, and is the most appropriate organization to
carry out verification functions on behalf of the international
community,'' he said.
   It can provide unique services, as a repository of data and
source of impartial observers and experts, he said.
   He called for 50 percent cuts in strategic weapons, complete
abolition of all tactical nuclear weapons, prevention of a nuclear
arms race in outer space, a comprehensive nuclear test ban, the
signing the nuclear nonproliferation treaty, and the removal of
nuclear weapons from naval vessels.
   Carlsson also condemned the use of chemical weapons in the
Iran-Iraq war and said the buildup of anti-personnel lasers also
must be stopped.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita of Japan, the only nation that
has been the target of an atomic attack, said his people pray for
disarmament. Japan's constitution prohibits the presence or
development of nuclear weapons.
   Takeshita announced that Japan plans to convene an international
conference with the United Nations to share Japanese technology in
seismology to verify nuclear testing. He said it could serve as
step toward establishing a global system for verification of
nuclear testing.
   He said Japan would increase its assistance to the United
Nations to prevent conflicts, noting that Japan recently
contributed $20 million to the United Nations, including $5 million
for use in Afghanistan where the world body mediated a settlement.
   The Japanese leader said he was considering the dispatch of
personnel for election supervision, transportation, communication
and medical services to Afghanistan.
   President Robert G. Mugabe of Zimbabwe delivered the opening
address as chairman of the non-aligned movement. He condemned the
superpowers for the nuclear arms race and said military spending
should be diverted to development.
   He said the international community must work toward achieving a
nuclear-free world with the help of the United Nations and the
multilateral Conference on Disarmament.
   Mugabe called for a comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty _ a
measure opposed by the United States _ and he opposed the
militarization of outer space _ a reference to the U.S. space-based
missile defense initiative, or ``Star Wars.'' He called for the
establishment of nuclear-free zones, including Africa.
   More than 25 heads of state and government will address the
159-member General Assembly in the next two weeks in the third
special session on disarmament in 10 years. The world body then
will adopt resolutions on disarmament, from nuclear to chemical,
and steps to achieve it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
