<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-RegionalConflicts     06-01 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Regional Conflicts,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Superpowers Dogged by `Serious Differences' Over Regional Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev acknowledged after five days of summit talks Wednesday
that they remain divided by ``serious differences'' over efforts to
end regional conflicts from Central America to the Middle East.
   Nonetheless, U.S. officials held out hope for progress in
southern Africa, and the two leaders cited the Soviet pullout from
Afghanistan as an example of what the superpowers can achieve if
they work together with warring factions.
   Gorbachev sent a strong signal that Soviet forces withdrawing
from Afghanistan would return fire if subjected to continuing
attacks from Moslem rebels battling the Soviet-backed government in
Kabul.
   ``We shall react accordingly and appropriately,'' said
Gorbachev, referring to recent assaults on Soviet troops and the
Soviet Embassy in Kabul. ``That should be absolutely clear.''
   The Soviets disclosed last week that more than 13,000 of their
troops had been killed since they intervened in Afghanistan in
December 1979.
   A senior U.S. official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said Gorbachev raised the issue of attacks on
withdrawing troops directly with Reagan this week. On Saturday, the
Soviet Foreign Ministry publicly protested continued arms shipments
to the Afghan rebels from Pakistan.
   Another U.S. official, also speaking privately: ``We'll stand by
Pakistan.''
   Soviet chief of staff Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev was reported to
have presented a detailed plan for withdrawal of the estimated
115,000 Soviet troops in Afghanistan, indicating that Moscow
intends to abide by the Geneva agreement to remove all its forces
by Feb. 15.
   The final communique issued by Reagan and Gorbachev said their
talks had ``revealed serious differences both in the assessments of
the causes of regional tensions and in the means to overcome them.''
   The leaders were able to agree only ``that these differences
need not be an obstacle to constructive interaction'' on regional
conflicts, the statement said.
   In other developments:
   _ Gorbachev told a televised post-summit news conference that
the Soviets are ready to consider restoring diplomatic relations
with Israel once an international conference on the Middle East is
convened. But he said several issues yet to be resolved included
Palestinian participation in the conference and topics to be
discussed.
   The Soviet Union and all its Eastern bloc allies except Romania
severed ties with Israel in 1967 over the Six Day War. The Kremlin
sent a consular delegation to Israel last year, and other East
European nations have strengthened their ties with the Jewish state
in recent months.
   _ A U.S. official, speaking on condition he not be identified,
said summit talks on southern Africa went well. He said the two
sides set a September deadline for completing a complex deal
involving withdrawal of 40,000 Cuban troops from Angola and
reconciliation of that country's Marxist government and U.S.-backed
guerrillas.
   Another potential area of U.S.-Soviet cooperation may involve
locating the 311 Soviet troops reported missing in action in
Afghanistan. Reagan signaled U.S. willingness to help, and
Gorbachev said Wednesday that contacts had been made with U.S. and
Pakistani officials in behalf of the MIAs.
   On the Middle East, Gorbachev said that ``there has been a
drawing closer of our positions,'' citing agreement that an
international conference is needed.
   ``We've given the Americans several years of opportunity to go
it alone'' in the Middle East, Gorbachev said. ``They saw that they
couldn't.''
   Other conflicts discussed by the two leaders and their
delegations included Central America and the Iran-Iraq war.
   The Reagan administration has tried to persuade the Soviets to
support an arms embargo against Iran and Iraq but Moscow has
hesitated. U.S. officials say Kremlin leaders want to avoid souring
future relations with neighboring Iran.
</TEXT>
