<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PossumBludgeoning     06-01 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Possum Bludgeoning,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Investigating Possum Bludgeoning at Vocational School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal rights officials are
investigating a complaint that a teacher used a shovel to beat an
opossum and five of its babies to death.
   The incident marks the second time in two years a teacher at
Greater New Bedford Voc-Tech High School has been investigated for
killing an opossum.
   In May 1986, the executive direcor of the Animal Rescue League
in New Bedford, sought charges against a chef-instructor at the
school for butchering an opossum for a cooking demonstration. But a
judge refused to bring charges.
   An investigator for the Massachusetts Society for the Prevention
of Cruelty to Animals went to the school Tuesday after an anonymous
complaint, according to Stephen J. Torre, director of the law
enforcement department for the Boston-based organization.
   Cruelty to animals is a criminal offense. If the killing is
found to be done with malicious intent, the penalty can be up to
$500 in fines or one year in prison, or both.
   The investigator retrieved the animals' bodies from a school
trash bin. They were mangled and one of the babies had been
decapitated, Torre said.
   Jeffrey E. Riley, superintendent-director at the regional
vocational-technical high school, said Tuesday he had heard reports
of the incident and was investigating. He declined to comment
further.
   Officials refused to identify the teacher.
</TEXT>
