<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     06-01 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Government, Corporations to Step Up Pollution Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODBRIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson
walked on a garbage-covered beach Wednesday and called on
corporations and the federal government to battle pollution more
vigorously.
   Jackson's campaign stop capped five days of seeking votes in New
Jersey, which has its primary next Tuesday. The biggest delegate
prize on that day is California, though, and the Democratic
contender headed back to that state late Wednesday.
   In New Jersey, stepping over broken glass, plastic bottles,
fast-food containers and a woman's shoe, Jackson described this
one-time popular resort beach along the Arthur Kill as an example
of ``economic and environmental violence.''
   ``If the Russians were poisoning our air, if they were dumping
sludge in the water, if they were killing fish, we would call that
chemical warfare and we would negotiate tough,'' said Jackson.
   Nearly all the trash on the beach here, including such hospital
waste as used syringes and plasma bags, floats across from the
Fresh Kills landfill in Staten Island, N.Y., and residents speak
harshly of New York's disposal practices.
   But Jackson said corporations and the federal government were
most to blame for the pollution. He said that cleaning up the shore
and toxic waste dumps would create jobs and protect the public's
health.
   ``This idea that it's coming from one state to another is one
focus. But in my judgment it's too narrow a focus,'' said Jackson.
``The federal government has an obligation. We must invest in
recycliong plants. We must challenge these corporations and offer
them incentives to build these recycling plants.''
   Jackson, who lags far behind Democratic front-runner Michael
Dukakis in New Jersey polls, used his stay in the state to further
define what he would want at the party convention in Atlanta.
   On Wednesday, he said the party needs him if it wants a victory
in November and said again he deserves consideration as vice
president should he not get the presidential nomination.
   Dukakis, campaigning in New Jersey over the Memorial Day
weekend, also called for stepped-up efforts to battle ocean
pollution. Jackson, asked how he differed from Dukakis on
environmental issues, said the Massachusetts governor's reputation
as a good manager is not enough to battle pollution.
   ``I take the position that we cannot just manage these
corporations as they exist. Their behavior must change. They must
be much more accountable,'' said Jackson.
   As he walked along the beach, a helicopter from the
Environmental Protection Agency skimmed the water. Local officials
said they had never seen one before.
   Jackson attributed the helicopter's arrival to ``Action
Jackson,'' a phrase he urges crowds to chant during rallies, and
said the agency has been ineffective against polluters.
   Richard Cahill, a spokesman for the EPA in New York, said the
helicopter was part of the agency's routine shore monitoring
program and its appearance Wednesday was coincidental.
</TEXT>
