<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviet-HumanRights     06-01 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Human Rights,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Gets High Marks On Human Rights, Despite Bureaucracy
Comment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some human rights observers questioned
President Reagan's assertion Wednesday that Soviet emigration
barriers are the result of bureaucratic bungling, but gave the
president high marks overall on his handling of the issue at the
Moscow summit.
   ``It's really hard to know where Reagan was coming from on
that,'' said Dawn Mann, a fellow at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, an independent policy research institute.
``The fact that there still are several hundred prisoners of
conscience is not attributable to bureaucratic snafus.''
   At his news conference in Moscow, Reagan said emigration
barriers may arise from a Kremlin ``bound in by bureaucracy,''
rather than deliberate Soviet policy.
   ``I think it's unfortunate ... that the president was not more
direct about the real reasons for human rights violations in the
Soviet Union,'' said Juliana Pilon, a Soviet scholar at the
conservative Heritage Foundation. ``After all, who is he kidding?
... It just isn't true.''
   But a Democratic congressman who studies human rights issues,
Rep. Gus Yatron, D-Pa., dismissed Reagan's comments as stemming
from a desire not to criticize his host too harshly while still in
the Soviet Union. ``I think it was more protocol'' than timidity on
human rights, said Yatron, chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
human rights subcommittee.
   ``I can think of no one in Congress or the administration who
feels that Moscow's repressive policies are not the results of the
repressive nature of a communist government,'' Yatron said. ``I
would want to give the president the benefit of the doubt.''
   Reagan's comment, which declined to pin responsibilty for
emigration denials directly on Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
really was a skillful diplomatic gesture, said Rep. Gerald Solomon,
R-N.Y., the senior Republican on Yatron's panel.
   ``That gives wiggle room for Gorbachev to react, and without
confrontational demands,'' Solomon said. ``I'm confident that it
will work.''
   Solomon and others said overall, Reagan had made human rights a
far higher priority at this fourth summit meeting than at previous
meetings with Gorbachev, and predicted improvements in Soviet
emigration and other human rights areas.
   ``I thought he was very forceful in his presentation of human
rights,'' Yatron said. ``I am cautiously optimistic that the
president's aggressive posture will spark more reforms.''
   ``We couldn't have hoped for more as a human rights
organization,'' said Jeri Laber of Helsinki Watch in New York.
``The president has certainly made this an important issue'' by
meeting with dissidents in the Soviet Union and making strong
statements about U.S. human rights values.
   But she said being diplomatic isn't always the best approach
when dealing with such an issue of inalienable rights. ``You've got
to be vocal and verbal and insistent, even to the point of
irritating'' those you are dealing with, said Laber. ``We recognize
he has a balancing act to do. Given all of that, he's done a very
good job.''
   ``Only time will tell,'' said Mann. ``If more people are
released in the next several weeks, if there are concrete actions,
then we can say Reagan was right to have been so tactful. There's
so much that we don't know.''
</TEXT>
