<DOCNO> AP880601-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FactoryOrders     06-01 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Orders,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two-Month Surge in Factory Orders Should Keep Plants Busy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories surged for the second
consecutive month in April, the government said Wednesday,
indicating that U.S. manufacturing plants will be humming in the
months ahead.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable and non-durable
goods rose a strong 1.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted $218.7
billion in April. The advance followed an even bigger 1.6 percent
increase in March.
   ``The boom-like conditions in factory America continue pretty
much unabated,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co.
   There was no change in order levels in February and a modest 0.6
percent drop in January. But that was one of only two declines in
the past year.
   Most economists had been forecasting only modest growth in new
orders of 0.5 percent in April. The bigger-than-expected number
likely will do little to alleviate concern among some analysts that
strong demand, particularly for exports, will trigger greater
inflation.
   David Wyss, chief financial economist at Data Resources Inc., a
Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm, noted the continuing increase
in the backlog of unfilled orders, indicating manufacturers have
been getting more orders than they can meet.
   ``This should be good news for production in coming months,''
Wyss said.
   The backlog of $418.1 billion was 10.8 percent higher than a
year ago. It jumped by 1 percent in April following a smaller
increase of 0.4 percent in March.
   The strength in new orders in April came in electrical
machinery, lumber and wood products and in petroleum, chemicals and
paper.
   The department revised its estimate of new orders for durable
goods, ``big ticket items'' expected to last three or more years,
to $116.4 billion, up 1.0 percent. The previous estimate for April,
released 10 days ago, was 0.8 percent. The gain in March had been
0.8 percent.
   Orders for non-durable goods increased 1.5 percent to $102.2
billion in April following a 2.5 percent rise a month earlier.
   Excluding the volatile category of military goods, orders were
up 1.2 percent in April, the third consecutive increase and the
sixth rise in seven months.
   Defense goods rose 2.2 percent to $10.0 billion in April,
following a whopping 14.6 percent rise in March.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a
barometer of business expansion plans, rose 1.9 percent in April to
$33.1 billion, following a drop of 3.8 percent.
   Analysts are looking for businesses to boost capital spending to
meet the rising demand abroad for U.S. goods, which have become
more competitively priced because of the devalued dollar.
   Orders for electrical machinery climbed 4.2 percent, following a
3.8 percent slide in March. Most of the April strength in that
category came from a large 25.4 percent rise in orders for
communication equipment, most of them from the Defense Department.
   Orders for primary metals such as steel declined 0.3 percent in
April, while orders for transportation equipment climbed a slight
0.1 percent and non-electrical machinery fell 0.6 percent.
   Shipments of manufactured goods were unchanged at $214.6 billion
in April following a 2.7 percent increase in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
