<2ND_LINE>AM-Discrimination Suit,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement Reached in Discrimination Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative settlement reached in a
sex discrimination case against a citrus grower calls for a payment
of $550,000 to women who alleged foremen forced them to trade sex
for job security.
   However, the settlement reached Tuesday has to be approved by a
federal judge and potential plaintiffs in the suit, which attorneys
for the six original plaintiffs say may be broadened to a class
action.
   Some of the six also are part of a 44-person racial
discrimination suit filed against Caulkins Groves in Martin County.
No trial date has been set.
   Caulkins lawyer J. David Richeson said that under the agreement,
the grower admits no guilt by settling the case.
   Under the tentative agreement, Caulkins' insurers would pay
$550,000 in a lump sum to the six women who sued in 1986, alleging
they were regularly forced to trade sex for job security, shuffled
into lower-paying, hard-working jobs and denied advancement.
   Caulkins, a limited partnership based at Indiantown, owns citrus
groves, a feed mill, a juice plant that makes concentrate and a car
dealership.
   From the late 1960s or early 1970s, women employees have given
statements saying they were raped by grove foremen. The latest
incident occurred in 1980.
</TEXT>
