<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Workers     06-01 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Workers,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police Disperse Workers Demanding Higher Pay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of factory workers smashed windows and
furniture at the Finance Ministry on Wednesday to press demands in
a labor dispute, and police dispersed them with tear gas.
   Police said five officers were slightly injured. Army radio said
15 protesters were injured by inhaling tear gas and several
ministry employees were hit by broken glass. Israel radio said 16
protesters were arrested.
   ``We didn't intend to break into the ministry,'' Moshe Levy,
head of the workers' committee, said on Israel television. ``We are
sorry for what happened. It was just all the anger and frustration
coming out.''
   Violence began after 400 workers from Beit Shemesh Engines held
an authorized demonstration outside the ministry. A few started
burning tires, pelted the building with stones and eggs, then used
an overturned garbage can to force open the door, Israel radio said.
   ``The workers did not obey our orders and overturned a police
barrier,'' said police Lt. Alex Lapidot. ``Then several dozen broke
into the ministry, smashing windows and plants.''
   Police fired tear gas about 15 minutes later, Lapidot said.
Paramilitary border police and mounted police were called to assist.
   ``We do not fear tear gas!'' Levy shouted through a megaphone as
he led the workers to another rally outside the nearby Parliament
building. No further violence was reported.
   The workers were protesting the breakdown of talks on
compensation for 260 workers laid off at the plant, Israel's
largest producer of aircraft engines.
   Victor Medina, deputy director of the Finance Ministry, told
Israel radio the demands of the workers were ``highly exaggerated''
and could not be met.
</TEXT>
