<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TestTubeBabies     06-01 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Test Tube Babies,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Urged To Regulate Test-Tube Baby Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicians are overpromising success to women
desperate to have children and there is need for congressional
oversight of the $30 million to $40 million test-tube baby
industry, Congress was told Wednesday.
   ``Under the best of circumstances, infertile couples already
face invasive medical procedures, the risk of dangerous
complications and low success rates,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
``Frustrated couples, many at an emotional breaking point,
shouldn't also have to face those who would exploit their faith in
modern medicine.''
   Wyden, chairman of the House Small Business subcommittee on
regulation and business opportunities, said he wants to determine
what role the government should play in protecting would-be parents
from unscrupulous clinics.
   He called attention to a recent study that found more than half
of the 169 clinics in the United States performing in-vitro
fertilization (IVF) in 1987 never produced a baby.
   ``Despite advances in technology and the claims made by some
clinics, the chance of having a baby from IVF still hovers at one
in ten,'' Wyden said. ``This slim opportunity costs most couples
thousands of dollars. The subcommittee has heard of couples
spending over $22,000 without yielding a baby in the bassinet.''
   The infertility study for the congressional Office of Technology
Assessment showed Americans spent $1 billion last year to combat
infertility.
   Gary Ellis, who directed the OTA study, told the subcommittee
the chances of becoming clinically pregnant _ when a fetus's
heartbeat is detected by ultrasound machines _ is about 17 percent,
and a woman still faces a one in three chance that the pregnancy is
ectopic or that it will end in a miscarriage or stillbirth. An
ectopic pregnancy is one outside the uterus.
   Therefore, he said, a woman's chance of taking home a test-tube
baby is about 6 percent.
   He said that infertility, generally defined as the inability of
a couple to conceive after 12 months of intercourse without
contraception, affects an estimated 2.4 million married couples and
an unknown number of would-be parents among unmarried couples and
singles.
   Wyden's subcommittee also heard from a woman, Vicki Eckhardt,
who said a fertility expert over a four-year span told her seven
times that she was pregnant, but that each time would find the
fetus had been ``absorbed.'' Her husband, Bill, said they had spent
$35,000 on infertility treatments, only to learn from another
doctor that Mrs. Eckhardt probably never had been pregnant.
   The doctor, she said, ``out and out lied to use, telling us I
was pregnant.
   ``Each time I felt like I had failed again, that my own body was
killing our baby,'' Mrs. Eckhardt said. ``But then I would get that
little urge again and want a baby so badly that I would go through
anything.
   ``It's hard to explain to other people, but when you want a baby
so badly and you're afraid you may never be able to have one, it's
all you can think about. It affects the way you see the whole
world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
