<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PregnancyRates     06-01 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pregnancy Rates,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Posts High Pregnancy, Abortion Rates, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pregnancy and abortion rates in the United
States are among the highest found in a new study of Western
nations, averaging 2.56 pregnancies and 0.76 abortions for each
woman of reproductive age.
   Only Greece and Ireland showed higher pregnancy rates, with 4.33
and 3.23 respectively, in the study of 17 industrialized countries.
   Greece also had a higher abortion rate, 2.24, as did Italy, with
0.80, according to researchers at The Alan Guttmacher Institute, a
New York organization that studies fertility issues.
   The study appears in the current issue of the institute's Family
Planning Perspectives.
   The lowest pregnancy rates appeared in West Germany, with 1.64,
and the Netherlands, with 1.68. The lowest abortion rates were in
Ireland, with 0.15, and the Netherlands, with 0.18.
   Abortion is outlawed by Ireland and another nation in the study,
Belgium, although abortions are still relatively easy to to obtain
in Belgium, the researchers wrote. Substantial limitations are
imposed by Australia, West Germany, Greece, and New Zealand, the
scientists said.
   The other countries in the survey were Canada, Denmark, Finland,
France, Great Britain, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland. The study
was based on the year of most recent abortion data, which was 1983
for the United States.
   Researchers also compared contraceptive use among the 17 nations
plus Australia, Portugal and Spain.
   Some method of contraception was used in 1982 by about 54
percent of American women of reproductive age, defined as ages 15
to 44, researchers said. That level ranked relatively low, along
with those of Portugal and Spain.
   About 37 percent of the American women used a contraceptive
pill, an intra-uterine device or male or female sterilization, a
``medium'' level of use in comparison to the other countries. That
showing is largely due to widespread use of sterilization,
researchers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
