<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Philippines     06-01 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Philippines,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Strategist Cautions Against Philippines-Vietnam Tradeoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To get American military forces out of the
Philippines Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev should offer much
more than shutting down the biggest Soviet overseas base at Cam
Ranh Bay, Vietnam, U.S. military strategist Brent Scowcroft said
Wednesday.
   A Cam Ranh-Philippines tradeoff by the superpowers ``would be
very much in the Soviet interest but not necessarily ours,'' said
Scowcroft, a retired air force lieutenant general and national
security adviser in the Ford administration.
   ``The Russians don't need that (Cam Ranh) nearly as much as we
do the Philippines,'' he said.
   Scowcroft spoke at a news conference marking the issuance of a
new expert study on forthcoming U.S.-Philippines base negotiations
produced for the U.S. Council on Foreign Relations, a non-profit,
non-partisan organization.
   The study noted that the massive Soviet military presence at Cam
Ranh Bay is used as justification for the U.S. military presence in
the Philippines and vice versa. Analysts have said Gorbachev's July
1986 Asian policy speech suggesting a U.S. pullout from the
Philippines implied an offer to reduce the Soviet presence in
Vietnam.
   The Philippine bases, Clark Field air base and Subic Bay naval
station, are vital for deploying U.S. forces to the Indian Ocean
and Persian Gulf while ``the Soviets can get to the Indian Ocean
through the back door'' from the other direction, Scowcroft said.
   He predicted that practical benefits to both countries are
likely to result in enough accomodation to produce a new
U.S.-Philippines base agreement when the current one expires in
1991. ``There is a fair chance that cool heads will prevail,'' he
said.
   Scowcroft and Prof. Fred Greene, a Williams College Asian
affairs expert and editor of the 155-page study, emphasized that
the issues are complex, tangled and emotional.
   Ever since 1947, Washington has handled base arrangements with
the Philippines through executive agreements requiring majority
votes in Congress for implementation.
   However, a two-thirds Senate vote is required to ratify a
treaty, and many in the Philippines are demanding this form for the
next base agreement so as to highlight Philippine sovereignty and
U.S. payment obligations, Greene said.
   That would play into the hands of American senators and others
``who for budget or policy reasons would like to have reductions
around the world, especially if the Philippines insists on a
treaty,'' Greene said.
   Estimating that 20 percent of Filipinos oppose the bases, he
said many are ``very intense and eloquent'' in their opposition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Justice-Christensen     06-01 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Christensen,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Aide Says He Thinks Meese Will Stay Through Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Deputy Attorney General Harold
Christensen said Wednesday he believes Attorney General Edwin Meese
III will remain at the Justice Department until the end of the
Reagan administration.
   During his first day on the job, Christensen said ``I don't have
any sense of crisis at all'' and that the department ``is
functioning well,'' despite a wave of departures in the past few
months.
   As the No. 2 official at the agency, Christensen will be in
charge this week at the Justice Department with Meese leaving on a
three-day trip to Munich, West Germany, for a meeting with law
enforcement officials.
   Asked whether he had any reservations when first approached
about coming to the department in view of Meese's ongoing legal
problems, Christensen told reporters: ``I had no qualms then and I
don't have any today.''
   Christensen is filling the post on an acting basis pending the
Senate confirmation process and said he thinks it unlikely he will
wind up running the Justice Department.
   While he has not discussed Meese's plans with the attorney
general, ``my personal perception'' is that he will ``stay through
Jan. 20 ... the attorney general will complete the Reagan
administration,'' Christensen said.
   On Monday night, Meese left open the possibility that he may
resign before Labor Day, but said he first wants to respond to
allegations concerning his ties to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
and a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline project.
   Independent counsel James McKay, who has been conducting a
criminal investigation of Meese for the past year, is expected to
issue a report this month raising questions about Meese's ethical
conduct. The questions are to be referred to the Justice
Department's Office of Professional Responsibility for review.
   Christensen said ``I have no intention'' of meeting with former
Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and ex-criminal division chief
William Weld, who resigned in protest March 29 over Meese's
continued tenure.
   ``I just want to discharge the responsibilities of my job, which
I perceive as day-to-day administration of the Justice Department
under the direction of General Meese,'' said Christensen, a Utah
trial lawyer.
</TEXT>
