<HEAD>AM-Lilly-Cocaine,560</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Calls Lilly Decision on Herbicide a Setback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eli Lilly & Co. has dealt a serious setback to
the Reagan administration's anti-cocaine program by refusing to
allow use of a ``safe and effective herbicide'' against
coca-producing areas in South America, the State Department said
Wednesday.
   ``We think the short-term impact is serious,'' said State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley, alluding to Lilly's decision
last week not to sell to the U.S. government the herbicide
tebuthurion in a coca eradication campaign focused mainly in Peru's
Huallaga Valley.
   She said the firm, which is the sole manufacturer of the
chemical, should reconsider its decision in light of the serious
cocaine problem in the United States. On Capitol Hill, Rep. Glenn
English, D-Okla., expressed outrage over Lilly's decision.
   The Indianapolis-based company gave no reason for its decision
in making the announcement last week, citing only ``a number of
practical and policy considerations.''
   But Mrs. Oakley told reporters Lilly apparently was worried
about possible retaliatory measures by ``traffickers or
terrorists.'' The company also had come under pressure from
environmentalists who were concerned about the ecological impact of
the herbicide.
   Mrs. Oakley said the State Department would have preferred to
have worked with the company on resolving its security concerns.
   She said the United States and Latin American governments have
been conducting field tests to identify a safe, effective herbicide
for use against coca for several years.
   Tebuthurion, known informally as ``Spike,'' was considered to be
among the safest and most effective, but no final decision had been
made about which herbicide should be used, Mrs. Oakley said.
   ``According to our information the safety and effectiveness of
spike has been clearly demonstrated and defended by the company.
Numerous environmental tests have been carried out in compliance
with federal regulations,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, Ann B. Wrobleski, assistant secretary of state for
international narcotics matters, said Lilly made the decision even
though the herbicide has been manufactured for more than 15 years,
has been proven safe by U.S. standards and is widely available in
this country for projects such as clearing brush for rights of way.
   The chemical is sold to other government agencies including the
Interior Department's Bureau of Land Management, she said.
   Testifying before a House Government Operations subcommittee
assessing the war on drugs, Ms. Wrobleski said State Department
lawyers are researching whether to propose legislation that would
compel Lilly to sell the State Department the chemical ``in the
vital national interests of the United States government.''
   The safety of Lilly's employees must be weighed against public
concerns about ``the 5 million regular users of cocaine and our
desperate need for a chemical solution to widespread coca
cultivation in the Andes,'' she said.
   English, chairman of the subcommittee, said he was ``stunned and
outraged'' at Lilly and called the company a ``deserter'' in the
war on drugs. He insisted that company representatives appear
before his panel to explain their decision.
   ``We're going to go to any length possible to get our hands on''
the herbicide for use in spraying programs in Peru, Bolivia and
Colombia, Ms. Wrobleski said.
   She said coca crops currently are destroyed by chopping them
down, a slow process that eradicates less than 1 percent of the
total.
   ``Unless we push the chemical button, we cannot dent that
problem appreciably,'' Ms. Wrobleski said.
</TEXT>
