<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArmSevered     06-01 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arm Severed,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine-Hour Operation to Reattach Boy's Arm Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeons Wednesday gave up trying to reattach
a 5-year-old boy's right arm, torn off at the shoulder, concluding
after nine hours in the operating room that the damage to the limb
and shoulder was too great.
   Fidencio Jaurequi, whose arm became caught in a farm machine
used to sort cherry tomatoes, was in critical condition at Tampa
General Hospital. He was expected to remain in the pediatric
intensive care unit several days.
   Three surgeons from the University of South Florida College of
Medicine spent from 3:15 p.m. Tuesday until 12:20 a.m. in the
operating room.
   ``Preliminary procedures had been performed,'' said Dr. Thomas
E. McKell, vice president of medical affairs. ``Regrettably, the
injury was so severe, with so much destruction of the tissue, that
it was not possible to rejoin the extremity.''
   The child, the son of Salvador and Eustolia Jaurequi of Dade
City, had gone to a barn at Singletary Farms where his mother was
working, according to a co-owner of the 75-acre vegetable farm.
   ``He stuck his arm into the machine'' and it got caught under
the conveyor belt on the roller, said Earl Singletary, who was
outside the barn when the accident occurred Tuesday.
   The severed limb was retrieved from the sorting machine.
   ``I had them put ice on his arm ... and I held a shirt up on his
arm _ that much I knew to do,'' Singletary said.
   Rescue workers arrived 13 minutes after the accident was
reported and packed the limb in ice and a saline solution, said
Pasco County Emergency Services Chief Derryl O'Neal.
   Less than 20 minutes after the accident, the boy and severed arm
were taken by helicopter 45 miles to Tampa General, O'Neal said.
   Three surgeons and three nurses from the hospital's microsurgery
team were called in.
   Singletary said Tuesday that the child should not have been in
the barn.
   ``We don't allow them in the tomato barn for just that reason,''
Singletary said. ``Little kids don't belong around farm machinery.
   ``We have a safety cut-off switch ... but it just happened so
fast,'' he said.
</TEXT>
