<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life for John Rambo seems to involve more
death with every adventure.
   Sylvester Stallone's character in ``Rambo III,'' a one-man
fighting machine who fends off an army of Soviets, includes 123
deaths and twice the violence of the previous ``Rambo'' movies, the
National Coalition of Television Violence said.
   The group this week condemned the ``glorification of war and
hatred'' in the 109-minute film.
   ``This film glorifies violence and will promote violent ways of
thinking and behaving in the millions of children, adolescents and
young adults who see this film,'' said coalition psychiatrist
Thomas Radecki.
   ``Rambo III,'' in which the hero goes to Afghanistan to rescue a
friend being held hostage, has grossed $21 million in its first six
days of release.
   Catherine Linclau, a publicist for Carolco Pictures, which
produced the film, was in a meeting Wednesday afternoon and
unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch says one of the five
lesions removed from his face proved to be cancerous, but it's not
threatening his health.
   ``The biopsy came back and one of the ridges removed is a basal
cell carcinoma which is not dangerous, doesn't have to be
treated,'' Koch said.
   The mayor said Tuesday he had spoken to Richard Green, a
dermatologist, who removed the lesions Friday. Koch said Green told
him ``hundreds of thousands of people have this.''
   The lesion, Koch said, had been over his right eye. The other
four proved negative, he added. Three of the lesions were caused by
the sun and two came from an inherited condition, he said.
   Koch said he spent the Memorial Day weekend at his sister's
house on Long Island and used a sunscreen to protect his face and
bald head.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Don Ameche finished filming ``Cocoon
II'' in Florida and returned to his Los Angeles-area home in time
for his 80th birthday.
   However, Ameche, who won an Oscar for his 1985 role in the
``Cocoon'' as an oldster who was transformed into a youngster,
didn't disclose how he spent his birthday on Tuesday.
   ``He has rejected any attention on his birthday,'' said
publicist Nick Stevens.
   ``Cocoon'' was Ameche's 50th screen appearance. As a 20th
Century Fox leading man in the 1930s and 1940s, Ameche was equally
popular in musicals, comedies and dramas.
   Previously, he gained his greatest fame from the title role in
``The Story of Alexander Graham Bell.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELLUNO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II plans to return to the
Italian Alps next month for a 10-day vacation in the town where he
spent a week last summer, the local bishop announced Wednesday.
   John Paul will stay in Lorenzago di Cadore, about 90 miles north
of Venice, said Belluno Bishop Maffeo Ducoli.
