<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSHotLine     06-01 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Hot Line,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hot Line Expands As Calls Accelerate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS hot line has
expanded from 130 operators to 220 to accommodate a rush of calls
generated in part by an educational pamphlet mailed to 10 million
U.S. homes, officials said.
   ``We're still in the beginning of the rush,'' said Carol
Humphries, coordinator for the National AIDS Hotline in Research
Triangle Park. ``Not everybody in the country has gotten the
pamphlet yet.''
   The government pamphlet ``Understanding AIDS'' forced hot line
officials to recruit operators through advertisements, flyers and
the news media.
   The 24-hour hot line, 1-800-342-AIDS, offers referrals in
English and Spanish for people seeking help in their areas for
acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Officials expect 2 million
calls in 1988.
   ``I think we're going to be at full capacity once we get
everyone trained,'' Ms. Humphries said. ``Things have been going
rather smoothly.''
   The hot line is run by the American Social Health Association
under contract with the U.S. Centers for Disease Control.
   AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving it defenseless to
many diseases. It is spread most often through sexual contact,
needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. There is no
known cure.
</TEXT>
