<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviets-Lawyers     06-01 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Lawyers,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Reportedly Barred From Attending Moscow Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has barred the entry of
several Israeli and British lawyers invited to a June 5-7 Moscow
conference on trade and human rights, a Jewish emigration group
said Wednesday.
   Yoram Dinstein, an Israeli expert on emigration, was listed on
the advance meeting schedule as the Western participant _ with two
Soviet lawyers _ in a public discussion of human rights, said Jerry
Goodman, director of the National Conference on Soviet Jewry.
   However, Soviet authorities did not grant visas to Dinstein and
three other Israeli legal experts and also barred several
prospective participants from Britain, including David Winter, a
lawyer who has visited the Soviet Union more than 35 times, Goodman
said.
   The Association of Soviet Lawyers and the London-based
International Bar Association are sponsoring the conference,
Goodman said.
   The National Conference on Soviet Jewry issued a statement
quoting the chairman of the group's lawyer's committee, Herbert
Teitelbaum, as saying Dinstein's absence ``will leave the human
rights session without a Western respondent, a situation which
simply cannot be tolerated in the age of purported `glasnost,''' or
openness.
   He said there would be a call for a boycott of the human rights
portion of the conference unless the Soviets grant visas to the
Israelis.
   ``This throwback to a hard-line `pre-glasnost' era is
troublesome, especially on the heels of the just completed
U.S.-Soviet summit meeting, which sought to develop a more
harmonious relationship in many areas,'' Teitelbaum said.
   A man who answered the telephone at the Soviet Embassy said no
spokesmen were available for comment.
</TEXT>
