<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Mine Explosion, 9th Ld-Writethru, a0756,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Explosion Kills 16 Miners, Traps 40</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with higher death toll, official saying
little hope of finding other survivors. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through a coal
shaft in central West Germany today, killing at least 16 miners and
trapping 40 of their comrades more than 300 feet underground.
   ``There is little hope that other miners can be found alive,''
said Gottfried Milde, the Hesse state interior minister.
   ``It's horrible, my husband is down there!'' said Ingrid Henke,
35. ``My daughters are aged just one and two.''
   One woman who would not give her name, but said her husband was
not in the shaft, said: ``All the women in this part of town are
doing their best to comfort each other.''
   Mayor Bernd Hessler of Borken told a news conference Wednesday
night the bodies of 16 miners had been found and the search
continued for about 40 others.
   What caused the blast had not been determined. Some reports said
explosives stored in the shaft detonated and others said it was due
to a buildup of coal dust.
   ``I have no real hopes. I think we'll have to bury a lot of
people,'' said Klaus Hausmann, a mechanic who has worked at the
mine for 20 years.
   Reports of the number of men trapped in the mine varied
throughout the day, with some officials putting it as high as 60
and others as low as 54. Milde said the total number, including the
confirmed dead, was 56.
   Rescue crews managed to get about 300 feet underground before
the shaft collapsed. ``This reduces the chance of finding many
survivors,'' a police spokesman who requested anonymity told
reporters.
   He said rescue crews were pumping oxygen into the shaft.
   Gerhard Heinz, an engineer for mine owner Preussen Elektra, said
the explosion occurred in a pit between 200 and 450 feet below
ground. Preussen Elektra of Hanover is one of the largest utility
companies in West Germany.
</TEXT>
