<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDS-ScienceAcademy     06-01 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Science Academy,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Says Anti-Discrimination Law Critical To AIDS Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a National Academy of Sciences
committee on AIDS said Wednesday that federal legislation shielding
carriers of the virus from discrimination is crucial to fighting
the epidemic.
   Calling that ``the first of equals'' among several other
recommendations in a new report, Theodore Cooper said providing
adequate protection against discrimination would form the
foundation for many other things that need to be done, such as
expanded voluntary testing for the virus.
   The Reagan administration opposes federal anti-discrimination
laws to protect AIDS carriers, and such protections were dropped
recently from AIDS legislation working its way through Congress.
   Cooper, who is also chairman and chief executive officer of The
Upjohn Co., acknowledged that winning passage will not be easy. He
said the solution is to ``get the message to the attention of both
the president and Congress, reiterate it and make it strong
enough.''
   He called such a federal law banning discrimination
``fundamental to the success of the program'' to combat AIDS.
   Cooper said the need for strong guidance on such basic policy
areas as discrimination legislation is one reason the committee
recommended creation of a new high-level AIDS commission to replace
the White House panel that goes out of business later this month.
   Robin Weiss, staff director of the academy's AIDS committee,
noted that the report issued Wednesday ``places much greater
emphasis on expanded voluntary testing'' than a 1986 report _ in
part as a way to get a better handle on the extent to which the
virus has spread.
   Such an expansion, she added, ``rests on comfort of people being
protected against discrimination'' if they test positive.
   Indeed, a major new element in the updated report _ a joint
project of the academy and its Institute of Medicine _ is a call
for revising the definition of AIDS as a disease to include the
hundreds of thousands of Americans unknowingly infected with the
virus.
   The committee's recommendation to focus on the numbers of those
infected with the virus _ rather than actual AIDS cases reported _
reflected what the panel said was a growing consensus that ``the
vast majority of persons'' with the virus ``will eventually
progress to AIDS if no treatment is found to slow or halt the
progression of the infection.''
   The Centers for Disease Control estimates that as many as 1.4
million Americans are infected with the virus.
   The report said evidence is now ``scientifically conclusive''
that the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, is what causes AIDS.
   The panel said many people infected with the virus suffer from
``clinical syndromes and laboratory test abnormalities that signal
the presence of disease but do not meet'' technical guidelines for
being listed as either AIDS or AIDS-Related Complex, known as ARC.
   ``The committee believes that the term ARC is no longer useful,
either from a clinical or a public health perspective, and that HIV
infection itself should be considered a disease,'' said the report.
   ``Viewing HIV infection as a disease is important because it may
eventually be amenable to treatment and patients will need to be
diagnosed and treated as early as possible.
   ``Clinically, it is more accurate to describe HIV infection as a
continuum of conditions associated with immune dysfunction,'' it
said. ``From a public health perspective the important event is
infection rather than full-blown disease because even asymptomatic
infected persons are capable of infecting others.''
   The report also called for development of federal standards for
labs doing AIDS testing and spelled out that the only mandatory
AIDS testing the committee backs is that involving the donation of
blood and organs for transplant.
   In the section calling for a new AIDS commission, the committee
singled out Surgeon General C. Everett Koop for ``continuing superb
leadership'' and cited biomedical researchers, the CDC and Food and
Drug Administration as ``areas of progress'' within the federal
government.
   ``Nevertheless, the committee has concluded that the federal
response has been too uneven,'' it said.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus
most often is spread through close contact with blood, blood
products or semen from infected persons.
   As of May 23, AIDS had been diagnosed in about 62,740 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 35,188 have died since June 1981,
according to the CDC. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
