<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     06-01 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Envoy Says Noriega Not Strengthened by Collapse of Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's chief negotiator
in efforts to oust Panamanian ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
said Wednesday that Noriega has not been strengthened by the
collapse of the talks last week.
   ``I don't think he's stronger by any means,'' said Michael
Kozak, a deputy assistant secretary of state dispatched to talk to
Noriega and other Panamanian officials in recent weeks.
   ``He's not on a winning curve right now. He's treading water.
That's something that's not gone away, and it's not going away,''
Kozak told the House Foreign Affairs Western Hemisphere
subcommittee.
   ``General Noriega is a pretty skillful guy ... It's not a stable
situation for him,'' he said.
   Kozak, in his first public appearance since the talks began,
commented only generally on the situation in Panama and declined to
answer specific questions in open session about deals the United
States had offered Noriega or even how many times he had met
personally with the military chief.
   Kozak deferred giving his answers until a closed-door meeting of
the subcommittee immediately after the public session, saying he
had given his word to Noriega that the negotiations would be
confidential.
   He said only that the discussions were not aimed at dictating
the composition of the Panamanian government or the role of the
Panamanian Defense Forces, which Noreiga heads.
   Those ``were issues to be decided by Panamanians, perhaps with
Latin American mediation, but not by the United States,'' Kozak
said.
   ``We continue to discuss with a number of governments in Latin
America the efforts they and we can undertake in pursuit of the
goal of re-establishing constitutional government in Panama,'' he
said.
   Kozak also declined to say specifically what other Latin
American countries were doing to help persuade Noriega to
relinquish power, although he said there is strong support
generally for the effort.
   ``A number of Latin American countries'' are sending their own
emissaries to talk to Noriega, he said. ``There is a fair degree of
solidarity.''
   Asked by subcommittee members to comment on rumors that Noreiga
has been able to cling to power because he has adverse information
used to pressure U.S. officials, including Vice President George
Bush, Kozak said he had no evidence that such information exists.
   ``He has said nothing to me about any information on the vice
president or anything else. As far as I know, there's nothing to
it,'' he said.
   Kozak said there is a danger that the United States might appear
too impatient to be rid of Noriega, and conceded it had been a
mistake to promote the belief that the problem could be solved
quickly.
   ``American impatience emboldens him,'' he said of Noriega.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
