<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SpellingBee 3rdLd-Writethru a0719 06-01 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spelling Bee, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0719,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifty-Six Eliminated in First 3 Rounds</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: First 5 grafs new with 3rd round results, picks up 3rd graf
pvs, bgng: ``As the ...''; SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng: ``It includes
...'' to eliminate redundant first reference to Awilda Cintron;
Picks up 17th graf pvs, bgng: ``Although contest ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-six competitors were eliminated in the
first day of the National Spelling Bee today, a contest in which,
for once, it wasn't just the children who made the mistakes.
   The 61st annual renewal of the competition began with a record
field of 200 contestants. During the third round _ the last of the
day _ 43 of them misspelled their way into elimination.
   Among those making errors were 13-year-old Awilda M. Cintron of
Ceiba, Puerto Rico, who did not begin learning to speak English
until the third grade.
   The eighth-grader misspelled the word strisciando, a musical
direction to play in a slurred, smooth manner.
   As the competition's second round began, bee officials began
handing to reporters a list of the words that had been asked during
the first round.
   But the distribution ceased when a reporter pointed out to a
tournament official that the list misspelled the word
``hitchhike.'' On the list, the word was spelled ``hitchike.''
   ``It was a typing error,'' said bee spokeswoman Susan H. Miller.
   The first entrant to drop out of the tournament was Monekia L.
Gause, 11, of Shallotte, N.C., who misspelled the word ``jargon.''
   The sixth-grader spelled it ``j-a-r-g-i-n.'' Told she had
misspelled the word, she tugged at the sleeves of her pink dress
and left the stage.
   ``I never heard it before,'' Monekia said afterward.
   The first round's only other dropout was Brian Yates, 11, of
Mentor, Ohio, who responded ``hitchhick'' when asked to spell
``hitchhike.''
   The bee has attracted its usual field of gifted children with
enough academic achievements to humble most adults, including its
youngest competitor ever.
   She is Iris Liu, a third-grader from Muncie, Ind., who doesn't
turn nine until June 20.
   Iris, whose parents immigrated to the United States from Taiwan
in 1979 and now own a bookstore, enjoys reading books in English
and Chinese when she isn't pursuing one of her other loves: jumping
rope.
   ``Not really,'' she said Tuesday evening when asked if she was
nervous.
   But as if to show that she's only human, she expressed
uncertainty about her chances of winning the bee, saying, ``They
have some funny words in there.''
   This year's field consists of 102 girls and 98 boys from 47
states, the District of Columbia, Guam, Puerto Rico, the Virgin
Islands and Mexico.
   It includes Maxwell T. Kelley, 14, of Oroville, Wash., who
received no formal institutional schooling until the third grade,
according to the bee's biographical booklet.
   Although contest rules allow children who are not yet 16 and
have not progressed beyond the eighth grade, no one competing in
the two-day event is 15 years old yet.
   Last year's winner was Stephanie Petit, an eighth-grader from
Bethel Park, Pa., who correctly spelled ``staphylococci,'' a type
of bacteria. It took 876 words to eliminate the 184 other entrants
in the 1987 bee.
   The 13-year-old Stephanie, like all previous winners, was not
allowed to re-enter the competition. But there are 20 contestants
making their second appearances, and two who are competing for a
third time: Bernard D. Noveloso, 13, of Grand Blanc, Mich., and
Clint W. Taylor, 14, of Durant, Okla.
   The contestants were culled from an estimated 8 million to 9
million competitors nationwide.
   The final authority for words used in the contest is Webster's
Third New International Dictionary, copyright in 1986, and its
addenda section.
   The contest, sponsored by Scripps Howard newspapers, offers
$1,500 plus other prizes to the winner, $1,000 to the second place
finisher, $750 for third place, $500 for fourth, $400 for fifth,
$300 for sixth, $200 each for seventh through 10th, $100 for 11th
through 20th, and $50 to each of the remaining 180 competitors.
</TEXT>
