<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Rights-Arms     06-01 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Rights-Arms,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Muted Rights Comments May Be Aimed At Cut In Europe
Forces</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By muting his criticism of Soviet human rights
abuses, President Reagan may be trying to speed up negotiations
that would substantially cut Red Army forces in Eastern Europe.
   Reagan, who built a political career bashing Reds and in his
first term called the Soviet Union an ``evil empire,'' confounded
observers on Tuesday and Wednesday by attributing Kremlin human
rights abuses to bureaucratic inertia and praising Mikhail S.
Gorbachev for trying to reform it.
   Reagan and his aides attributed the softening of the president's
rhetoric to Gorbachev's efforts to reform the system.
   But the answer to the riddle may lie in Reagan's often-stated
preference for ``quiet diplomacy'' and the link that U.S. officials
have established between human rights and the professed desired of
both sides to reduce conventional arms in Europe.
   Gorbachev, at the opening of the summit on Sunday night,
repeated to Reagan his 1986 proposal for cuts of 500,000 soldiers
in the opposing armies of the North Atlantic Treaty Alliance and
the Kremlin-led Warsaw Pact.
   Nice idea, said the Americans, but such reductions must come
through negotiations involving all the allies on both sides, and
the ideal forum is the Conference on Security and Cooperation in
Europe now under way in Vienna.
   Those talks grew out of the 1975 Helsinki Accords, in which the
Soviets pledged to observe human rights. For 13 years the United
States has accused the Kremlin of violating the accords, and Soviet
officials are now conceding as much, releasing political prisoners
and allowing greater public discussion of formerly taboo subjects.
   Many Americans, including Sen. Sam Nunn., D-Ga., chairman of the
Senate Armed Services Committee, believe that sharp reductions in
conventional forces should accompany the 30 percent to 50 percent
cuts in long-range nuclear missiles envisioned in the proposed
Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
   From the American point of view, the main objectives of reducing
conventional arms would be a reduction in the 2-to-1 advantage the
Warsaw Pact holds on tanks and a reduction in the 380,000 Red Army
troops in East Germany.
   Although the edge may have dulled on Reagan's anti-Communist
rhetoric, his schedule was designed to emphasize U.S. concern with
human rights: he met with nearly 100 Soviet dissidents at the
residence of the American ambassador, he pointedly praised the
virtues of American democracy at every turn, he chatted with with
writers, artists and students.
   And U.S. officials let it be known that Reagan had canceled a
meeting with the Zieman family of Jewish refuseniks because a
high-ranking Soviet official had warned that a visit to their home
would kill their application to emigrate.
   Much of the hardball was being played behind the scenes, said a
senior administration official, noting that the American and the
Soviet regularly but quietly were engaged in discussion of human
rights issues.
   The president's statements would be hard to explain, unless
there was something going on behind the scenes. And his spoken
words were particularly puzzling in light of his extra-curricular
activities at the summit, which appeared designed to focus
attention on Soviet human rights policy, especially the
difficulties that Jews face in emigrating.
   But on Tuesday, Reagan told students at Moscow State University
that recalcitrant bureaucrats were to blame for Soviet human rights
abuses. And under pointed questioning at a news conference on
Wednesday, Reagan said similar problems could be found everywhere.
   ``I just have to believe that in any sort of government some of
us do find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy,'' Reagan said.
   And after four days of talks with Gorbachev, he expressed
confidence that the Kremlin leader was trying and would succeed in
improving the situation.
   Soviet human rights activists attributed Reagan's comments on
human rights to naivete.
   ``The bureaucracy has nothing to do with it,'' said Tanya
Zieman, whose family had waited in vain for Reagan's visit on
Sunday.
   Reagan and his aides may have been calculating that, having made
their views known in Moscow, they should tone down the rhetoric in
hopes of winning long-sought cuts in Soviet conventional forces in
Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITORS: Bryan Brumley, a Washington-based national security
reporter for The Associated Press, has been covering U.S.-Soviet
affairs since 1981, when he was a correspondent in Moscow.
</TEXT>
