<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-ANightOut 3rdLd-Writethru a0785 06-01 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-A Night Out, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0785,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Over, Gorbachevs Take Reagans to Bolshoi Ballet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New in first 5 grafs with Reagans taking evening stroll
through Red Square. Picks up 3rd graf pvs bgng: Reagan and ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their summit business over, President and Mrs.
Reagan spent their last night in Moscow at the Bolshoi Ballet,
dined privately with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his
wife and took an impromptu walk through Red Square.
   After ballet and a 2{-hour dinner Wednesday at a state-owned
dacha in a verdant area just outside Moscow, the Reagans stopped at
Red Square and walked across the cobblestone plaza between St.
Basil's Cathedral and the Kremlin.
   Reagan, holding hands with his wife, described his Soviet
evening on the town as ``wonderful ... very warm and hospitable.''
   He said the couple decided to stop at Red Square ``because Nancy
hasn't seen it. We're leaving tomorrow and I didn't want her to
miss it.''
   Earlier, the Gorbachevs and Reagans shared the royal box in the
world-famous Bolshoi Theater for 90 minutes of ballet. Many in the
audience of about 2,000 people waved and applauded when they
arrived at the opulent red and gold theater, and again before they
departed.
   Reagan and Gorbachev sat next to each other, even moving their
seats closer together as the ballet began, and clasped arms around
each other's waists briefly as they left the theater.
   By contrast, Mrs. Reagan and Raisa Gorbachev, whose relationship
was described by the president's wife as a ``Mexican standoff,''
seemed cool and did not speak. Mrs. Reagan, dressed in a short
white dress and pearls, sat by Gorbachev's side and Mrs. Gorbachev,
wearing blue, sat next to Reagan.
   It was the first non-political evening the Reagans have enjoyed
in three consecutive days of summitry. The Gorbachevs gave a
toast-filled state dinner for their guests Monday night, and Reagan
returned the favor with a dinner for the Gorbachevs at Spaso House,
the U.S. ambassador's residence.
   The royal box in the Bolshoi Theater was draped with U.S. and
Soviet flags, and the orchestra played the national anthems of both
countries. Reagan mouthed the words to the American national
anthem, and Mrs. Reagan held her hand to her heart.
   The Reagans both used opera glasses to watch the Bolshoi Ballet
perform excerpts from ``Sleeping Beauty,'' ``Swan Lake'' and
``Romeo and Juliet.'' The last was performed by Nine Ananiashvili
and Andris Liepa, winners of a 1986 world ballet competition in
Jackson, Miss.
   When it was over, the dancers applauded the superpower leaders
from the stage.
   The Bolshoi Theater, founded in 1776, has six tiers of box
seats. It was the first permanent theater in Moscow, and its ballet
and opera companies gained an international reputation in the 1950s
and 1960s.
   Tickets cost about three rubles ($5) but are nearly impossible
for Soviets to obtain without contacts in the theater or luck
enough to receive an allocation at their jobs.
</TEXT>
