<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Moynihan-McMillan     06-01 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moynihan-McMillan,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Island Lawyer Officially Begins Campaign Against Moynihan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican attorney Robert McMillan
announced his candidacy Wednesday for the U.S. Senate seat held by
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan since 1976.
   McMillan, 55, promised to run an aggressive campaign against the
61-year-old Moynihan, who's seeking a third term this November, and
stress issues such as day care for working families, garbage
disposal and acid rain that the Republican maintained concern New
Yorkers most.
   ``I know I have an uphill battle, but I have one thing in my
favor _ the issues,'' McMillan said at a news conference. ``For too
long, the Democrat senator from New York has chosen to ignore the
problems that confront the average family in the state.''
   He will be formally designated the Republican candidate during a
meeting next week in New York City of the state's GOP committee,
according to party Executive Director Edward Lurie.
   McMillan is an attorney in the influential Garden City law firm
of Rivkin, Radler, Dunne & Bayh.
   A one-time football player at Adelphi University and bronze star
recipient during the Korean War, McMillan worked on Richard Nixon's
1960 presidential campaign. He also worked in 1964 and 1965 for
Nixon when the former president was a private citizen.
   His only attempt at elective office came in 1964, when he was
defeated easily in a special election for a New York City council
seat.
   McMillan said he has received assurances of help from Vice
President George Bush's campaign in New York.
</TEXT>
