<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0741 06-01 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Commander Says Iran Building New Silkworm Missile Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT one graf after 9th graf pvs, ``Investigators found ..
., UPDATING with U.N. development. Picks up 10th graf pvs, In other
... with minor editing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS CORONADO, Persian Gulf (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran is still a threat
despite military setbacks and is building a new missile site that
threatens the entire Strait of Hormuz, the U.S. commander for the
Middle East said Wednesday.
   Gen. George B. Crist said construction of the Silkworm site was
one reason for deploying a sophisticated U.S. Aegis-type missile
cruiser in the Persian Gulf with long-range air surveillance and
weapons systems.
   He said the ship is ``a quantum leap forward in our ability to
handle that threat'' in Hormuz, the gulf's narrow gateway.
   Iran remains a formidable presence in the gulf despite losing
six naval craft April 18 in clashes with the U.S. Navy, Crist said.
The four-star Marine general heads the Central Command based in
Tampa, Fla., administrative headquarters for U.S. military
activities in 19 countries of the Middle East and North Africa.
   Tehran has been ``very circumspect and careful'' since April 18,
he said, ``but I don't get any feeling that the Iranians have run
up a white flag or that sort of thing. I would not say they have
given up their thoughts about trying to get to us.''
   In an interview with members of a Pentagon news media pool on
the Coronado, the Navy flagship in the gulf, Crist also said:
   _Military analysts determined ``no enemy missiles'' were
launched at three U.S. warships in the Strait of Hormuz during the
fighting April 18, despite reports from shipboad officers that five
were fired. The confusion resulted from multiple radar contacts of
missiles and bombs from U.S. forces, ``and what you were getting
was hits on the system as they picked up seekers and missiles
moving through the air.''
   _A U.S. Navy H-2 helicopter from the destroyer O'Brien took
``evasive action'' to avoid a missile fired by the U.S. missile
frigate Jack Williams. ``It obviously wasn't hit, so there's a
little bit of mystery as to who was firing at what.''
   _Investigators found no evidence that a Marine Corps helicopter
gunship lost later in the day was shot down, as Iran claims. ``We
don't know and probably never will'' know the cause of the crash.
   In New York, diplomats at the United Nations said Iran agreed to
hold more U.N. talks on ending the gulf war but repeated that Iraq
must be branded the aggressor as the first step toward peace. The
diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, provided a copy of a
letter from Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, dated Tuesday, stating
Iranian conditions.
   In other developments Wednesday, the death toll rose from one to
two in a mine explosion Tuesday that destroyed a fishing boat in
the Gulf of Oman off the United Arab Emirates. Lloyd's Shipping
Intelligence Unit in London said a second vessel was damaged.
   A net apparently dredged the mine up from the seabed. Shipping
executives said six fishermen were injured but it was not known if
the second dead man had been included in that total.
   The mine exploded near a busy tanker anchorage just south of the
entrance to Hormuz, near where Soviet warships and tankers stop and
north of the usual staging area for American-flag Kuwaiti tankers
and their U.S. Navy escorts.
   Crist said the new Iranian missile site at Kuhestak, overlooking
central Hormuz, is a fixed installation rather than using mobile
launchers as Iran has done in the past.
   He said it might become operational in late summer, ``but that's
a guess. It could be used anytime. They're building one hell of a
big Silkworm site down there, and they've got Silkworms.''
   From Kuhestak, all the inner strait and the northern tip of the
Oman peninsula would be within the Silkworm range of 50-60 miles.
   The Silkworm, officially known as the HY-2, is a Chinese version
of the 30-year-old subsonic Soviet Styx. Although crude by modern
standards, it can be devastating to ships.
   U.S. officials are on record as saying they would respond with
force if any U.S. vessel was fired on or even tracked by a Silkworm
battery's radar.
   There are no signs of work progressing on another suspected
Silkworm site, on Abu Musa island in the southern Gulf, Crist said.
   Silkworms on Abu Musa would threaten the main gulf shipping
lanes and the United Arab Emirates coast. ``Clearly we were
concerned. So we watched it like a hawk, and nothing happened,''
Crist said.
   He said assignment of the Aegis-type missile cruiser USS
Vincennes to the gulf provides ``a much greater surveillance
capability.'' The 9,400-ton vessel arrived during the past week
from San Diego.
   With its state-of-the-art long-range air surveillance radar
system ``we can see a lot farther,'' Crist said, and the Vincennes
also has ``excellent capability'' against Silkworms.
   ``So if they decided to use those missiles over there, Aegis
really represents a quantum leap forward in our ability to handle
that threat,'' he said.
</TEXT>
