<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-Indecency     06-01 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Indecency,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadcasters, First Amendment Groups Challenge Rules on Indecency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of broadcasters and other First
Amendment advocates told a federal appeals court panel Wednesday
that the government's rules on indecent broadcasts are
unconstitutionally vague.
   Attorney Timothy B. Dyk said the groups do not challenge the
Federal Communications Commission's authority to govern indecency
on the air, but he said the FCC's policy does not give broadcasters
a clear idea what they can air without fear of sanctions.
   ``What we would like is some guidance'' on what can be
broadcast, he told a panel of three U.S. Court of Appeals judges.
``Broadcasters do not want to risk their licenses.''
   The result of the FCC's policy has been to chill fully protected
speech, Dyk said.
   The FCC in April 1987 cracked down on indecent broadcasts with a
new policy that went beyond simply prohibiting the ``seven dirty
words'' that comedian George Carlin once used in a radio broadcast.
His monologue led to a 1978 Supreme Court decision on indecency.
   The agency said it would enforce the Supreme Court's definition
of indecency: ``language or material that depicts or describes, in
terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary community
standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory activities
or organs.''
   The FCC said broadcasts that fit that definition, and not just
programs that used the ``seven dirty words,'' could be subject to
sanctions unless the programs were broadcast after midnight, when
children were not likely to be in the audience.
   The policy serves ``the government's compelling and well
established interest in protecting children's exposure to salacious
material,'' said Diane Killory, FCC general counsel.
   Killory said the decision to set aside the early morning hours
after midnight as ``safe harbor'' represents ``a balancing of a
number of interests'' and ``doesn't lend itself to a precise
mathematical formula.''
   Judge Ruth Ginsburg said the FCC's evidence on the number of
children in the late-night radio audience appeared to be
``flimsy,'' but Killory countered that ``even with all the
resources in the world ... it would still come down to a judgment
call.''
   Killory said the commission's policy was aimed at helping
protect minors from indecent material but was not designed to
displace parents as the primary protectors of children.
   ``It would be unrealistic to assume parents can supervise their
children at all hours of the day and night,'' Killory said.
   Among the groups joining the petition challenging the FCC's
policy are Capital Cities-ABC, CBS, National Broadcasting Co., the
National Association of Broadcasters, Action for Children's
Television, Public Broadcasting Service, National Public Radio, The
New York Times, The Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press
and People for the American Way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
