<DOCNO> AP880601-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Glance     06-01 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Glance,0446</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Includes AM-AIDS-Monkeys, a0793; AM-AIDS-Antibodies, a0847;
AM-AIDS-Hotline, a0813; AM-AIDS-Science Academy, a0825.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the latest developments on the AIDS front:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-MONKEYS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS virus probably did not jump from
monkeys to humans but could have infected the common ancestors of
humans and monkeys millions of years ago, researchers say.
   Japanese biologists who have determined the entire genetic code
of the AIDS virus that infects African green monkeys found that the
monkey AIDS virus differed from the two known human AIDS viruses.
If the virus had jumped from monkeys to humans in recent times, as
some have suggested, the viruses would be identical or nearly so.
   The findings appear in Thursday's issue of the British
scientific journal Nature.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-ANTIBODIES</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers studying four AIDS-infected men who
appeared to stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease
said the virus may have stopped reproducing in those patients.
   Tests to pinpoint AIDS are based upon detection of the
antibodies produced by the body to fight the virus. But Alfred J.
Saah, epidemiology professor at the Johns Hopkins School of Public
Health, said the findings do not imply increased dangers of blood
supply contamination, since the instances of AIDS victims who stop
producing detectable antibodies to the disease are ``very, very
rare.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-HOTLINE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS hotline has expanded
from 130 operators to 220 to accommodate a rush of calls generated
in part by a government educational pamphlet ``Understanding AIDS''
mailed to 10 million U.S. homes, officials said.
   The 24-hour hotline, 1-800-342-AIDS, offers referrals in English
and Spanish for people seeking help in their areas for acquired
immune deficiency syndrome. Officials expect 2 million calls in
1988.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-SCIENCE ACADEMY</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Academy of Sciences committee on
AIDS said federal legislation shielding carriers of the virus from
discrimination is crucial to fighting the epidemic.
   The report also said the hundreds of thousands of Americans
unknowingly infected with the virus should be considered as
suffering from the disease even if they don't have full-scale AIDS.
The panel said there is a growing consensus that ``the vast
majority of persons'' with the virus ``will eventually progress to
AIDS if no treatment is found to slow or halt the progression of
the infection.''
   The report called for development of federal standards for labs
doing AIDS testing and recommended that AIDS testing be mandatory
only in cases involving donations of blood or organs for transplant.
</TEXT>
