<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EastStLouisWoes     06-01 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East St Louis Woes,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Meets Most Of Payroll, But Some City Employees Still Waiting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infusion of state money enabled
this financially strapped city to pay most of its 300 workers
Wednesday, five days after their paychecks were due, the city's
treasurer said.
   But city Treasurer Charlotte Moore said unless Mayor Carl E.
Officer authorized the transfer of additional funds into the city's
general revenue account, about 30 city employees would not get paid
for a few days more.
   Officer was in a meeting and could not be reached for comment,
his office said.
   On Wednesday morning, Mrs. Moore said, the town received its
regular quarterly personal property tax payment from the state
totaling $93,464. The payment supplemented money already on hand
and allowed it to meet most of its $274,000 bimonthly payroll.
   But Mrs. Moore said East St. Louis still was $55,000 short of
being able to pay all workers.
   ``We'll pay all police, all firefighters, all public works
employees and then we'll go from there,'' she said. The checks were
issued early in the afternoon, she said.
   The remaining employees might have to wait a few days for their
paychecks until the city's regular state sales tax payment arrives,
she said, unless the mayor authorizes the transfer of motor fuel
tax funds into the payroll account, a move that a state official
said could jeopardize future state support.
   Employees in this Mississippi River town of 55,000 were supposed
to be paid this past Friday. It was the second time in less than a
month that paychecks were delayed.
   Though Officer could not be reached by The Associated Press, he
told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch on Tuesday that there was enough
money in the city's various bank accounts to cover the paychecks _
if the treasurer would cooperate and issue the checks. He did not
elaborate.
   Officer contended that the late paychecks were ``an unfortunate
situation that is not necessary'' and blamed Mrs. Moore, contending
that she was angry because her entire staff was laid off in April
to help save money.
   Mrs. Moore countered that Officer was upset because she was
enforcing sound accounting policies.
   Dale Klohr, spokesman for the state transportation department,
said that motor fuel tax funds could be used to pay city employees
who do road work but not for other employees. A transfer of motor
fuel funds for other workers would violate department guidelines,
and the department could withhold future motor fuel tax payments,
he said.
</TEXT>
