<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FormerHostage     06-01 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Former Hostage,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hostage Practices Urban Missionary Skills In Chicago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a year ago, Katherine Taylor trudged
through the rough terrain of Sudan, a captive of rebel soldiers.
   Now, she's giving out food and clothing to desperate people in
an urban ministry, in hopes of developing skills to use as a
Christian missionary in Mexico City.
   The 32-year-old Tennessee native, who went to Sudan to teach
English and work as a missionary, says the seven weeks she spent as
a hostage are behind, but not forgotten.
   ``A lot of people don't have certain freedoms and suffer a great
deal. It's one thing to know about it cognitively, but it's another
thing to experience a little of it yourself,'' Ms. Taylor said
Wednesday.
   She was kidnapped last July 7. She and her three fellow
hostages, including two Americans, were freed seven weeks later
thanks to appeals from former President Jimmy Carter and the U.S.
and Kenyan governments, Ms. Taylor said. After a 100-mile walk,
they arrived safely in Kenya on Aug. 25.
   Ms. Taylor remembers being roused from sleep in the middle of
the night by soldiers who claimed they were ``saving our lives.''
   The captors, members of the Sudanese People's Liberation Army,
planned to attack the village and did not want the three ``caught
in the cross-fire,'' Ms. Taylor said.
   The Sudanese rebels have waged a five-year civil war against the
government, which is dominated by Moslems from the predominantly
Arab northern section of the country.
   The Sudanese People's Liberation Army is fighting for government
reforms and autonomy for Sudan's three southern provinces, where
most people are Christian or animist.
   After packing malaria medicine, some first-aid supplies, a Bible
and a few other belongings, Ms. Taylor was led out of the house she
was living in at Bishop Gwynne College near the southern Sudanese
town of Mundri.
   Ms. Taylor said she and three other hostages were forced to walk
through the countryside of Sudan, the largest country in Africa.
   They slept on the side of the road or in rebel camps, ate
sporadically, drank bad water and trudged through waterways, she
recalled.
   ``Certain aspects of the physical parts were hard _ long walks
and bad water,'' she said. ``But the psychological parts were hard,
too ... not knowing how long we would be kept, not knowing what
each day was going to bring.''
   In October, Ms. Taylor arrived in Chicago to work with the
Circle Urban Ministries providing emergency food, clothing and
housing to poor people in the Austin neighborhood on the city's
rough West Side.
   Ms. Taylor said she and four friends are volunteering in the
urban mission as preparation for a missionary project they've been
planning for more than a decade.
   The five _ a nurse, an architect, two teachers and a
businessman-aviation mechanic _ plan to leave for Mexico City after
another year of training and language classes in Spanish.
   ``Our commitment to the Lord is the underlying thing,'' she said.
   ``Everything isn't rosy, but there's a commitment underneath it
_ ours is strong.''
   Ms. Taylor's mother, Martha Taylor of Johnson City, Tenn., said
in a telephone interview Wednesday that the first thing her
daughter wanted to do when she got home was eat broccoli.
   ``We really expected her to be different, but she was the same
old Katie,'' Mrs. Taylor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
