<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-Train     06-01 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-Train,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Collision Kills 2, Hurts 29 in Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger express train going more
than 70 mph rear-ended a sitting freight train Wednesday, killing
two people and injuring as many as 29, a Dutch railway spokesman
said.
   The four-car passenger train carrying about 60 passengers
derailed and tumbled down an embankment after hitting the
gravel-laden train in southwestern Netherlands at about 10:40 a.m.,
said spokesman Hans Meijer.
   He said the 39-year-old locomotive engineer of the passenger
train was killed, as was a 79-year-old Dutch woman, identified as
A. Sitter.
   Meijer said nine people were hospitalized, two in critical
condition, and up to 20 others were treated for minor injuries.
   The lead passenger car was left with one end sticking up in the
air, Meijer told The Associated Press in a telephone interview from
the railway's head office in this central Dutch city.
   He said the cause of the collision was not immediately known.
   The passenger train traveling at about 74 mph was bound from
Roosendaal, a major junction in the southern Netherlands about 60
miles south of Amsterdam, to Vlissingen in Zeeland province, the
railway spokesman said.
   Visibility was good at the site of the accident between the
stations of Rilland-Bath and Krabbendijke, where the double-track
Roosendaal-Vlissingen main line runs in a slight bend, according to
Meijer.
   He said the freight train was being used to try out a new energy
conservation method and the gravel cars were hooked up to the
electric engine as a simulated payload. The train was supposed to
start and stop three times, he said, adding that it was not clear
``why the engineer of the passenger train didn't see it, or whether
the signals failed.''
   The line has an automatic signaling system, according to the
spokesman.
   Wreckage blocked both tracks and considerable damage was done,
Meijer said.
</TEXT>
