<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-DragonMarch     06-01 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Dragon March,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satirical March Needles Jaruzelski; Two Activists Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of marchers in Wroclaw chanted
for a ``Revolution of the Dwarfs'' and likened Poland's leader to
an evil dragon Wednesday in a satirical observance of Child's Day,
opposition spokesmen said.
   ``We know nothing about it,'' said a police headquarters
spokesman in the southwestern city when asked for comment about the
public needling of Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   Parents and grandparents give small gifts to children on Child's
Day, which is observed in Poland each June 1.
   The Wroclaw march and rally was organized by Orange Alternative,
an opposition street theater group that stages frequent
``happenings'' lampooning the government.
   More than 10,000 people took part, said Barbara Labuda, a
spokeswoman for the banned Solidarity trade union in the city, and
Krzysztof Albin of Orange Alternative. They spoke by telephone from
Wroclaw.
   Albin said the main slogan was a call for a fairy-tale
``Revolution of the Dwarfs.'' He said marchers also chanted
``Jaruzelski, dragon of Wawel,'' referring to the dragon once said
to live under Wawel Castle in Krakow, and ``We want a jester
instead of little Wojciech.''
   Included in the chants were rhyming parodies of old Solidarity
anti-government slogans, Albin said.
   Marchers walked from the central market to a square about 15
blocks away, then another 15 blocks to a park on an island in the
Odra River, he said, with some people painting slogans on walls and
a police van en route.
   Police watched but did not arrest anyone, according to Albin.
   In another development Wednesday in Wroclaw, police freed two of
four activists accused of assaulting a factory guard May 5 during
labor unrest, said the wife of one of those still in jail.
   Alexandra Sarata and Jolanta Skiba were freed in response to a
plea by Roman Catholic Bishop Adam Dyczkowski, Maria Pinior said.
Her husband, Solidarity activist Jozef Pinior, and his associate
Czeslaw Borowszyk remain in jail, she said.
</TEXT>
