<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Protest     06-01 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Protest,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alternative Political Party Stages Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of members of a group that proclaims itself
an alternative to the Communist Party demonstrated downtown
Wednesday, demanding a multiparty political system and an end to
what they called political repression.
   The protest by members of the Democratic Union, a group formed
in Moscow last month, attracted a crowd of about 200 by a boulevard
near a statue of 19th-century Russian writer Nikolai Gogol.
   ``I think it was the first time there was a political meeting
without repression and I think it was because of the presence of
Mr. Reagan,'' Democratic Union member Yuri Mityunov said later in a
telephone interview.
   Several demonstrations daily have taken place in Moscow during
President Reagan's visit. None of them were broken up by police.
   Mityunov said the group, carrying banners, marched hundreds of
yards to the end of the boulevard and returned to the Gogol statue
in a 1{-hour demonstration.
   Police watched the group closely when it held meetings in Moscow
early in May. They arrested dissident journalist Sergei Grigoryants
shortly before he was to act as host at a final meeting of the
group.
   Grigoryants, accused of disobeying a police officer, served a
seven-day jail term.
</TEXT>
