<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0738 06-01 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Economic Consultants Embrace His Deficit-Fighting Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Darman, Feldstein comments in top 20 grafs,
picking up in 13th graf pvs, Many economists; deletes grafs 23-26
pvs, One of ... treasury secretary.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's ``flexible freeze''
plan to end the federal budget deficit by 1993 depends on an
optimistic outlook and a reduction in interest rates by at least 2
percentage points, his economic advisers said Wednesday.
   ``We all concluded that a flexible freeze is the right way to
go, that is indeed doable,'' said former Deputy Treasury Secretary
Richard Darman as Bush ended four days of private talks with
Republican leaders and advisers at his seaside vacation retreat.
   Darman said Bush would contrast his plan to the ``Massachusetts
mirage'' of Michael Dukakis, a slap at the Democratic
front-runner's references to a ``Massachusetts miracle'' of
home-state revival while he has been governor.
   Bush's plan also depends on a reduction in the budget deficit
that is occurring anyway and a fast-rising surplus in the nation's
Social Security trust fund, the consultants said.
   The vice president has said he would reduce the deficit by the
end of a first term by freezing most spending and without raising
any taxes.
   Martin Feldstein, who quit his job as President Reagan's chief
economist in 1985 because his advocacy of a tax increase was at
odds with White House policy, told reporters he was a convert to
the Bush proposal.
   If Bush is elected, financial markets will rally on the
assumption that the deficit will be attacked seriously, Feldstein
suggested.
   ``The markets will respond and bring down interest rates another
notch, 2 percentage points, and that will get us down and get us
within inches of budget balance in 1993,'' said Feldstein, a
Harvard economist.
   However, Bush's declarations that he would reject the advice of
a bipartisan commission studying the federal deficit if it should
call for a tax increase drew skepticism on Wednesday from one of
those he met with, Rep. Bill Frenzel.
   Frenzel, a Minnesota Republican and a member of the blue-ribbon
panel, said the commission's work would not be swayed by Bush's
comments.
   ``We are not going to get involved in any presidential
campaigns,'' Frenzel told reporters during a picture-taking session
Wednesday with the vice president.
   Bush interrupted Frenzel at one point, saying: ``I hope the
commission listens a little bit to the American people in this
election.''
   ``That's what I think an election is about. The commission can
take an objective look and come up with whatever it wants. I'd be
much more persuaded by what the American people say.''
   The National Economic Commission, made up of appointees of the
Reagan administration as well as members of both parties in
Congress, was formed earlier this year to try to come up with a
bipartisan package of deficit-reduction proposals.
   The panel, which will also include two members appointed by the
new president-elect in November, will submit its report in 1989.
   Democratic critics, as well as many private economists, argue
that it is unlikely the budget deficit, $150 billion last year, can
be eliminated without some form of new taxes.
   Bush's proposal calls for a ``flexible freeze'' that would keep
overall spending except for Social Security payments at levels in
the budget approved by Congress for fiscal year 1989, plus
inflation.
   The freeze would be flexible because some spending could go up,
but increases would have to be offset by identical reductions in
other areas.
   So far, Bush has not provided details on which programs he would
like to cut and which ones he would like to see expanded.
   The vice president, who has clinched the Republican nomination,
has also proposed a reduction in the tax on capital gains _ profits
from the sale of real estate, stocks or other assets _ to 15
percent from its current maximum of 28 percent.
   Many economists have suggested that Bush's proposals would not
go far enough in trimming the budget deficit.
   ``I'm not surprised that the Democrats would say that,'' Bush
said Wednesday. ``All they want to do is spend and tax. There is no
change I can see or hear out of the campaign that would lead you to
believe anything other than that on the Democratic side.''
   Bush held two days of talks on economic issues on Tuesday and
Wednesday. They followed similar discussions with outside advisers
last Friday and Saturday on other domestic issues.
   He has been at his retreat overlooking the Atlantic Ocean since
last Thursday and will remain here until Friday, combining strategy
and issues sessions with a vacation.
   Bush said that the economists who advised him assured him that
the U.S. economy was strong.
   On Wednesday, the Commerce Department reported that the Index of
Leading Indicators, a major guage of the country's economic health,
was up in April for the third consecutive month.
   Bush said that none of the half dozen private economists
visiting him foresaw a recession in the coming months.
   Bush who has frequently trumpted the 65-month economic expansion
as a sign of success for Reagan economic policies _ policies he
derided in 1980 as ``voodoo economics'' _ cautioned the Federal
Reserve Board on Tuesday not to do anything that would jeopardize
that expansion.
</TEXT>
