<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Homeless     06-01 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Homeless,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Remarks On Homeless Cause Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the homeless Wednesday criticized
President Reagan's remarks at a Moscow news conference defending
the nation's treatment of the homeless by citing the case of a
street woman who fought New York City's efforts to hospitalize her.
   They said Reagan inaccurately described the case of Joyce Brown,
the homeless woman who waged the much-publicized battle against the
city.
   Reagan's remarks came in response to a reporter's suggestion
that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev was not convinced by the
president's statements that serious human rights deficiencies did
not exist in America.
   He said he wished Gorbachev would visit the United States long
enough to correct the ``mistaken view about the things that
occasionally dominate the press, about prejudice, racial or
religious, in our country, about people, the so-called street
people who apparently have no place to live.''
   ``But I don't think he quite could understand a recent
situation: a young lady living on the sidewalks of New York, living
out there on the sidewalk, winter and summer, and so for her own
sake, the police picked her up to bring her to where she could be
placed in a shelter and she took her case to court and won her case
in court that she should be allowed to go back and sleep on the
sidewalk where she had been because that's what she preferred to do.
   ``Well, when you have a free country, how far can we go in
impinging on the freedom of someone who says this is the way I want
to live? I think we could straighten him out if he saw what we did
in our country.''
   Brown, also known as Billie Boggs, was taken off Second Avenue
in Manhattan last year under a city program regarding mentally
disturbed street people.
   Homeless who are believed to threaten the safety of others or
themselves are taken off the streets and put in a special ward of
Bellevue Hospital. They are not taken to a shelter, as the
president said.
   Brown, it was alleged, defecated on the street, shouted at
passers-by and burned money that was given to her.
   A judge ruled that Brown was competent to decide where she
should live. On appeal, she was found to be incompetent, but was
released when another judge found that the city could not force her
to take medication.
   She has not returned to the streets, but is receiving disability
payments and living at a private shelter for the homeless.
   ``Although I have my freedom, I still do not have adequate
housing. Why doesn't the president assist me in getting permanent
housing?'' Brown said in response to the president's remarks,
according to Norman Siegel, her attorney and executive director of
the New York Civil Liberties Union.
   He said she was ``hoping someone from the White House would call
and help her find an apartment.''
   Siegel said Brown's case showed that ``the system was forced to
work to protect her right to individual liberty, but it also served
(to show) in a broader context of the failure to provide adequate
housing.''
   ``Today, in America, there are thousands of homeless on the
streets'' and he attributed it to ``the failure of the Reagan
administration to provide meaningful programs.''
   Peter Smith, president of the Partnership for the Homeless,
which operates shelters in New York and elsewhere, also decried
Reagan's comments.
   ``The president's statement ... suggesting that the shameful
problem of growing homelessness in America is the result of what he
referred to as `street people' who are homeless by choice totally
ignores the fact that the vast majority of homelessness has been
caused by his own policies which have gutted the principal federal
programs to provide affordable housing for low-income and
moderate-income people,'' Smith said.
   ``The most authoritative national survey of 47 of our largest
cities shows that less than 7 percent of the homeless are so by
choice and most homeless are members of families who simply cannot
find affordable housing.''
   Edward Abrahams, associate director of the Coalition for the
Homeless in New York, agreed that Reagan had misrepresented the
homeless problem. Many of the homeless are families, he said; he
estimated there were 750,000 homeless children, and their average
age is 6.
   ``If Mr. Gorbachev was to visit this country, he wouldn't be
here long before he saw homeless people. He would see them at
Kennedy Airport, where he might arrive; he would see them living
across the street from the White House, where he would be
greeted,'' Abrahams said.
</TEXT>
