<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NBC-Wright     06-01 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC-Wright,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC President Warns Broadcast Rules Hampering Networks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government regulation is hobbling the three
major television broadcast networks in the face of unregulated
competition from the cable industry, the president of top-rated NBC
said Wednesday.
   ``Given the economics of the network business today, the
depressing fact is that you have to be the first-place network to
keep your head above water, because second- or third-place doesn't
do it for you anymore,'' Robert Wright said in a speech to
representatives of the cable and broadcast industries.
   ``And without some new sources of income, the future of the
networks, to put it charitably, is uncertain,'' he said.
   Wright said NBC, the prime-time leader, is in a better financial
position than CBS and ABC because of ``a few more hit shows than
the other guys have and a gentleman named Bill Cosby, who cannot be
expected to carry us over the top forever.'' The Cosby Show is one
of TV's top-rated shows.
   The NBC president said the networks are being hamstrung by
outdated federal regulations that bar the networks from having a
financial interest in programs produced by others and limit what
they can produce themselves. The government also prohibits the
networks from owning cable systems, syndicating programs
domestically and sharing in the profits of syndication of shows
produced by network-owned stations.
   Supplying cable programming and operating cable networks are two
of the few opportunities available to the networks to broaden their
business bases, he said.
   ``We can do in cable what we can't do in broadcasting,'' Wright
told reporters after his speech.
   NBC last month announced that it had agreed to buy the Tempo
Television cable channel from Tele-Communications Inc., and use it
to launch two new cable services. The services _ a
sports-programming network and a business-news service _ will rely
on the resources of NBC News and NBC Sports.
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. also has stepped into the cable arena,
with ownership of ESPN.
   ``The fresh breeze of deregulation hasn't blown much over the
networks. We've felt very little benefit,'' Wright said. ``The
network rules still stand like an aging colosseum. We're inside
looking over the walls at the young lions who have been set free to
enjoy an open marketplace.''

</TEXT>
