<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hutton-Libel     06-01 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hutton-Libel,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hutton Investigator Says He Couldn't Find Guilt in Top Management</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Attorney General Griffin Bell testified
Wednesday that his private investigation of check kiting at E.F.
Hutton didn't fault senior management because he couldn't find
evidence of wrongdoing at the top.
   Bell, sued for defamation for identifying a former Hutton branch
manager as a wrongdoer in a 1985 report, stoutly defended the
investigation his Atlanta law firm conducted after Hutton pleaded
guilty to 2,000 mail and wire fraud charges.
   ``I thought I could catch a high person, but I never could,''
Bell said.
   Though he was suspicious that top officials were aware of
illegal overdrafting practices, Bell said he found no evidence of
intentional wrongdoing by senior executives.
   ``I'm not going to put my name on something charging somebody
with wrongdoing if they ... did not have the intent to do something
wrong,'' Bell testified in the federal court trial of the case
brought by former Hutton branch manager John M. Pearce.
   Pearce, now a Sarasota, Fla., businessman, claims Bell
negligently ignored evidence that cash management practices that
led to Hutton's guilty plea were approved by top executives.
   Pearce, who ran Hutton branches in Bethesda, Md., and St. Louis,
alleges that Bell's report put false blame on him and the eight
other branch and regional officials who were identified as
initiating illegal overdrafting.
   But Bell testified that Pearce ``never told me that anybody
authorized him to do that.''
   ``I asked him about paying a penalty. He said he didn't think he
should have to pay a penalty because he was a manager and not an
account executive.''
   The former attorney general quoted Pearce as saying: ``Why don't
you take it out of my bonus.''
   Bell, a senior partner at the Atlanta law firm of King &
Spalding, was hired by Hutton to conduct the investigation after
the brokerage firm pleaded guilty to the charges on May 2, 1985.
His report was issued on Sept. 4, 1985.
   Hutton, now part of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., agreed to pay a
$2 million fine and reimburse banks for interest lost on checks
written for amounts greater than funds it kept in its checking
accounts.
   The company also agreed to stop certain cash management
practices that investigators said gained Hutton as much as $250
million a day in interest-free loans.
   Bell said that when he had trouble getting documents from the
company's law firm, he visited Hutton chairman Robert M. Fomon to
get the material for his investigation.
   ``I told him there was going to be an historical marker in front
of the Hutton building saying: `This is where the company was. They
lost the company because their lawyers were claiming
attorney-client privilege.''' Bell said.
   ``At that point I started getting documents,'' said Bell, a
former federal appellate judge who also served as President
Carter's first attorney general.
   Although Bell did not find wrongdoing by top managers, he
faulted senior executives for not properly monitoring the cash
management procedures being followed at lower levels in the company.
   ``They didn't have any controls at all,'' Bell testified. The
company was ``just letting people go wild, doing whatever they
wanted to do.''
   The report recommended that Thomas P. Morley, the ``money
mobilizer'' who devised aggressive cash management systems, be
relieved of any duties involving Hutton's banking activities.
   ``Everybody disowned Mr. Morley,'' Bell said. ``Nobody owned up
that they had anything to do with him.''
   Thomas P. Lynch, executive vice president, was identified in the
investigation as the company's chief financial officer and forced
to resign for failing to maintain proper controls.
   Bell said his investigation had trouble identifying which top
executive ultimately was responsible for the firm's financial
procedures because ``nobody wanted to be known as the chief
financial officer.''
   Many overdrafting procedures used by large companies, including
Hutton, are legal because the banks are aware of them, Bell said.
   But he conceded in questioning by Pearce's lawyer, Stephen
Milliken, that in the case of many Hutton accounts, ``most banks,
or many banks, did not know what was happening to them.''
   ``My best information was they did not tell the banks, except in
a few instances'' Bell said.
</TEXT>
