<2ND_LINE>AM-House-Juveniles,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Legislation For Juvenile Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted 377-5 on Wednesday for a bill
that would authorize money for juvenile delinquency, runaway youth
and missing children.
   The legislation, which went to the Senate, is an authorization
bill that does not include actual appropriations.
   The bill would establish a new program to finance prevention and
treatment programs for youth gangs. Grants would be issued to local
groups and agencies in an effort to prevent youngsters from taking
part in gang activities.
   The legislation also would increase the minimum grant for state
juvenile justice programs from the current $225,000 to $325,000.
   An amendment added on the House floor would require any
applicant for money to assure it has a policy of a drug-free
workplace.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimated the bill would cost
$25 million in fiscal 1989, $84 million in 1990, and $118 million
in 1991.
