<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugCase     06-01 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Case,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Document Alleges Mexican Officials Received Bribes From Drug
Trafficker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of dollars in bribes were paid to
Mexico's defense minister and other officials, and U.S. Customs
agents let loads of marijuana pass through a border station,
according to an affidavit in a drug-smuggling case.
   The affidavit was filed by the U.S. attorney's office in U.S.
District Court in support of the government's seizure of more than
$10 million in assets belonging to Jaime Javier Figueroa-Soto and
nine others. They were arrested last week during raids involving
more than 100 officers in several cities.
   Drug Enforcement Administration agent Leonard Williams displayed
some of the assets Tuesday and said he expects more arrests and
asset seizures in coming weeks.
   The affidavit contains a charge by a DEA informer that Gen. Juan
Arevalo Gardoqui, Mexico's defense minister, received a $10 million
bribe in 1984 from an alleged partner of Figueroa-Soto's, Rafael
Caro Quintero, to assure protection of marijuana and poppy fields
in the Mexican state of Chihuahua.
   Arevalo Gardoqui has denied his family is involved in drug
trafficking, and the Mexican federal attorney general's office also
denied the allegations against Arevalo and other top law
enforcement officials, The Arizona Daily Star reported Saturday.
   The affidavit also alleged that in 1983 Figueroa-Soto, as head
of a marijuana growers' cooperative in Sonora, paid Dr. Samuel
Ocana-Garcia, who was then Sonora's governor, to ensure the safety
of fields. Sonora is the Mexican state that borders Arizona.
   Ocana-Garcia also has denied any tie to narcotics trafficking.
   Officials have described Figueroa-Soto, who was arrested at his
Scottsdale home last Thursday, as perhaps the largest Mexican
marijuana dealer and worth an estimated $150 million. He was
ordered held under $50 million bond last week.
   The affidavit, which was filed last week and first made public
by The Daily Star, also said DEA agents were told that INS
inspector Oscar Sainz allowed tons of marijuana to enter the United
States at Nogales in 1983.
   It also said Customs official Robert Huerta allowed trailer
loads of up to 15 tons of marijuana to pass his inspection station
at Nogales.
   Acting port director in Nogales Gary Rehbein would not say
whether Sainz or Huerta were under investigation, The Arizona
Republic reported Wednesday. He said Sainz resigned about four
years ago without disciplinary action and that Huerta was still
working at the port.
   The DEA's Williams said Tuesday that officers seized $6.7
million in cash and bank accounts in last week's raids in cities in
Texas, Arizona and California, along with an estimated $500,000 in
jewelry, seven homes valued at $1.7 million, 40 vehicles worth $1
million, two airplanes worth $115,000 and 90 pounds of marijuana.
   Williams predicted more arrests and cash seizures in coming
weeks.
   Judge G. Thomas Meehan of Pima County Superior Court on Tuesday
delayed preliminary hearings for Figueroa-Soto and several others
until at least June 9.
</TEXT>
