<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderContract     06-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Contract,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Honor At Heart of Bedouin Murder Conspiracy Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 3rd graf, `The Tarawnehs ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bedouin couple demanded the death
and mutilation of their unwanted son-in-law to avenge their honor,
prosecutors said Wednesday, but the defense accused authorities of
blowing up a tragic family problem into a murder conspiracy case.
   Suad and Ghada Tarawneh, now of Toledo, Ohio, are accused of
plotting to kill their daughter's husband and his family because in
1986 the 17-year-old girl spurned a marriage they arranged, and
instead married her Syrian cousin.
   The Tarawnehs asked a private detective, Ron Petrillo, to cut
off the son-in-law's finger and genitals and return them to the
couple, along with color photos of the bodies, Assistant State
Attorney William Dimitrouleas said in his opening arguments.
   The alleged plot was stopped before anyone was hurt, but the
parents were accused of murder conspiracy and solicitation to
commit murder. The Tarawnehs were arrested last February in Toledo
after Petrillo contacted authorities about the case.
   ```I'd like to keep the photos of the body as a souvenir,'''
Dimitrouleas quoted Tarawneh as saying on secretly recorded tapes.
```You're Italian, Petrillo, you understand family. You understand
honor. That's why we asked you to help us.'''
   Dimitrouleas quoted Tarawneh as telling the detective ``We are
Moslem, and when you are in the desert, honor is very important to
you.''
   The prosecutor took aim at defense contentions that the threats
against the son-in-law were only empty words. He noted that the
cautious Tarawneh had even called Petrillo to Toledo because he did
not want to use the word ``kill'' over the telephone.
   In his opening arguments, defense attorney Don Spadaro disputed
the prosecution version, saying the Tarawnehs were not killers, but
tragic victims wrapped up in the emotions of their family crisis
and the father's drinking.
   ``The first tragedy was the drinking problem, the second was the
loss of their daughter in 1986 and the third was the hiring of this
investigator,'' said Spadaro.
   Petrillo, he said, had been hired to find the daughter and
located her in nearby Tamarac. But when she refused to see her
parents, the detective turned their angry initial reaction into a
murder plot, Spadaro said.
   Tarawneh, 46, a gynecologist, and his wife, 44, a nurse, left
Jordan 18 years ago. When their daughter Raniah married her Syrian
cousin Mouataz Abdulsalam in 1986 over their objections, the
angered parents said their honor had been blackened and had to be
avenged. Abdulsalam is the son of Mrs. Tarawneh's sister.
   The daughter testified Wednesday that her father once sent her
uncle to kill her in Syria, and had tried to cut off her hand when
she first told him she wanted to marry her cousin. He also had her
jailed briefly on what she said were trumped-up charges of stealing
her mother's jewelry.
   ``He said I'd regret it, he'd kill me, he'd kill my husband,
that I would regret it for the rest of my life,'' she testified.
   But, she said, he also wrote her a card apologizing, saying ``I
never meant to hurt you _ you are my blood and flesh.'' She said
her father abused both alcohol and prescription drugs, and had lost
jobs at hospitals because of his habits.
   At first the Tarawnehs planned to kidnap their daughter and sell
her into a prostitution ring in Jordan, but that fell through and
they switched to the murder plot, according to investigator Mike
Breece of the Florida Department of Law Enforcement.
   The alleged plot was stopped before anyone was hurt, but the
parents were accused of murder conspiracy and solicitation to
commit murder against Abdulsalam, his mother and his younger
sister. The Tarawnehs were arrested last February in Toledo after
Petrillo contacted authorities about the case.
</TEXT>
