<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeadWater     06-01 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lead Water,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Lead Concentrations in School Water Violates EPA
Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city shipped bottled water to half of its
elementary schools Wednesday after state health officials found
lead concentrations in drinking water exceeded federal limits.
   Officials also plan to test schools outside the city following a
report that drinking water in 40 Boston grade schools is unsafe and
that water in another 19 schools contained lead levels just below
Environmental Protection Agency limits, said Deborah
Prothrow-Stith, state public health commissioner.
   ``Obviously there is a problem and there's going to have to be
more testing to insure that the public health and welfare is
protected,'' said Paul G. Keough, EPA deputy regional
administrator. ``We are concerned because some of the levels were
very high.''
   Some parents gave their children bottles of water to take
Wednesday, and school officials said they were concerned about the
dangers of extended consumption of lead-tainted water for the
city's 30,000 students in pre-kindergarten through fifth grade.
   ``This is another situation where urban schools are left
behind,'' said William Ubinas, principal of the William Blackstone
School in the city's South End. ``Now we not only have to deal with
the drug problem and the traffic outside but the lead. When will we
be allowed to educate?''
   The state Department of Public Health sampled water at 79 public
and two private elementary schools over the Memorial Day weekend
after a television station reported high lead content at eight
schools.
   Water at 40 schools exceeded the EPA limit of 50 parts per
million of lead in drinking water. The tests revealed a level of
2,300 parts per million at the water supply source in one school
and 1,400 ppm at a water fountain in another.
   Keough said the EPA in July plans to recommend reducing the
unsafe lead content level to 20 ppm. The tests showed an additional
19 schools had lead concentrations of between 20 and 50 ppm.
   Lead poisoning attacks the brain, kidneys, nervous system and
red blood cells and can lead to brain damage and death, health
officials said. Lead occurs in food, air, soil, dust, paint and
water.
   Officials said poisoning is rarely caused by contaminated water
alone, but overexposure to lead can stunt physical and mental
development in children, causing nervous disorders, learning
disabilities and mental problems. Children under 8 are especially
vulnerable, they added.
   Ralph Timperi, director of the State Laboratory Institute in
Boston, which analyzed the water samples, said three likely sources
for the lead are lead pipes, lead solder used from 1980-86 and
electric cooling systems in water fountains. Some lead pipes in
Boston schools are more than 50 years old, he said.
   Schools are more susceptible to high lead levels because water
sits in pipes after school and on weekends, allowing greater lead
absorption.
   In a 1976 study, the EPA found that 25 percent of Boston-area
households exceeded federal lead safety limits.
   Keough said officials will attack the problem on a ``fountain by
fountain'' basis by repairing or replacing pipes, solder and
cooling systems.
   The Great Bear Spring Co. of Canton Wednesday delivered 680
five-gallon bottles of water, 136 coolers and 272,000 paper cups to
city schools, Great Bear sales manager Donna Pires-Donaghy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BroadwaySeason     06-01 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Broadway Season,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadway Season Ends With Box Office and Attendance Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business boomed on Broadway during the 1987-88
season with a record $253 million worth of tickets sold to more
than 8.1 million theatergoers, the League of American Theaters and
Producers announced Wednesday.
   The figures solidified the upturn in ticket sales that began
during the previous season when grosses totaled $209 million and
some 7 million people saw a Broadway show, the league said.
   But while the grosses and attendance were up, production was
down, with only 32 shows opening on Broadway between June 1, 1987
and May 29, 1988, compared to 40 the previous season. Still, the
shows that managed to get to Broadway during the 1987-88 survived
longer.
   ``There's a lot of choice on Broadway which is probably why
there are so many people going,'' said George Wachtel, director of
research for the league. ``We sold almost 200,000 tickets in each
of the last three weeks. That's about as good as it ever gets.''
   Musicals, particularly ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' again
dominated the year, but several plays were also very strong at the
box office. ``Phantom,'' which had a record $19 million advance
sale, is expected to have as long a life in New York as such hardy
holdovers from other seasons as ``Les Miserables,'' ``Cats,''
``42nd Street'' and ``A Chorus Line.''
   There were 12 new musicals on Broadway during the 1987-88
season, compared to 11 the previous year. Although ``Phantom'' was
the season's biggest musical hit, several other musicals were
popular including ``Sarafina!,'' a South African musical;
``Chess,'' the Tim Rice-ABBA-Trevor Nunn extravaganza about
international chess matches, and ``Into the Woods,'' a fairy tale
musical written by Stephen Sondheim and James Lapine. Of the
season's six revivals, the most successful was the Lincoln Center
revival of Cole Porter's ``Anything Goes.''
   There were eight new plays on Broadway, down from 13 the
previous season, but of the eight, only one _ ``Serious Money'' _
was a quick flop. Five others are still running including the four
Tony nominees for best play _ ``A Walk in the Woods'' by Lee
Blessing, ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' by August Wilson, ``M.
Butterfly'' by David Henry Hwang and ``Speed-the-Plow'' by David
Mamet.
   ``How many seasons have there been where a show like `Burn This'
would not be nominated for best play?'' Wachtel said, referring to
the season's fifth new play still running. ``In that sense, I think
it was a rich season.''
   If box office receipts were up, so were costs and ticket prices
as well as risks to producers. The $50 ticket for a musical is now
the norm rather than the exception. A $40 top ticket for a play on
weekend nights is also not unusual. The average paid admission,
according to the league, was $31.10, up from $29.86 for the
previous season.
   The flops were more costly too. ``Carrie,'' a musical based on
the Stephen King horror novel, lost a record $8 million and closed
after five performances, the most expensive failure in Broadway
history.
   Wachtel looks for the increase in ticket sales to continue.
   ``In terms of attendance, I think we will do very well because
the last three weeks have been extraordinary,'' he said. ``We have
the momentum to keep going. A lot of that may be from tourism and
the weakness of the dollar. The pick up we usually get from tourism
during the summer is happening earlier.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SecurityClearances     06-01 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Security Clearances,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Strikes Down Ban On Secrecy Pledges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has struck down a congressional
provision that bars the Reagan administration from requiring
government workers to sign secrecy pledges during the first 10
months of this year.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch ruled that the provision
contained in a spending resolution passed by Congress last December
unconstitutionally intruded on the president's power to protect
government secrets.
   ``With a tug of the purse strings section 630 (of the spending
resolution) establishes a precedent unrestrained by discernible
standards and intrudes dramatically upon presidential authority,''
Gasch said in a May 27 ruling made public this week.
   The judge made the decision in suits by seven members of
Congress and three federal employee organizations charging the
Reagan administration flouted the continuing resolution by
requiring employees with access to classified information to sign
security forms.
   SF189, already signed by more than 1.7 million federal
employees, is a pledge never to divulge classified or classifiable
information without permission. The other form, SF4193, requires
employees to seek ``prepublication review of contemplated
disclosures.''
   The forms are criticized by members of Congress who contend that
they stem the flow of information to Capitol Hill.
   Gasch found that ``the sensitive and complicated role cast for
the president as this nation's emissary in foreign relations
requires that congressional intrusion upon the president's
oversight of national security information be more severely limited
than might be required in matters of purely domestic concern.''
   Gasch said he found ``particularly offensive'' provisions of the
continuing resolution that barred the president from preventing
federal employees from communicating with Congress or interfering
with the legislative branch's ability to get secret information
from government employees.
   Another provision Gasch found objectionable bars any secrecy
agreement that is at odds with existing law.
   ``Read together, these provisions of section 630 permit the
president to ensure the secrecy of national security information
only by those means authorized by Congress,'' Gasch said.
   The suits were filed by the American Federation of Government
Employees, the American Foreign Service Association and the
National Federation of Federal Employees. They were joined by Sens.
David Pryor, D-Ark.; Charles Grassley, R-Iowa; and William
Proxmire, D-Wis.; as well as Reps. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.; Jack
Brooks, D-Texas; Patricia Schroeder, D-Col.; and Gerry Sikorski,
D-Minn.
   Gasch dismissed all suits except several claims by AFGE that the
secrecy agreements violated employees' First and Fifth Amendment
rights.
   Patti Goldman, an attorney for Public Citizen Litigation Group,
which represented the foreign service officers, said the plaintiffs
planned to appeal what she called an unprecedented limit on the
power of Congress in this area.
   Usually courts defer to the president in the absence of any
action by Congress, she said. ``I don't know of any situation where
Congress acts and the president says `Nay, nay, I am not going to
do it.' This is a new twist.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
