<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-01 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet Texas; Storms Range The Plains, Great Lakes, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms that brought flooding to north central
Texas redeveloped Wednesday, while other powerful storms rumbled
from the Plains to the Northeast, and hot weather clung to the Ohio
and Tennessee river valleys.
   North central Texas' storms brought wind gusts to 54 mph near
Haskill, but showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across
south central and southeast Texas.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered from central and
eastern parts of Nebraska and Kansas into north central and
northeast Oklahoma. Showers and thunderstorms were also devbeloping
across parts of central Missouri.
   Showers and thunderstorms were also scattered across parts of
the northern Plains, and from the eastern Great Lakes region
through New York state and north central Pennsylvania to the
central New England coast.
   Rainshowers also were scattered across the Pacific Northwest.
   The storms were being triggered by cooler air sagging southward
from Canada and the Northeast into a large area of very warm
temperatures.
   Temperatures reached the 90s Wednesday from the western Ohio
Valley through the middle Mississippi Valley and eastern Arkansas
to the Carolinas and mid-Atlantic Coast.
   Readings were in the 60s from northern New York into Maine, with
a few 50 degree temperatures across east central and southeast New
York.
   The low for the nation Wednesday was 23 at Gunnison, Colo.
Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47 degrees
at Missoula, Mont., to 97 degrees at Pope AFB near Fayetteville,
N.C., and the Naval Air station near Meridian, Miss.
   The national forecast for Thursday predicted rain likely across
the northern Pacific Coast, widespread across the Pacific Northwest
into northern California. Showers and thunderstorms will be
scattered from parts of northeast Texas through the lower Missouri
and middle Mississippi valleys, the upper Great Lakes and the Ohio
Valley into the middle Atlantic states.
   High temperatures will be in the 70s or 80s across much of the
nation; in the 60s across much of the Pacific Northwest into the
central California coast, and from the eastern Great Lakes into
central New England; in the 50s across northern Maine and the New
England coast; the 90s in the Southern California valleys, the Rio
Grande Valley of Texas and much of the Southeast; and, between 100
and 110 across the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
