<HEAD>20 Oklahoma Delegates Switch Allegiance To Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wholesale shift of Oklahoma delegates to
the camp of Michael Dukakis was announced Wednesday, moving the
Massachusetts governor ever closer to clinching the Democratic
nomination for president.
   The switch of 20 of the 26 delegates previously pledged to
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore was announced at a news conference at
the state Capitol by state Sen. Stratton Taylor, D-Oklahoma City,
chairman of Gore's Oklahoma campaign.
   Dukakis also picked up an endorsement from U.S. Sen. David
Boren, formerly a supporter of Gore.
   Boren, in a statement issued through his Washington, D.C.
office, called Dukakis a ``hard-working and capable governor.
   ``He has clearly emerged as the strong front-runner for the
nomination and is now entitled to have consensus support from the
party as we move toward the national convention in Atlanta,'' said
Boren.
   The changes announced Wednesday raised Dukakis' delegate
strength in Oklahoma from nine to 29. Dukakis finished third in
Oklahoma during the March 8 Super Tuesday primary behind Gore and
Rep. Richard Gephard of Missouri, who has since dropped out of the
race.
