<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TexasStorms     06-01 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Storms,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Move Back After Rains, Broken Dam Force Evacuation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMANCHE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy thunderstorms dumped more than 10
inches of rain on this north-central Texas town, overflowing a
creek, obliterating an earthen dam and forcing the evacuation of
about 60 people early Wednesday, authorities said.
   The storm waters also damaged homes, businesses and bridges and
briefly shut down some highways elsewhere in the area late Tuesday
and early Wednesday.
   ``A wall of water came through here and these people barely got
out in time,'' said Gayle Godfrey as he stood amid torn furnishings
and soggy carpet drying on the shore of Lake Eans.
   The flood's apex came between 3 a.m. and 6 a.m., and by 8:30
a.m., residents were allowed to return to their homes.
   All that remained of the former 100-acre private lake at
daylight were acres of mud, tons of debris and fallen trees.
   Maida Godfrey pointed to grass and mud stains 4{ feet high on
the white walls of her home, which she estimated sustained about
$30,000 in damage.
   ``We had to leave out the back door when the water came pouring
in,'' she said. ``We've lived here 22 years, and it's never gotten
this high before.''
   Mrs. Godfrey, 40, and her 18-year-old son, Sheridan, ran up a
hill to the home of a neighbor. From the top of the hill, she said
she heard a loud roar about 5 a.m. as water broke through the dam
that was built in the 1930s in a water reclamation project.
   Floodwaters also overflowed the banks of Indian Creek, tearing
through homes and businesses in Comanche and knocking chunks of
pavement from bridgets.
   ``I looked outside my trailer house to see how the rain was and
saw water flowing over my tires,'' said Terry Donald, who evacuated
his home about 4 a.m. ``My parents came over in a four-wheel drive
and got me. A fire truck came into the Indian Creek area later and
evacuated everybody else.
   ``At the trailer house across the street, they had to get a boat
to find that man. Water was chest-high in his house,'' Donald said.
   At Lake Comanche, about four miles southeast of this town of
12,600, a dam held but water spilled over its lip, said Duane Ogle,
a teacher at Comanche High School, where the evacuated residents
stayed until the floodwaters subsided.
   North along U.S. 377, the floodwaters blocked several
underpasses and bridges with logs and debris. The driver of an
18-wheeler reportedly swam to safety as floodwaters washed his
truck off the road.
   Streets in several other counties in the area also were flooded
by the storms, the National Weather Service reported.
   Comanche and 42 other Texas counties, most of them in the
north-central part of the state, remained under a severe
thunderstorm watch until late Wednesday night.
</TEXT>
