<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-PoorNations     06-01 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Poor Nations,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Will Support Help with Debts of `Poorest' Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States said Wednesday it
supports granting concessions to some of the world's poorest
nations to make it easier for them repay billions of dollars in
loans.
   Treasury Secretary James C. Baker told a news conference at the
annual meeting of the African Development Bank that lower interest
rates or more liberal terms of repayment could help ease the
pressure on those countries.
   Baker said members of the Paris Club _ a group of lenders
including the United States, Britain and France _ should be able to
negotiate their own terms of financing.
   ``It is important to realize that what we are talking about here
is a change in the policy of the Paris Club, which would permit
creditor governments to differentiate in the approach to
rescheduling,'' he said.
   Concessions would involve only ``official debt owed by the
poorest of the poor,'' he said.
   Most of the money owed by the poorest countries is ``official
debt'' _ funds lent by developed countries.
   Many African nations cannot repay foreign debts that now exceed
$200 billion for the continent and have urged Western nations to
write off part or all the obligation. Baker made clear he does not
propose that kind of relief.
   He said the U.S. proposal ``will continue to require that each
country be looked at on a case-by-case basis. It is therefore not a
call for a generalized debt relief proposal or a global approach,
if you will. But it does represent a change, it certainly does, as
far as official debt owed by the poorest of the poor.''
   In effect, this means the United States will not block efforts
by the other Paris Club member countries to draw up debt concession
agreements with certain countries.
   Asked if other members of the Club of Paris are likely to favor
his proposal, Baker said: ``I think it is a major step in the
direction of some suggestions that have been heretofore made by
some of our Paris Club partners. So I believe they will welcome
this.''
   ``Those governments that felt free, legally or from a policy
basis, to grant concessional or perhaps more concessional interest
rates would be free to do so, whereas other governments could
perhaps look at a broader range of maturities as a means of
contributing,'' Baker said.
   Baker said the U.S. administration does not have the authority
to write off debt.
   ``One of the difficulties ... the United States has with a
proposal to move to concessional interest rates on official debt is
that that constitutes to a degree debt forgiveness, which the
executive branch is not empowered, alone, to grant,'' he said.
   ``We are permitted to negotiate more liberal terms of repayment.
We have been doing that, and my remarks indicate a willingness on
our part to consider moving along that same path in the future,''
Baker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0259 </DOCNO>
