<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Disease     06-01 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Disease,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Causes Given of Legionnaires' Disease Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor maintenance of the air conditioning system
and extensive construction in the vicinity were responsible for a
fatal outbreak of Legionnaires' disease at BBC headquarters,
investigators said Wednesday.
   Thirty-nine people contracted the disease in and around the
British Broadcasting Corp. offices from mid-April to early May and
two died, according to the Westminster Public Health Office.
   BBC executives and engineers who made up the investigating team
recommended improved maintenance procedures relating to its
water-cooled air conditioning system and examining links between
the disease and local construction and demolition projects.
   ``The outbreak appears to have been due to a combination of
internal and external factors,'' said chairman Charles Sandbank,
deputy director of engineering. ``The external factors included the
extensive demolition and building activity in the vicinity of
Broadcasting House.''
   ``Shortcomings were revealed in the ... procedures associated
with the applications of water treatment chemicals and biocides to
the cooling tower,'' he said.
   Legionnaires' disease was first diagnosed in 1976 when 221
people contracted it at an American Legion convention in
Philadelphia. It produces symptoms similar to pneumonia and often
caused by bacteria from water-cooled air conditioning units.
   The BBC has said air systems in its buildings have been
disinfected.
</TEXT>
