<DOCNO> AP880601-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeabrookWithdrawal     06-01 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook Withdrawal,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MMWEC Board Votes to Stop Payments on Seabrook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUDLOW, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major investor in the Seabrook nuclear
power plant said it would pull out of the troubled project
Wednesday, a setback that one opponent claimed could kill the
controversial plant.
   ``Our many successes have been hidden by the shadow of
Seabrook,'' said Gary L. Hunt, general manager of the Massachusetts
Municipal Wholesale Electric Co., after its eight-member board of
directors voted to withdraw.
   MMWEC, with its 11.6 percent stake in the plant, is Seabrook's
fourth-largest investor. Its action ``will enable MMWEC to get on
with its business,'' Hunt added.
   The $5.4 billion Seabrook reactor is completed but lacks
approved evacuation plans required for commercial operation.
   In addition, its largest investor, Public Service Company of New
Hampshire, filed for U.S. Bankruptcy Court protection from
creditors on Jan. 28. PSNH owns 36 percent of the project.
   Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams said the action would have no
immediate effect, but he said the project's joint owners would meet
soon to discuss it.
   ``The rest of the owners remain committed, and the bottom line
remains the plant is very much needed for New England,'' he said.
``We will overcome this and the plant will be brought on line.''
   Bob Backus, a lawyer for the Seacoast Anti-Pollution League,
which has fought the project since its inception, said MMWEC's
action could doom the project.
   ``I believe there's a major funding problem for the project and
it is so grossly uneconomic right now that this may be the end of
it,'' Backus said.
   The top three owners of the Seabrook project _ PSNH, United
Illuminating and Eastern Utilities Associates _ said Wednesday that
they wouldn't pick up MMWEC's 11.6 percent stake in the plant.
   The New Hampshire plant has been dogged by troubles since PSNH
announced its intention to build it 20 years ago. The company
shelved its original plans, and environmental impact hearings
delayed the project in the 1970s.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis has opposed evacuation
planning for communities in his state near the plant in an effort
to prevent it from going into service.
   MMWEC's action comes less than one week after New York State
reached an agreement with Long Island Lighting Co. to abandon the
$5.3 billion Shoreham nuclear plant, which also has never generated
a watt of electricity.
   MMWEC, which supplies power to 34 municipalities across the
state, bought its shares in Seabrook on behalf of 28 utilities in
Massachusetts and eight in other Northeastern states.
   The company has sunk $875 million into the stalled plant so far.
   Hunt said several utilities have asked MMWEC to withdraw because
of the steady rise in electric rates required to meet Seabrook's
costs.
   The company pays about $90 million a year for its long-term
Seabrook debt and payments of about $15 million to $20 million
annually to support the idle plant.
   MMWEC's board voted to stop further payments for Seabrook but to
continue to service the debt.
   By pulling out of the project, MMWEC hopes the state will allow
it to issue tax-exempt bonds to refinance its Seabrook borrowings,
officials said. Previously, Dukakis has refused tax-exempt
financing for the project.
   Hunt declined to speculate on the effect the withdrawal would
have on the project, saying it was ``of secondary consideration.''
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., another Seabrook opponent, said
the decision ``reflects the bottom-line reality that Seabrook is a
teetering financial dinosaur about to become extinct.''
   Hunt's plan calls for MMWEC to ask other Seabrook owners to
assume its share of construction and maintenance costs or buy its
shares outright. He declined to say what might happen if they
refuse.
   Hunt estimated that MMWEC had three months' worth of payments in
an escrow account that the other investors would exhaust before
taking any action. The joint owners also usually grant a five-month
grace period before declaring another owner in default, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2208EDT</FILEID>
