<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Slaying,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film Set Designer Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British film-set designer Tessa Davies, who worked
on the movie ``The Killing Fields,'' was found dead in a pool of
blood and her companion unconscious in their home near London,
police said Wednesday night.
   Richard Furgerson, a TV set designer who owns the house, was
reported hospitalized in serious condition.
   Detective Superintendent John Childerley said there was no sign
of a struggle. He said the 47-year-old Miss Davies, found in a
downstairs room, was killed by heavy blows to her head with some
household object. Childerley said Furgerson, 51, was in a bedroom
upstairs.
   Police said they were not looking for a third party.
   Furgerson's ex-wife lives near the house and they have two sons
in their late 20s, Childerley said.
   Police said they broke into the house at Hurley near Maidenhead,
soon after dawn, after receiving an emergency telephone call from a
friend in London who was worried about the couple.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said Miss
Davies dressed the sets for David Puttnam's ``The Killing Fields''
in 1984, about the communist takeover of Cambodia, and was
nominated for an Academy Award. It said she was also nominated for
an Academy Award for her work with Barbra Streisand in ``Yentl.''
   Her latest film, which she had just completed on location in
Mexico, was ``The Old Gringo,'' starring Jane Fonda, the agency
reported.
