<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SpyBook     06-01 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spy Book,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Loses ``Spycatcher'' Appeal in Australian High Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The High Court of Australia on
Thursday rejected the British government's final appeal to stop
publication of the book ``Spycatcher'' in Australia.
   In a unanimous decision, the judges dismissed Britain's appeal
from a New South Wales court of appeal ruling, paving the way for
publication of the book in Australia.
   The British government was ordered to pay costs.
   Although 240,000 copies of the book by Peter Wright have been
sold in Australia, Britain wanted further copies of it banned and
to be awarded all profits from past sales here. Britain contended
that Wright was obligated not to write about his experiences as a
former British intelligence official.
   The High Court decision cleared the way for Thursday's scheduled
paperback launch of the book in Australia.
   In ``Spycatcher,'' Wright details his 20 years in Britain's MI-5
secret service tracking down traitors and accuses his former boss,
the late Sir Roger Hollis, of being a Soviet mole _ or deeply
concealed double agent.
   Wright, 73, lives in retirement in Tasmania, Australia's
southernmost state, where he breeds thoroughbred horses with his
wife Lois.
   Despite a ban on sales of the book in Britain and Hong Kong, the
work has sold an estimated 1.4 million copies worldwide, according
to publishers Heinemann Australia Pty Ltd.
</TEXT>
