<HEAD>Salvadoran President Undergoes Tests at Army Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``He is ...'' to
UPDATE with acting president's commentsl; Picks up 5th graf pvs,
bgng: ``Duarte's illness ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador-Duarte Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors at Walter Reed Army Medical Center
conducted a battery of tests Wednesday on Salvadoran President Jose
Napolean Duarte who was flown to the United States suffering from
what he called an ulcer ``of a malignant nature.''
   Duarte, 62, was admitted to Walter Reed after arriving late
Tuesday night on a special flight from San Salvador.
   Hospital spokesman Pete Esker said Duarte rested comfortably
Tuesday night and that medical tests were started Wednesday morning.
   ``He is in good spirits and his condition is stable,'' Esker
said. He declined to give more detailed information on Duarte's
condition.
   Salvadoran Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount, who
became acting president when Duarte was flown to Washington for
treatment, on Wednesday described Duarte as ``a man on the verge of
death.''
   ``It has been confirmed that President Duarte has a cancerous
bleeding ulcer in the stomach. Today's (Wednesday's) examination of
his whole body _ the abdomen and thorax _ showed that the liver is
also affected by cancer.''
   Castillo Claramount said that when it was believed the cancer
was limited to the stomach ``there was a tendency to operate. But
that may have changed with the results of the subsequent
examinations.''
   Duarte's illness has been described by those around him as both
an ``ulcer'' and as ``a tumor.''
   As he was preparing to leave El Salvador on Tuesday night,
Duarte told reporters at Illopango military airport, ``What I have
is a bleeding ulcer seven centimeters (2{ inches) long in the
stomach, of a malignant nature.''
   He said a prognosis will be determined by medical tests in the
United States.
   Media Communications Minister Roberto Viera, asked about the
president's statement, said Duarte has ``a large tumor'' in his
stomach. ``The doctors don't want to characterize it until they do
a biopsy,'' Viera said.
</TEXT>
