<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0787 06-01 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0787,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Duarte, Ill, Leaves Battered Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with vice
president confirming Duarte has cancer. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he departed for medical
treatment in Washington this week, President Jose Napoleon Duarte
left behind a country ravaged by war and a Christian Democratic
party torn by infighting.
   On Wednesday night, Rodolfo Castillo Claramount, the acting
chief executive, told journalists Duarte has cancer and was ``a man
on the verge of death.''
   But in his final year in office, Duarte already had become a man
devoid of much power and one whose absence was not expected to have
a profound effect on El Salvador's problems.
   The 62-year-old president, arguably Washington's staunchest ally
in the Western Hemisphere, is in Walter Reed Army Medical Center
for diagnosis and treatment. He told reporters before departing
Tuesday that he was suffering from ``a bleeding ulcer of a
malignant nature.''
   Vice President Castillo Claramount, who became acting president
Tuesday when Duarte was flown to Washington, told reporters at the
presidential residence in San Salvador late Wednesday, after
meeting with U.S. Ambassador Edwin Corr:
   ``It has been confirmed that President Duarte has a cancerous
bleeding ulcer in the stomach. Today's (Wednesday's) examination of
his whole body _ the abdomen and thorax _ showed that the liver is
also affected by cancer.''
   He said to the correspondents, ``I ask for a minimal expression
of humanity, of charity. A fellow man's pain cannot be toyed with.
No one can doubt the word of a man on the verge of death, who has
had the courage to say it.''
   The farewell ceremony Tuesday had the air of a funeral at which
the deceased was on hand to say goodbye. Many of Duarte's family
members were openly crying, and the president gave long embraces to
friends and associates.
   Duarte appeared lean and haggard and at times on the verge of
tears.
   Leftist guerrillas said in a broadcast by their clantestine
radio station: ``Duarte leaves the country with an incurable
political disease because of the failure of the counterinsurgency
plan. Duarte leaves, and the people remain to carry out the
revolution.''
   The rebels are waging an 8-year-old war against U.S.-backed
government forces.
   Whether the government's campaign against the revolutionaries
has failed remains to be determined. But almost all of the vows
Duarte made upon assuming the presidency in June 1984 remain
unfulfilled.
   The guerrillas still carry out attacks and sabotage throughout
the country and exercise a significant degree of political control
and open activity in two northern provinces.
   The economy is in a shambles. The average Salvadoran's real
income is almost 40 percent below what it was at the start of the
war. About 500,000 people _ 10 percent of the population _ has been
displaced to squalid shantytowns and refugee camps.
   Because of the lack of security, investment is virtually nil.
   Duarte's Christian Democrats suffered a scathing defeat in
municipal and legislative elections in March.
   The electorate, in what was seen as a massive popular rejection
of the incumbents' performance, gave control of the legislature to
the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena.
   A surging Arena appears in good shape to win the presidential
election next March. The Constitution prohibits Duarte from running
again in any event.
   The Christian Democrats are trying to keep their party from
splitting. Two former Cabinet ministers and party founders, Julio
Adolfo Rey Prendes and Fidel Chavez Mena, claim the party's
presidential candidacy.
   Duarte tried last month to avoid a split by calling on both to
back a unity candidate. They ignored his appeal.
   He left Castillo Claramount in charge of the executive branch.
Castillo Claramount delivered Duarte's state-of-the-republic
address Wednesday to the new legislature.
   He promised to pursue Duarte's project to meet with leaders of
other parties, unionists, businessmen and peasants to draft a
united proposal to the guerrillas for ending the war.
   But the proposal, if and when it is worked out, is expected to
be a new version of old calls to lay down arms and participate in
elections. The guerrillas have rejected such a call, claiming the
conditions for democracy do not exist.
   They demand a share of power, which the government refuses to
consider.
   The conservative daily Prensa Grafica said Wednesday of Duarte's
illness: ``The absence of the chief executive, for very worrisome
motives, makes for even more uncertainty as to what will happen
during the next year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
