<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OlympicProtest     06-01 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympic Protest,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize About 100 Students In Anti-Olympic Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police broke up an anti-Olympic
protest and arrested about 100 radical students Thursday outside a
hotel where Juan Antonio Samaranch, the International Olympic
Committee president, was staying.
   Yonhap, the Korean news agency, said police had information some
of the protesters had plans to kidnap Samaranch. The report gave no
details.
   Hundreds of police quickly dispersed the peaceful demonstration
and dragged away shouting students who tried to block a road
outside the Shilla Hotel.
   Protesters denounced Samaranch for saying that communist North
Korea cannot act as co-host for the 1988 Olympics, set to begin
Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   ``Stage united Olympics!,'' students yelled before police
overpowered them.
   Hundreds of police remained on guard around the hotel after the
incident.
   Radical students have demanded that North Korea be allowed to
act as Olympics co-host to help promote reunification of the
divided Korean peninsula.
   The two Koreas, divided since 1945, are bitter enemies who have
clashed repeatedly over the years. In the 1950-53 Korean War, the
United States and other nations fought under the United Nations
flag on the side of South Korea and China intervened on the
northern side.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Games if it is not
co-host. The International Olympic Committee and South Korea have
said this is impossible because the Games are awarded to a single
city.
   Samaranch, in Seoul to inspect facilities for the Games, said
this week North Korea could not be co-host. He repeated his
committee's offer to let the north stage up to five events if it
drops its demand and takes part in the Seoul Games.
   South Korea and the United States accused North Korea of blowing
up a South Korean airliner Nov. 29 with the loss of all 115 people
aboard as part of efforts to disrupt the Olympics. The north says
it had nothing to do with the incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
