<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BlackMormons Adv06   06-01 1239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Mormons, Adv 06,1271</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ten Years Later, More Blacks Embrace Mormon Faith</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Ten years ago, the Mormon Church began admitting
blacks to its priesthood. While its missionaries have achieved
remarkable success in Africa and elsewhere abroad, at home they
labor to dispel the bitter legacy of 130 years of racial exclusion.
   ___</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon elder Joseph Freeman today guides
his white brethren through sacred temple rituals that just a decade
ago were denied him because of his black skin.
   ``I think I have been greatly blessed. I feel my life has been
very much fulfilled,'' said Freeman, who twice monthly performs
rites in the church's Denver Temple.
   ``I may never be a rich man, but I don't care to be. The riches
I have are to have a good family, to teach my children the gospel.''
   The ban ended June 9, 1978, when the late church President
Spencer W. Kimball announced he'd received a revelation from God
opening the priesthood, held by all worthy Mormon males older than
11, to black members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints.
   But despite the church's startling success among blacks since
then, particularly in Africa, it still labors at home to overcome
the ban's legacy: a lingering perception that Mormonism is a faith
for whites.
   The church numbers 8,500 members in Nigeria and 5,000 in Ghana
and is growing by about 2,000 converts a year in each country. New
missions have opened recently in Zaire, Liberia, Zimbabwe and
Sierra Leone.
   In predominantly black Haiti, the church reaps more than 70
converts monthly.
   Blacks in the American South hold leadership positions once open
only to whites.
   ``I started out being exotic and ended up being generic,'' said
Alan Cherry, one of the few American blacks baptized before 1978.
   Nor does the legacy of the ban appear to have slowed the
church's overall growth. Since 1978, the church says its membership
has nearly doubled from 3.8 million to 6.5 million worldwide.
   Black members say deliberate racism is extremely rare among
white Mormons. Rather, they say, blacks and whites struggle with
cultural and economic barriers that can undermine the most sincere
fellowships.
   ``The first question I get is, `Where did you play ball?''' said
Van Williams, a black employed in the church's public
communications department. ``When I say I didn't, then in their
minds I'm either a pimp or a drug dealer. I'm still struggling with
people who won't accept me for who I am, but I won't let that
affect my beliefs.''
   Like many black Mormons, Williams is skeptical of the church's
claim of a divine origin for the doctrine. ``I choose to look at it
as something that man placed and God removed,'' he said, echoing a
view shared by independent Mormon scholars and at least one
high-ranking church official.
   The late Hugh B. Brown, a member of the Council of the Twelve
and a counselor to former church President David O. McKay, never
accepted the ban as doctrine and nearly engineered its reversal,
said Brown's grandson, Edwin B. Firmage.
   Ten members of the Twelve, which assists the governing First
Presidency, voted to lift the ban in 1969. Firmage said the vote
was nullified when the council's senior active member, Harold B.
Lee, returned to town.
   Little evidence indicates the policy originated with church
founder Joseph Smith; it was not among the dozens of written
revelations he left before his 1844 assassination in Illinois. As
articulated by Smith's successor, Brigham Young, the ban was rooted
in the belief that black Africans were descendants of the biblical
Cain, cursed by God for murdering his brother, Abel.
   Church leaders in 1969 reiterated the policy was divine doctrine
taught by Smith and every succeeding Mormon prophet, but by 1978,
months before the ban's demise, they were saying that only God knew
the reason why.
   A decade later, that apparently remains the official view. Elder
Dallin H. Oaks, a member of the Twelve, said in an interview that
theological arguments trying to buttress the doctrine were largely
speculative. God doesn't give reasons for his revelations, he said.
   ``We can put reason to revelation. We can put reasons to
commandments. When we do, we're on our own. Some people put reasons
to the one we're talking about here and they turned out to be
spectacularly wrong,'' Oaks said.
   Mormons define priesthood as the authority to act in the name of
God, and membership is a prerequisite to any appointment in the
church's lay leadership or to performing such rites as baptism,
temple marriage and healing the sick.
   Freeman, for instance, was not permitted to bless his infant
sons before Kimball's revelation. A white member of the priesthood
gave the blessings instead.
   ``There were restrictions which, in a worldly sense, were hard
to accept,'' said Freeman, who two days after the ban was lifted
became the first black ordained to the faith's priesthood since the
faith's infancy, when at least two blacks held priesthood offices.
   Among Africans, the restriction appears to have made less
difference. ``They don't seem to take it the way I think I would if
I had been involved,'' said Reed Clegg, a missionary in Ghana and
Nigeria in the early 1980s.
   As early as 1946 the church was receiving inquiries from
Nigerians who had read church missionary tracts or articles. The
Nigerian government, however, refused to admit missionaries until
the policy was dropped.
   The appeal of Mormonism also spread to Ghana. When missionaries
arrived in the two countries, they were greeted by thousands eager
for baptism.
   Among American blacks, memories of the ban haunt missionary
efforts. But black and white Mormons alike say economic and social
barriers are more divisive than church doctrine.
   ``I would say that where you have black middle-class converts
coming into middle-class congregations, the prognosis is good,''
said Armand Mauss, a Washington State University sociologist who
has monitored the progress of black Mormons. ``Where you have
lower-class blacks being converted to middle-class congregations,
that's not good.''
   Mauss cited surveys taken from 1972 to 1985 by the National
Opinion Research Corp. that suggested white Mormons were slightly
more tolerant of blacks than non-Mormon whites. But when racial
tensions flare, they take their toll of fledgling black converts
alreay sensitive to the church's image among non-Mormon friends and
relatives.
   In Greensboro, N.C., black baptisms averaged six to 12 a month
in the early 1980s, but a majority fell away after racial
incidents, said John McCoy, a black who sits on the high council of
the Greensboro Stake, or diocese.
   Among those who left the church was McCoy's wife, taunted with
epithets by 11-year-olds she was teaching in Primary, the church's
organization for children.
   ``A very few whites, two or three, were still prejudiced and
they let the blacks know it. It made the rest of the whites feel
bad because the blacks were judging the church by them,'' said
McCoy, a member of eight years.
   Worried at the erosion among black converts, local leaders
offered them a choice, to continue attending mixed congregations or
form their own with black leaders. They unanimously picked the
latter.
   Since then, the number of active black participants has risen
from about 50 to more than 200.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
