<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices shot up in a post-holiday weekend
buying spree that pushed up the Dow Jones industrial average nearly
75 points.
   Analysts could not point to any specific developments to account
for Tuesday's rally, but they said sentiment seemed to have grown
that interest rates are near a peak for the time being.
   The Dow industrials rose 74.68 points to close at 2,031.12. That
was the widely followed barometer's best gain since a 76.42 rise on
Jan. 4 and the sixth biggest increase ever.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New-home sales climbed 4 percent in April to
the highest level in a year, the government said, but analysts said
rising interest rates would likely dampen sales this summer.
   New single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 679,000 last month, the fastest pace since new homes sold
at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987, the Commerce and Housing and
Urban Development departments said in a joint report Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction projects
declined 6 percent in April from the previous month, extending a
downward slide that began last fall, a report said.
   The survey, released Tuesday by the F.W. Dodge Division of
McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co., estimated the annualized value
of all newly started construction projects in April at $226.97
billion, compared with $242.38 billion in March.
   F.W. Dodge said high vacancy rates in commercial properties,
particularly offices and apartments, were responsible in reversing
the industry's five-year upswing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products in May
averaged 3.1 percent over April levels and were 4.7 percent over
their mark for the same month last year, the Agriculture Department
said.
   ``Higher prices for hogs, oranges, soybeans and broilers were
partially offset by lower prices for tomatoes, onions, milk and
upland cotton,'' the department's Agricultural Statistics Board
said in its preliminary report Tuesday.
   May farm commodity prices averaged 134 percent of a 1977 base
used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures. A year
ago the index was 128.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign purchases of U.S. businesses dropped
22 percent to $30.5 billion in 1987, the first dip since 1983 in
the rush by overseas investors to acquire American assets, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that foreigners spent $39.2
billion to acquire or establish businesses in the United States in
1986, compared with $23.1 billion in 1985 and $15.2 billion in 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a victory for bargain
hunters and discount dealers, upheld federal regulations that allow
a multibillion-dollar ``gray market'' in which costly imported
goods are sold at reduced prices.
   The justices, voting 5-4 Tuesday, said the U.S. Customs Service
does not have to shut down the gray market _ famous-name,
foreign-made goods bearing valid U.S. trademarks sold in this
country without approval from trademark owners.
</TEXT>
