<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. said it was only coincidence a
Taiwanese Boeing 737 that disintegrated and crashed in 1981 and an
Aloha Airlines 737 that lost part of its fuselage over Hawaii last
month were built one after the other.
   The cause of the Aloha accident is still under investigation.
However, the Federal Aviation Administration has ordered U.S.
airlines flying older 737s to reinspect the aircraft.
   Boeing believes the Far Eastern crash was caused by maintenance
problems, spokesman Jack Gamble of Boeing Commercial Airplanes said
Tuesday. Any similarities between that crash and the Aloha accident
are ``a series of coincidences,'' he said.
