<TEXT>
   Four years after his autobiography conquered the
bestseller lists, Chrysler Corp. chairman Lee Iacocca is back in
print _ grumbling about Japanese trade practices, volunteering to
pay more taxes and revealing that he once considered a takeover of
General Motors Corp.
   The new book, ``Talking Straight,'' arrives in bookstores today.
The initial printing is 750,000; booksellers can only hope that it
measures up to ``Iacocca: An Autobiography,'' which has sold 2.6
million hardcover copies and 3.5 million paperbacks worldwide.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices soared as traders celebrated their return from the
three-day Memorial holiday with a buying spree. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials climbed 74.68 to 2,031.12, its highest
level since it closed at 2,036.31 on May 4.
   Bond prices also rose, while the dollar and gold prices
strengthened in foreign exchange. Commodity prices surged broadly.
