<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Rise In Advance of OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices moved higher, but trading was
extremely light as dealers remain reluctant to make any significant
moves ahead of the OPEC meeting scheduled for June 8.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Tuesday, the contract for
June delivery of West Texas Intermediate closed up 8 cents at
$17.51 per 42-gallon barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline rose 0.40 cent to 52.95 cents a gallon. Wholesale
heating oil rose 0.45 cent a gallon to 48.23 cents.
   ``You had a very boring day,'' said Jayne Ball, a trader in the
international energy futures department at Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in New York. Asked why the market was so slow, she said,
``Would you put your money on a horse that hasn't run yet?''
   Traders said they were concerned about taking speculative
positions primarily because of the uncertain outcome of the planned
meeting among ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries in Vienna.
   OPEC's failure to decisively curb production excesses at an
inconclusive conference in April was blamed for a subsequent drop
in oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MacmillanRestructuring Bjt   06-01 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan Restructuring, Bjt,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Restructuring Could Leave Room for Bid by Bass, Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc.'s new billion-dollar
restructuring plan, designed to thwart a hostile takeover bid by
Texas investor Robert M. Bass, leaves the door open for higher bids
from Bass or other potential suitors, some analysts believe.
   The venerable publishing giant announced Tuesday that its board
of directors had adopted a plan to split the company's publishing
and non-publishing operations into two separate, publicly owned
corporations and to pay special dividends to shareholders.
   Macmillan valued the dividends and securities to be paid under
the restructuring plan at more than $64 a share, or over $1.66
billion. Some analysts who follow the company estimated the plan
would be worth $65 to $70 a share.
   Bass, who leads a group of Texas investors that launched a bid
for Macmillan in mid-May, offered $64 a share for Macmillan's
roughly 26 million outstanding shares. The bid by the Bass group _
which holds 9.1 percent of the company's shares _ was rejected as
inadequate by Macmillan's board.
   The investor group had no comment on Macmillan's restructuring
proposal, said Dee Kelly, an attorney at the law firm Kelly, Hart &
Hallman of Fort Worth, that is representing the group.
   The proposed restructuring still leaves room for Bass and other
potential suitors to bid for Macmillan, but makes the possibility
of an offer being supported by management more remote, said Bruce
Thorp, an analyst for Provident National Bank in Philadelphia.
   ``This really puts pressure on (potential suitors) for time,''
Thorp said.
   Other possible bidders cited by market watchers are competitors
Gulf & Western Inc., McGraw-Hill Inc. and British media tycoon
Robert Maxwell.
   Bass is keenly interested in Macmillan's information services
business, the company's fastest-growing and most profitable area,
according to analysts. The business, which publishes reference
books such as Who's Who and trade guides for lawyers, had sales of
$229 million in 1987 _ up from $146 million two years before.
   Under the restructuring plan, the two new companies would be
called Macmillan Publishing Co. and Macmillan Information Co.
Macmillan Information, now a subsidiary of the parent, would be
``spun off'' as a dividend to shareholders.
   For each share of existing Macmillan stock, shareholders would
receive a cash dividend of $52.35, a half-share of common stock in
the new Macmillan Information, and $4.50 principal amount of
Macmillan Information subordinated debentures.
   The cash dividend of $52.35 consists of $25.20 from Macmillan
Inc. and $27.15 from Macmillan Information.
   Macmillan stock dropped $2.25 a share Tuesday to close at $70.25
on the New York Stock Exchange. There had been rumors on Wall
Street that Macmillan's management might be planning to buy the
company from shareholders, speculation that had sent the stock up
$2.37{ a share on Friday.
   Macmillan said it had obtained commitments for all the financing
needed to pay the special dividends.
   The company said the restructuring plan had been under study for
a year, but analysts suggested the timing of the decision likely
meant it was taken to counter the Bass bid.
   ``I think the timing was a reaction to Bass,'' said Bert Boksen,
an analyst for Raymond James & Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla.
He called the restructuring ``a reasonable deal.''
   A takeover by Bass, Boksen suggested, would have boosted
Macmillan shares to $80 to $90 _ while the restructuring could lift
them to around $80.
   Macmillan Chairman Edward P. Evans told shareholders at the
annual meeting on May 18 that the company was not for sale. The
shareholders approved a proposal by management to authorize the
issuance of additional stock in Macmillan, as a defense against
hostile takeovers.
   Under the restructuring plan, Macmillan Information would
include the information services, textbook and retail businesses
currently owned by the parent. The operating managements of
Macmillan Publishing and Macmillan Information would remain the
same as in the current subsidiaries, and senior management would
continue in their positions.
   The company had revenue of $469.4 million from its publishing
operations and $486.4 million from its information businesses in
1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Stocks-Rally Bjt   06-01 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stocks-Rally, Bjt,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Scramble to Explain Reasons for Latest Stock Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market broke out of its May doldrums
with a buying spree that carried the Dow Jones industrial average
to its second biggest gain of the year.
   But analysts were hard-pressed to come up with an explanation
for Tuesday's surge, which came on the heaviest daily volume since
late January.
   ``Sometimes it's better just to enjoy and not analyze things
like this,'' said John L. Manley Jr., a portfolio strategist for
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``It's been a bad May.''
   Peter DaPuzzo, manager of retail equity trading for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc., said the warm weather over the Memorial Day
holiday may have brightened investors' outlooks and prompted them
to put some cash to work.
   ``You've got to start a summer rally sometime, and Memorial Day
is usually the threshold to the summer,'' he said.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 74.68 on Tuesday
to 2,031.12, its highest level since it closed at 2,036.31 on May 4.
   It was the biggest one-day advance in the market's most
widely-followed index since a 76.42-point gain on Jan. 4, the first
trading day of the year, and the sixth biggest rise ever.
   The gain in the Dow Jones industrials was so strong that a
voluntary limit on computerized program trading was triggered when
the Dow's rise swept past 50 points in the last hour of trading.
   But even after the so-called ``collar'' went into effect for the
rest of the day, the blue-chip average extended its gain. It was
the third time the collar had gone into effect since it was adopted
in the aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash in a bid to curb
market volatility.
   Gainers outpaced losers by nearly 4 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,211 up, 333 down
and 401 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 247.61 million shares,
up from 133.59 million in the previous session and the highest
since 275.25 million shares were traded there on Jan. 25. Two
utility stocks with dividend deadlines approaching accounted for
about 90 million shares of volume.
   Nonetheless, volume was up from the sluggish pace of recent
weeks that has prompted speculation that brokerage firms may resort
to a round of layoffs.
   Analysts had been saying that the slow pace of trading reflected
investors' uncertainty about the implications of continued strength
in the economy.
   While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits,
some investors worried that it could also reignite inflation and
prompt the Fdederal Reserve to choke it off by encouraging higher
interest rates.
   Even as stock prices and trading volume swelled on Tuesday, some
potential ingredients for a new surge in inflation were evident.
   Commodity futures prices surged, propelling a key inflation
indicator, the Commodity Research Bureau's index of 21 commodities,
to a three-year high.
   But that failed to dampen enthusiasm in the stock market.
   Analysts said stock traders were heartened by the dollar's
continuing stability and the bond market's resilience in the face
of rising commodity prices.
   Recent declines in bond prices have pushed their yields higher
and made them more competitive with stocks for investors' money.
   They also cited relief that the Fed failed to boost its discount
rate _ its interest charge on loans to financial institutions _ as
some feared it would after the markets closed last week.
   Eldon A. Grimm, a senior vice president at the brokerage Birr,
Wilson Securities Inc., said there is ``an enormous amount of cash
around out of the market'' due to wariness in the wake of last
October's crash.
   ``But every time we get a little rally going, people think they
will miss the boat and buy something,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USAirFlights     06-01 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USAir Flights,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attendants' Shortage Cancels USAir Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir said normal flight schedules would
resume today after numerous holiday weekend flights were canceled
when flight attendants refused to work end-of-the-month overtime to
protest an impasse in contract negotiations.
   The airline, based at National Airport in Arlington, Va.,
canceled about two dozen of its 1,600 flights Tuesday, said
spokesman Dave Shipley. The Washington, D.C.-based airline also
canceled one flight Saturday, 81 on Sunday and 61 on Memorial Day.
   ``It's a very, very small percentage of the total,'' Shipley
said. ``There's not chaos at the airports.''
   Shipley said flight attendants' overtime is governed by federal
regulations that limit them to 85 hours per month. He said flight
attendants may fly five extra hours per month as overtime at the
request of airlines, but they are not required to do so.
   Since today is the first day of the new month, the flight
attendants would revert to their normal work schedules.
   USAir has yet to complete an agreement for a new contract and
seniority list with its flight attendants and those employed by
Pacific Southwest Airlines, which USAir acquired last year and
merged into its system on April 9.
   ``Apparently there is (a protest), but it's not a
union-organized protest. I think it's a spontaneous protest. I was
as surprised as anyone else,'' said Juliette Lenoir, vice president
of the Washington, D.C.-based union and a USAir flight attendant.
   ``My best sense is that flight attendants are just very upset at
this whole issue of pay parity for the former PSA flight
attendants. That may have been the straw that broke the camel's
back,'' she said.
   Ms. Lenoir said USAir also has been asking attendants to do more
work, such as serving travelers before takeoff, without a raise in
pay since at least 1985.
   Shipley said most passengers booked on the canceled flights
switched to other USAir flights or to other airlines.
   USAir's central operating hub is Greater Pittsburgh
International Airport.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
