<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Coupe Delay,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Delay For Turbo Coupe by Maserati</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debut of the Turbo Coupe, a Chrysler-styled,
Maserati-built luxury sports car, has been hit with another delay
and probably won't show up in U.S. showrooms until late summer.
   The trade journal Automotive News reported this week that the
$30,000 coupe's launch was delayed for two more months because of
snags involved in a hard top as a no-cost option and by other
last-minute refinements.
   The car comes with no other options.
   ``We experienced a bit of difficulty with the hard top,''
Anthony Richards, director of Chrysler's Lamborghini and Maserati
programs, told the trade journal.
   The Maserati-Chrysler hybrid was scheduled for introduction in
mid-May on the West Coast but won't appear until the end of July _
well into the warm weather selling season for convertibles.
   The car, once planned for U.S. launch in early 1987, went into
production in low volume at Maserati's Innocenti plant in Milan,
Italy, earlier this month. The car will be sold and serviced by 300
Chrysler dealers in the United States and 30 in Canada.
   Chrysler plans to sell about 5,000 to 6,000 of the luxury sports
models a year, but the plant has the capacity to build as many as
8,000.
   The car first was shown in January 1986. Some of the many delays
in its introduction included different design ideas held by
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca and Maserati Chairman Alejandro De
Tomaso, Automotive News reported.
   The car was styled primarily in Detroit and engineered and built
in Italy. It is the first fruit of a Chrysler-Maserati joint
development agreement on vehicles for the North American market.
</TEXT>
