<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MechanicalAirBags     06-01 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mechanical Air Bags,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jaguar Plans First Use of Mechanical Air Bags in all 1990 Models</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar Cars Ltd. plans to offer completely
mechanical air bags on all models in 1990 using a New Jersey
company's system that cuts the cost of the devices to as little as
$40 each, a trade journal reported.
   The mechanical bags, developed by Breed Automotive Corp. of
Boonton, N.J., include a single sensor, no wiring and no expensive
electronics, Automotive News reported in this week's edition.
   Instead, the bags, packaged in the steering wheel and the
passenger side dashboard, inflate when a ball inside each package
is jarred loose during impact.
   The Jaguar installation would be the first use of the system,
which was tested and approved by the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration last year.
   Other air bag systems include sophisticated electronic sensors
that trigger a bag-inflating charge at the beginning of impact and
cost between $200 and $800 each.
   Tokai-Rika Co., a wholly owned subsidiary of Toyota Motor Corp.,
has been licensed by Breed to produce the mechanical air bag and
other Breed sensor technology, Automotive News reported.
</TEXT>
