<DOCNO> AP880601-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GM-LoomingLayoffs     06-01 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Looming Layoffs,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Counseling Helps Workers Prepare for Life After Layoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Malone is urging soon-to-be-laid-off
General Motors Corp. workers to do as he says and as he did _ stop
using credit cards and pay off all the debts they can while they're
still working.
   Malone prepared for his layoff two years ago by paying off
$3,000 in bills in one month so he wouldn't end up ``hitting the
wall'' _ losing his home or other possessions after layoff benefits
run out.
   ``I knew it was easier to pay them off when I was working
11{-hour days than after I was laid off,'' said Malone, who was
recalled in May and is using his experience at the UAW-GM Crisis
Center.
   Malone counsels laid-off GM workers who already have hit the
wall. But GM, the UAW and local agencies including Oakland Family
Services and Credit Counseling Centers Inc. also are trying to
teach workers how to avoid it.
   About 8,500 Pontiac-area workers are on layoff or will be by
1990, a portion of more than 30,000 GM workers whose jobs will
disappear in closings of at least 16 plants nationwide.
   Among the advice they receive: Stop using credit cards and
prepare a realistic budget that takes into account lower income
while benefits are coming in and potentially drastic reductions in
income afterward.
   The lessons are hard for some workers to learn, Malone said.
   Losing a job ``is a loss just like the other losses we
acknowledge, like the loss of a loved one,'' said Barbara La Fonz,
employment projects coordinator for Oakland Family Services.
   Victims experience the same stages of grief _ denial, anger,
depression and finally acceptance _ as with other major losses, she
said. But with a job loss, ``people have a tendency not to reach
out for help available to them.
   ``There is a desire to hide from the situation. They might bring
in the mail, but they don't really open up the bills. Imagination
takes over and makes it seem a worse situation than it is,'' La
Fonz said.
   Laid-off workers have hit the wall if they are being threatened
with foreclosure, eviction, repossession or bankruptcy.
   Some give up, La Fonz said. But many are directed to Credit
Counseling Centers Inc., a non-profit counseling agency that
provides free assessments.
   Giving up can lead to bankruptcy filings, as many as 50 percent
of which are unnecessary, said Credit Counseling spokeswoman Nancy
Leahey, citing a recent study by Purdue University.
   The study showed half of 1,199 bankruptcy petitions surveyed had
no ability to repay debts; 20 percent could have paid all but
mortgage debts in three years, and 25 percent could have repaid 75
percent of their debts in three years, Leheay said.
   ``Once filed, a bankruptcy stays on the credit record for 10
years and indefinitely for life insurance policies and mortgage
credit requests,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
