<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Help-WantedAds     06-01 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Help-Wanted Ads,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Help-Wanted Advertising Steady in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Help-wanted advertising, an indication of the
demand for labor, held steady in April, the Conference Board
reported Tuesday.
   The Board's Help-Wanted index, unchanged from the previous
month, measures the volume of classified advertising in 51 major
newspapers nationwide.
   But trends in the labor market continue to confound experts.
   ``While help-wanted advertising volume has shown no significant
strength since last November, employment continues to rise,'' noted
Conference Board economist Kenneth Goldstein.
   The Labor Department reported April's unemployment rate was 5.4
percent, down from 5.6 percent in March.
   ``The best odds still favor a slowing of employment growth in
the coming months, rather than a spurt in want-ad volume,'' he said.
   Advertising volume rose in five of the nine geographic regions
measured, with the East South Central region posting the largest
gain of 5.5 percent. It was followed by the South Atlantic, where
help-wanted advertising rose 2.9 percent, and the West North
Central region, up 1.7 percent.
   The Middle Atlantic region registered the greatest decline of
5.8 percent.
</TEXT>
