<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Centel Bjt   06-01 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Centel, Bjt,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Centel Dismisses Takeover Offer as Not Credible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centel Corp. officials dismissed a $2.8 billion
cash takeover bid from an investment group as not credible and as a
mere tactical device in a proxy fight.
   Reaction on Wall Street was also skeptical.
   Centel stock rose $4.87{ a share to close at $50 on the New York
Stock Exchange on Tuesday, but that was $15 below the price offered
by the investment group led by Asher B. Edelman and George L.
Lindemann.
   John P. Frazee Jr., Centel's chairman, said the offer was an
apparent attempt to aid efforts by Lindemann and Edelman to gain
three seats on Centel's 11-member board of directors.
   Edelman and Lindemann said in a letter to Centel management that
their investment group was willing to pay $65 a share for each of
Centel's approximately 43 million shares outstanding.
   But they conditioned the offer on Centel's canceling an
agreement to pay $763 million to buy United Telespectrum, the
cellular telephone subsidiary of United Telecommunications of
Kansas City, Mo. They said they would drop the bid to $60 a share
if Centel held to the deal, which was announced Friday.
   ``We believe the investment community overall reacted favorably
to our announcement regarding our proposed acquisition of United
Telespectrum,'' Frazee said in a statement. ``Our decision was part
of our strategic repositioning that follows closely our overall
business plan to emphasize three main lines of business _ cellular
communications, cable television and local exchange telephone
service.''
   That business plan in the long term would provide a far better
return for investors than any short-term gain under Lindemann and
Edelman's proposal to sell off company assets to boost stock value,
Frazee said in a telephone interview.
   Edelman is a financier who lives in New York. Lindemann is
chairman of Metro Mobile CTS Inc., a New York-based mobile-phone
business.
   Their group holds 5.5 percent of Centel's stock.
   Centel also announced plans Friday to sell its Centel Business
systems division, which executives had said could quiet dissident
shareholders who have called for a breakup of the company.
   In their letter, Edelman and Lindemann criticized Centel's plan
to acquire United Telespectrum and its $9.5 million debt.
   In light of that plan, they wrote, ``it is apparent to us that
management is not operating the company with shareholder values in
mind. This acquisition is overpriced and substantially reduces
shareholder values.''
   The letter said the takeover offer was designed ``to maximize
the values of the company,'' but Edelman and Lindemann also said
the offer was subject to financing being arranged and to regulatory
approval.
   They said said that if the offer were accepted, the group would
seek to dispose of Centel assets under the program they previously
urged.
   ``This is a friendly overture towards acquiring the company,''
Edelman said in a telephone interview from New York. ``It's very
friendly to the company. I'm not sure it would be friendly to the
management.''
   He would not comment on the group's next move if Centel offered
no response by the June 10 deadline set in the letter.
   In a statement, Frazee said, ``We feel the actions by Lindemann
and Edelman today should not distract attention from the basic
issue before the shareowners regarding Centel's future and the need
to re-elect directors who are committed to our strategic plan to
maximize shareowner values.''
   And in an interview, he said, ``We believe that our track record
of enhancing shareowner value in the past is very solid.''
   In an earlier statement, Centel said the acquisition of United
Telespectrum would increase Centel's presence in cellular phone
markets in the Southeast and give it a foothold in the Northeast,
including New York City and nearby areas of New Jersey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
