<HEAD>Tate & Lyle Offer For Staley Expires; Merger Expected Within A
Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staley Continental Inc.
shareholders have tendered more than 90 percent of their stock to
Tate & Lyle PLC under a $1.5 billion takeover.
   About 31.5 million shares of Staley's common stock were tendered
by Tuesday's 5 p.m. EDT expiration of the $36.50 per share offer,
said Mary Conway, a Tate & Lyle spokeswoman.
   With those shares, plus the 1.5 million common shares that Tate
& Lyle already owned, the British company had more than 90.3
percent of Staley's outstanding common shares, Ms. Conway said.
   Staley has guaranteed Tate & Lyle delivery of all other
oustanding shares, she said.
   ``Tate & Lyle anticipates merging Staley Continental Inc. into
its indirect, wholly owned subsidiary, RP Acqusition Corp., within
a week,'' Ms. Conway said.
   Tate & Lyle's complete offer for the corn-sweetener and
food-service company amounted to some $1.5 billion.
   Staley Continental, headquartered here in suburban Chicago, is a
leading maker of corn sweeteners and food-service supplies.
   Tate & Lyle, Britain's second-largest sugar refiner, is buying
the company mostly for its Decatur-based A.E. Staley Manufacturing
Co. subsidiary, the second-largest U.S. refiner of corn syrup.
   Tate & Lyle has said it plans to sell Staley's food-service
subsidiary, CFS Continental Inc., and move the corporate
headquarters back to Decatur, Ill.
   Staley Continental agreed to the takeover, which was announced
May 13.
