<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     06-01 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Management Reportedly Favors Beazer Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. Inc., which waged a three-month
war to avoid a takeover bid by British industrialist Brian Beazer,
now appears ready to accept a slightly improved offer to sell the
company to Beazer affiliate BNS Inc.
   Koppers officials reportedly favor a bid $1-per-share higher
than BNS's latest offer over an internal plan to restructure and
remain independent, the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette reported today.
   Koppers President Glen Tenley refused to confirm an agreement
had been reached between the two companies, which battled publicly
for months via advertisements in major newspapers and trade
publications.
   ``We haven't decided what to do yet,'' Tenley said. ``We're
still reviewing our options. We're reviewing capitalization, our
litigation and any other options.''
   The companies would confirm only that ``serious negotiations''
aimed at reaching an agreement began in New York over the Memorial
Day holiday weekend.
   Before the negotiations began, BNS had twice raised its bid for
the Pittsburgh-based construction and chemical company, from an
original $45 per share to $60 per share. The weekend talks
reportedly produced a $61-per-share offer.
   ``Such negotiations are expected to continue although there can
be no assurance that such negotiations will result in a mutually
acceptable agreement,'' the companies said Tuesday in a one
paragraph statement.
   Koppers spokesman Robert O'Gara said Koppers' goal is still to
keep the outcome of the discussions in the best interests of
shareholders, employees and the Pittsburgh area.
   ``All I can say is that serious negotiations and talks are
continuing,'' he said.
   BNS had extended its $1.7 billion, or $60 per share, tender
offer through Wednesday, saying it either owns or has offers to buy
80 percent of Koppers' common shares. BNS is owned by Beazer PLC
and Shearson Lehman Hutton.
   As part of the deal, Beazer has agreed to compensate Koppers'
top officials and employees, a package reportedly worth from $70
million to $100 million over 12 months, the Post-Gazette reported.
   Earlier, Beazer said a federal appeals court in California had
lifted one of the legal roadblocks to BNS' takeover bid of Koppers.
   Beazer said the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last
Friday that BNS may proceed with its attempt to acquire Koppers'
stock once a trustee is appointed to control Koppers' Sully-Miller
Contracting Co. subsidiary, a quarry and road materials supplier in
Irwindale, Calif.
   But O'Gara said the decision imposes further delays on the
takeover bid because it said the trustee cannot take over the
subsidiary until BNS acquires a controlling interest in Koppers.
   Also, O'Gara said, the order states that an injunction issued by
Chief U.S. District Court Judge Manuel Real in Los Angeles will
remain in force until the trustee is appointed.
   Roger Beidler, Koppers vice president for communications and
investor relations, said the firm is pleased with the ruling
because it recognized Real's authority to decide the anti-trust
issues raised in the case.
   Sully-Miller is a direct competitor of a company owned by Beazer
PLC, a British construction firm. Koppers had filed challenges
before Real alleging anti-trust violations.
   Real is scheduled to hold a hearing on the Koppers matter on
Wednesday.
   Another legal roadblock to Beazer exists in U.S. District Court
in Pittsburgh, where Judge Maurice B. Cohill halted the BNS bid
because of his concerns over financing. He has scheduled hearings
for Monday on the legality of the financing involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
