<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MurrayOhio     06-01 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murray Ohio,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arguments Set in Electrolux Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oral arguments are scheduled for next week
in a federal court lawsuit involving an attempt by AB Electrolux of
Sweden to take over Tennessee lawn mower and bicycle manufacturer
Murray Ohio.
   AB Electrolux, which has made a $52-per-share offer, filed suit
in U.S. District Court in Columbus last week against Murray Ohio
and its board of directors, including Chairman W.M. Hannon and
President J.L. Duncan, and various Ohio officials. Oral arguments
have been set for June 9.
   The suit asks the court to declare the Ohio Takeover Act and the
Ohio Foreign Business Acquisition Act unconstitutional and that
Ohio's Control Share Acquisition Act be declared inapplicable to
Electrolux's tender offer.
   It also seeks a court order to stop Murray Ohio from using any
of those acts to block the purchase of Murray stock.
   Parties in the suit agreed Tuesday to an expedited discovery
process and agreed to file motions by next week on whether the
court should abstain in the matter.
   Electrolux's offer of $52 per share to acquire Murray Ohio
amounts to $197.1 million.
   Also named as defendants in the suit are Ohio Division of
Securities Commissioner Mark Holderman, Ohio Department of Commerce
Director Linda Page, Ohio Attorney General Anthony Celebrezze Jr.,
Ohio Department of Development Director David J. Baker and Ohio Tax
Commissioner Joanne Limbach.
   Electrolux also has sued in Tennessee to have the Tennessee
Investor Protection Act declared unconstitutional.
   The act requires a company trying to buy a publicly held company
based in the state to file with the Tennessee Department of
Commerce and Insurance before the offer can become effective.
   Murray Ohio, which was incorporated in Ohio in 1919 and operated
in Toledo until 1955, no longer has holdings in Ohio. It makes lawn
mowers and bicycles at its Lawrenceburg, Tenn., plant.
   AB Electrolux is an international appliance manufacturer with a
product line that includes chain saws and weed trimmers. The
company has no relation to the vacuum cleaner manufacturer
Electrolux Inc. of Marietta, Ga.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
