<1ST_LINE>r f PM-US-JapanBeef     06-01 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Beef,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Progress Reported in New Round of Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials have dismissed as inadequate a
new Japanese proposal in the dispute over admitting more American
beef to the Japanese market.
   ``We don't feel progress has been made,'' a U.S. spokeswoman
said Tuesday, as the two countries opened a new round in their
prolonged negotiations.
   Japanese Deputy Agriculture Minister Hidero Maki, who arrived
from Tokyo during the weekend, met for nearly three hours with
Assistant U.S. Trade Representative Michael Smith. They agreed to
continue talks today, said Smith's spokeswoman, Kelly Winkler.
   Maki's new proposal involved raising tariffs on beef to protect
Japanese producers from the impact of removing import quotas as
demanded by the United States. Smith and his negotiators felt the
proposal ``was not adequate to address our concerns,'' Ms. Winkler
said, giving no other details.
   Maki also brought a new proposal to resolve a similar dispute
between the two countries over admitting more American oranges and
orange juice to the Japanese market. It is under study, the U.S.
spokeswoman said.
   The United States had agreed to beef and orange quotas under a
1984 accord that expired at the end of March. Meanwhile, two rounds
of negotiations have failed and the United States has requested
GATT, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, to declare the
Japanese quotas illegal under international trading rules.
</TEXT>
