<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Higher at Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were pushing higher at midday
Wednesday as dealers took heart from sharp gains on overseas equity
markets.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 20
points, or 1.1 percent, at 1,804.4 at 12:30 p.m. local time.
   Trading volume continued to disappoint the market, as a light
266.2 million shares changing hands by midday, compared with 224.3
million shares at the same time Tuesday.
   Wednesday's midday rise followed a 74.68-point jump in the Dow
Jones industrial average to 2,031.12 on Tuesday and a 287.21-point
gain in the Nikkei Index in Tokyo to 27,703.91 Wednesday. A
19.56-point advance in the Hang Seng index in Hong Kong to 2,516.24
also heartened market players, several analysts said.
   The market ``seems to be rejoicing in the gains overnight in New
York and Tokyo,'' one dealer said.
   However, several analysts were skeptical of the recovery and
weren't convinced that the market had turned a corner.
   ``I'm not prepared to say that we're out of the woods quite
yet,'' one equity strategist for a major U.K. brokerage said.
   International stocks, including chemical and pharmaceutical
issues, were helped by a sinking pound, dealers said.
