<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TreasuryBills     06-01 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rates On Short-Term Securities At Highest Level Since October
Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities have risen to the highest level since the October stock
market crash.
   In Tuesday's auction, the Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion
in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.53 percent,
up from 6.34 percent last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in
six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.83 percent, up
from 6.71 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 19 when three-month bills
sold for 6.84 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.21 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.73 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,834.90 and 7.17 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,654.70.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Tuesday the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages increased to 7.58
percent last week, up from 7.40 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
