<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DiamondStar     06-01 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diamond Star,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diamond-Star to Begin Building Pilot Cars Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The start of production at the new
Diamond-Star Motors Corp. factory will find robots and humans
working together on about 100 pilot cars.
   As the assembly line begins rolling slowly today, about 400 auto
workers will get their first taste of working side by side with
robots in the new $650 million plant, said Robin Skiles,
Diamond-Star spokeswoman.
   The state-of-the-art auto plant features high-technology
machinery and equipment including robotics on the final assembly
line. Plant supervisors and workers have received intense training
courses, including trips to Japan to study new methods and
management techniques.
   Diamond-Star is scheduled to begin full-scale production of
sporty coupes at the new plant the first week in September.
   Diamond-Star Motors is a joint venture of Chrysler Corp. and
Mitsubishi Motors. It will build a two-door, front-wheel-drive
coupe for the 1989 model year. The car will be sold at prices
starting at less than $10,000.
   Ms. Skiles said robots will be tested on an individual basis and
programmed for their specific chores. After each is properly
performing its task, the robots will be choreographed to get the
exact sequence on the assembly line and to perfect their timing.
   ``The first pilot cars will not come off the assembly line until
mid-June,'' she added
   The pilot cars will be checked closely for design quality and
possible production flaws.
   ``The pilot cars will be used by distributors as show cars and
in other media activities,'' she said. ``They will not be for sale
to the public.''
   Chrysler will market the vehicle as the Plymouth Laser.
Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America, which has 205 dealerships in the
United States, also will distribute the sports car, but its name
has not been announced.
   Ms. Skiles said Diamond-Star will have about 1,300 employees
when its first-shift of employees is on board and will produce
upwards of 80,000 in the first 12 months of operation.
   Eventually, the 2 million-square-foot assembly plant will
produce 240,000 cars annually and employ 2,900. Plans call for
Diamond-Star to build a compact sedan at its Normal plant beginning
in 1989. When it reaches full capacity, the plant will crank out
about 63 cars per hour.
   Chrysler and Mitsubishi have exchanged parts, engines and cars
for nearly 20 years, but the Diamond-Star project marks the first
production partnership.
</TEXT>
