<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-MapleMuncher     06-01 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maple Muncher,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pear Thrips Threatens Sugar Maples</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Thrips is both singular and plural form; also running on
general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New England's maple syrup industry is
threatened by an insect that usually chews on fruit trees but has
found sugar maples more to its liking this spring, a plant expert
says.
   ``If you've got a maple tree, you're in trouble,'' said Terry A.
Tattar, a plant pathologist at the University of Massachusetts'
Shade Tree Laboratory.
   Widespread defoliation blamed on the insect _ called a pear
thrips _ has been reported across New York and New England in the
past 10 days, he said Tuesday.
   ``It's everywhere from Litchfield, Conn., to eastern and western
New York, and the hills of Massachusetts, Vermont and New
Hampshire,'' Tattar said. ``And we just don't know very much about
it. We never had a population blowup of the insect similar to
this.''
   The pear thrips was introduced into California from Europe in
1904 and found its way from there into East Coast cherry, apple and
pear orchards, he said.
   ``I'm looking out of my window and I can see bare tops all over
the hills,'' said Richard Chandler, coordinator of the
Massachusetts Maple Producers Association. ``This certainly will
have an adverse effect on next season's production.''
   After four years of early thaws that cut short the sugaring
season and sent prices of syrup to nearly $40 a gallon, New England
maple sugar producers reported near-normal yields from their taps
this spring.
   Massachusetts annually produces about 50,000 gallons of syrup.
Vermont, the nation's largest maple sugar producer, averages about
500,000 gallons.
</TEXT>
