<DOCNO> AP880601-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 0954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Housing-Rates 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing-Rates, 1st Ld-Writethru,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Industry Slowed By Rising Interest Rates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, Higher rates ... last fall., to clarify that
contract total is an annual rate.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising interest rates have come knocking on the
housing and construction industries, threatening to blow down five
straight years of solid gains in nationwide sales.
   But economists say the cyclical ``big bad wolf'' isn't likely to
cause too much damage in 1988, although the outlook for the next
couple of years remains in question.
   ``It will be a weaker year than it could have been because of
interest rates ... but we're still expecting a good year,'' said
John Tuccillo, chief economist for the National Association of
Realtors.
   Tuccillo estimated that sales of existing homes would total 3.3
million and new home sales would total 650,000 in 1988, down from
3.65 million and 690,000 respectively last year 1987, but still
among the strongest years this decade.
   A report released Tuesday by the Commerce and Housing and Urban
Development departments said that new-home sales climbed 4 percent
in April to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 679,000 _ the
third consecutive rise and the fastest pace since new homes sold at
a rate of 728,000 in April 1987.
   In a report last week, the National Association of Realtors said
sales of existing homes rose 4.5 percent last month after increases
of 2.5 percent in both March and February.
   While economists said the reports show solid gains, they
cautioned that consumers rushed to do their buying then before
interest rates headed higher. They said May might not be as strong.
   ``People are trying to negotiate a settlement and get a mortgage
in the face of a fairly certain rise in interest rates,'' said
George A. Christie, chief economist with the F.W. Dodge Division of
McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.
   Mortgage rates are actually slightly lower now than they were a
year ago _ averaging about 10.46 percent for a 30-year fixed-rate
conventional mortgage, vs. an average 10.60 percent in May 1987,
according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., known as Freddie
Mac.
   But after falling sharply since the Oct. 19 stock market crash,
rates started to creep up again over the past several weeks on
fears that the economy may be overheating and inflation might be on
the rise. The 30-year mortgage rate, for instance, has risen more
than half a percentage point since February, when it averaged 9.89
percent, Freddie Mac said.
   Many economists predict mortgage rates will continue to rise
through the summer and top 11 percent by the end of the year. A
handful are forecasting rates in excess of 12 percent in 1989. At
the same time, experts are calling for moderate inflation of around
5 percent this year.
   Frank Nothaft, deputy chief economist for Freddie Mac, said the
rise in fixed-rate mortgages may cause some would-be homebuyers to
switch to adjustable rate mortgages. He said some savings and loan
associations also will become more accommodative, for instance, by
requiring smaller down payments or lowering closing costs to
encourage sales.
   Tuccillo also remains optimistic. He said that the ``Baby
Boomers,'' the large segment of the population born after World War
II, should remain interested in home buying as their families and
incomes expand.
   But David H. Resler, chief economist for Nomura Securities Inc.,
said, ``I think we're heading downhill in this industry, and
eventually the fate of the housing market ... will filter through
the rest of the economy as well.
   ``New homes need to be furnished with durable goods, like
refrigerators or washers and dryers,'' he said.
   The higher rates also threaten new construction contracts,
including residential and non-residential units, said Christie.
F.W. Dodge reported Tuesday that contracting for new projects
declined 6 percent in April from the previous month to an annual
rate of $226.97 billion, extending a downward slide that began last
fall.
   Bhristie said high vacancy rates in commercial properties,
particularly offices and apartments, were responsible for reversing
the industry's five-year upswing. But he said rising interest rates
will only aggravate the situation since they translate to higher
borrowing costs for contractors.
   ``The export boom which is pumping up the 1988 economy isn't
much help to the construction industry, and could even prove
troublesome,'' Christie said. ``As economic activity heats up,
rising interest rates imply still lower building later in the
year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
