<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Guinness     06-01 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Guinness,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bail Continued for Guinness Accused</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate Wednesday continued bail until July
11 for former Guinness PLC Chairman Ernest Saunders and five other
men facing charges relating to the British brewing giant's 1986
takeover of Distillers Co.
   Saunders' attorney said he planned to appeal to Britain's high
court over the magistrates court's refusal to grant the fired
executive legal aid.
   Wednesday's court date was set in April in order to speed up the
presentation of the evidence, after the defending lawyers
complained about delays in bringing the Guinness affair to trial.
   The six accused, free on bail equivalent to $915,000, were not
required to appear in court Wednesday, and only Saunders was
present.
   The other accused are former Henry Ansbacher and Co. Ltd.
director Lord Spens; stockbroker Anthony Parnes; Roger Seelig,
former corporate finance director at Morgan Grenfell and Co. Ltd.;
financier Sir Jack Lyons, and Gerald Ronson, chairman of Heron
International.
   All six are to appear in court on July 11 together with David
Mayhew, senior corporate finance partner at stockbrokers Cazenove
and Co., who has been released on bail separately.
   The prosecution said it has presented details of its evidence to
defense lawyers. But Saunders' attorney, Norman Turner, said the
substantial job of studying the evidence was blocked by Saunders'
inability to pay his defense costs.
   He said this could delay bringing the case to trial.
   Guinness has said its former management under Saunders arranged
for third parties to repurchase the company's stock, apparently to
boost its price illegally and make Guinness' cash-and-stock offer
for Distillers, a gin and whisky maker, more attractive than a
rival bid.
   The defendants face varying charges, including aiding and
abetting a share-support operation, theft and false accounting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
