<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower, Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybean futures opened slightly
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade, then turned mixed in
early trading.
   Analysts said the opening losses were due to profit-taking after
Tuesday's sharp gains, which saw contracts for future delivery of
soybeans, soybean meal, corn and oats all advance the limit allowed
for daily trading.
   Dry planting conditions last month and fears of a summer drought
in the Midwest are behind the dramatic increase in grain and
soybean futures prices this year.
   The weather outlook for the remainder of the week offered some
straws of hope for farmers, analysts said.
   ``Some light rains are expected Thursday and Friday but they
sure don't look like anything substantial,'' said Dale Gustafson,
an analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The Agriculture Department reported Tuesday that U.S. soybean
planting was about 74 percent complete as of Sunday. The USDA
reported the corn crop in good to fair condition and noted some
deterioration in the condition of the maturing winter wheat crop.
   In early trading, wheat was 3{ cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.48 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2 cents lower with July at $2.22} a bushel; oats were \ cent lower
to 1{ cents higher with July at $1.83} a bushel; soybeans were {
cent to 4 cents higher with July at $8.02 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .17 cent higher with June
at 72.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .30 cent
higher with August at 76.57 cents a pound; hogs were .17 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with June at 54.60 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent lower to .58 cent higher with July at 56.90
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Tuesday with pork
bellies posting limit gains.
</TEXT>
