<2ND_LINE>PM-Toyota,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota Executive Says Decision On U.S. Firm Is Near</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Co. will decide soon whether to
build a truck plant in the United States, a move that would halt
Japanese truck exports to the American market, a Toyota executive
said.
   Negotiations have ``progressed to a rather considerable extent''
and a decision is expected soon, Tsutomu Oshima, executive vice
president of Toyota, said in an interview in today's Los Angeles
Times.
   Such a move would result in the end of Toyota's truck exports to
the United States, he said. Although he refused to disclose the
export value of Toyota trucks, he said the company sent 280,000
pickup trucks to the United States last year, with an average
retail value of $9,000.
   Sites under consideration for the plant, Oshima said, include
Fremont, Calif., where Toyota operates a joint venture producing
passenger cars with General Motors; Georgetown, Ky., where Toyota
just opened an independent passenger car production plant; or a new
location.
   Start-up costs could eliminate the possiblity of a new location,
Oshima said.
   ``Before the yen started appreciating in value, Japan developed
the (small) pickup market in the United States. Even with a 25
percent tariff, we could sell our trucks at inexpensive prices,''
he said.
   Toyota has been forced to raise its retail truck prices an
average of 26.7 percent since 1985 and the prices ``have become a
burden on the user,'' Oshima said.
   American sales of Toyota trucks totaled about 250,000 in 1987,
down 30,000 from 1986. This year, sales have continued to decline,
Oshima said.
</TEXT>
