<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OECD-InterestRates     06-01 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OECD-Interest Rates,0383</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT _ time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>OECD Forecasts Interest Rate Rise for U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates could rise further in the United
States in the coming months, and there is little likelihood of any
easing of rates in West Germany, Japan, Canada and Italy, the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development said
Wednesday.
   France is the only member of the ``Group of Seven''
industrialized countries where the cost of credit is expected to
decline, the OECD said in the latest issue of its publication
Financial Market Trends.
   The interest rate outlook for Britain is less clear because it
depends on how the government allows the pound to move in relation
to other currencies, the report said.
   The OECD's observation on U.S. rates was made before the U.S.
Federal Reserve tightened credit last week by pressuring up the
overnight rate charged among banks for overnight loans to meet
reserve requirements.
   The OECD said it based its forecast for U.S. rates on concerns
about a pickup of inflationary pressures, strong credit demand and
the country's large trade deficit.
   Total credit demand in the United States is expected to
strengthen over the coming months as the economy's expansion
continues, chiefly due to an anticipated steep rise in corporate
borrowing, the OECD said.
   Turning to Britain, the organization observed that Britain's
trade gap widened sharply in the first quarter. While stemming the
deficit ``would perhaps require bringing the pound to a more
competitive level, implying lower interest rates,'' such a move
would clash with the government's anti-inflation policy, the report
said.
   The OECD predicted all major segments of Japanese financial
markets would remain very active in the coming months, suggesting
that the growing financing needs of the economy ``should be met
without any particular strain on current credit conditions.''
   ``The scope for lower rates remains limited,'' because Japan's
money supply is already expanding at an unprecedented rate, and its
possible inflationary implications are giving rise to concern, the
report said.
   West German interest rates are also unlikely to come down
further because of the strength of overall loan demand and growth
in the money supply that is running ahead of the target rate, the
OECD said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
