<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AlleghenyInternational     06-01 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Allegheny International,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxy Date Vote Set June 20</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge set for June 20 a proxy vote
to decide who will control consumer products maker Allegheny
International Inc.
   District Judge Alan Bloch on Tuesday set the date for the
company's annual meeting, at which shareholders will choose between
slates of directors put forth by management and dissident
shareholders.
   The fight to gain control of Allegheny International is being
waged by two New York investment houses that are heavily invested
in AI's preferred stock.
   The investment houses, Spear Leeds & Kellogg and Bomar Holdings,
say the company's managers are trying to entrench themselves while
ignoring shareholder interests. They contend management plans to
appease creditors by giving them large amounts of company stock,
thus diluting the holdings of present stockholders.
   Management says Spear Leeds cannot be trusted to run Allegheny
International and that its candidates have no experience in running
a consumer products company.
   A judge supervising AI's bankruptcy delayed the May 20 proxy
vote. Bloch overruled the bankruptcy judge, but an appeals judge
delayed the meeting again until the full appeals court could
consider the matter.
   Ruling on a narrow legal issue, the appeals court last week
refused to further delay the meeting, but left room open for
further arguments.
   Unsecured creditors wanted to halt the proxy vote, claiming a
change of management would delay the company's emergence from
bankruptcy while the campaign would drain money from the
financially ailing company.
   In rescheduling the meeting, Bloch said the courts should not
``interfere in corporate democracy absent a compelling showing of
need.''
   Allegheny International's best-known products are Sunbeam and
Oster appliances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
