<HEAD>Bank Acquisition Completed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wells Fargo & Co. said Wednesday it has
completed its purchase of Barclays Bank of California for $125.7
million.
   Wells Fargo reached a tentative agreement on Jan. 15 to buy
Barclays from Barclays Bank PLC in a move to continue its
aggressive retail franchise expansion across California.
   Barclays Bank, a subsidiary of the London-based Barclays group,
said the transaction was consistent with the company's increasing
focus on the corporate rather than retail market.
   Wells Fargo had assets of $44.2 billion at the end of 1987. Its
subsidiary, Wells Fargo Bank, is the ninth largest bank in the
nation.
   Barclays, which ranked 17th among California banks with $1.3
billion in assets at the end of 1987, said it will continue to
operate in its two corporate banking offices in San Francisco and
Los Angeles.
   Wells Fargo said it will close about 30 branch offices and lay
off 100 of Barclays' 1,100 employees. Most of the 100 Barclays
layoffs, effective on Wednesday, were in administrative positions.
</TEXT>
