<HEAD>Grain Futures Close Lower; Soybeans Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed lower Wednesday amid steady
profit-taking on the Chicago Board of Trade. Soybeans finished
mixed.
   Traders who had bought into Tuesday's limit gains turned sellers
as meteorologists predicted scattered light rain in the Grain Belt
over the next few days, analysts said.
   ``We picked up better chances for rain in the eastern Corn Belt,
but there's not a lot of moisture anticipated,'' said Jerry Gidel,
an analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co.
   The bullish interest in near-month soybean contracts remained
strong. The price for July delivery of soybeans surpassed $8 a
bushel, the highest price for a nearby soybean contract in more
than four years.
   Gidel said soybean contracts for 1988 delivery also got a boost
from reports that Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng had said he
would not authorize increased soybean acreage this year. The
Agriculture Department confirmed the reports.
   The USDA reported Tuesday U.S. soybean planting was about 74
percent complete as of Sunday. The USDA reported most of the corn
crop in good to fair condition and most of the maturing winter
wheat crop remained in fair shape.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 7 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.47{ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 3\ cents lower with July at $2.21 a bushel; oats were 2} cents
to 3} cents lower with July at $1.78} a bushel; soybeans were 9{
cents lower to 4{ cents higher with July at $8.02{ a bushel.
