<HEAD>Prices Edged Higher In Advance of OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices edged higher in listless trading
Wednesday as traders mostly stayed on the sidelines, awaiting the
upcoming ministerial meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   Contracts for July delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, closed up 7 cents at $17.58 per 42-gallon
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among July contracts for refined products, wholesale unleaded
gasoline rose 0.28 cent to 51.74 cents a gallon, while wholesale
heating oil rose 0.13 cent a gallon to 47.31 cents.
   ``It was another one of those dull, dull days,'' said Peter
Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders Futures
Inc.
   He said the market showed no reaction to reports that the start
of OPEC's regular summer meeting had been postponed by three days _
to June 11 _ because of an apparent scheduling conflict with
another event.
   Traders have been reluctant to commit themselves in the market
until they get some idea of how the meeting turns out, Beutel added.
   Representatives of the cartel's 13 members are expected to make
another attempt at negotiating a package of production cutbacks in
order to support prices.
