<DOCNO> AP880601-0325 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SocializedElectricity     06-01 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Socialized Electricity,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Edison Launches Energy Cooperative That Relies on Peer
Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A kind of socialism is being tried by a group of
Boston Edison Co.'s biggest commercial customers that have agreed
to cooperate with each other to ease energy consumption.
   Under a year-long trial that began Wednesday, 10 Boston Edison
customers will work together to decide which should forfeit some
electrical power during peak demand periods. They might do this by,
for example, shutting off a bank of elevators or turning off the
hot water for a few hours.
   As a result the utility estimates it could save 10 megawatts, or
enough to meet a year's electrical needs in 5,000 homes.
   Boston Edison has 640,000 residential and business customers in
40 cities and towns within a 30-mile radius of Boston.
   In addition to cutting back their electricity bill, the members
of the Northeast Energy Cooperative, as the group is called, will
be paid as if they are electricity providers. That's not new,
however.
   What is different is that the arrangement combines peer pressure
and altruism to save money and energy. To reinforce the cooperative
spirit, each member of the group will be ``graded'' by the other
members.
   If successful, the experiment will generate long-term contracts
and more companies will be invited to join the cooperative.
   The cooperative will be headed for its first year by John
Phillips, a former engineer who heads the non-profit California
Energy Coalition, which runs eight such utility cooperatives.
   ``The era of building (power) plants is over and the time for
better utilization of resources is here,'' he said at a news
conference explaining the cooperative plan, which he said also is
being used on New York's Long Island.
   A self-described arch-conservative, Phillips said in an
interview later that he has explained the dea to visiting planners
from the Soviet Union and Sweden. He said they all found the notion
novel.
   ``What we have here is ... a democratic society in a more
socialist environment,'' he said. ``You can't force people to do
things.''
   Bernard Reznicek, president of Boston Edison, said the
experiment is an attempt to deal with changes in demand for power.
   ``We have been an industry in a supply side mentality. That
strategy has been a high-cost strategy,'' he said. ``Intelligent
people stop and take a look and say there has to be a better way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880601-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FrequentFuelers     06-01 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frequent Fuelers,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fina Hopes To Fuel Distributors' Initiative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fina Oil and Chemical Co. has unveiled an
incentive plan in its 22-state gasoline distribution network that
will give independent distributors as much as $35,000 annually in
retirement benefits.
   Under the plan, which analysts say is unprecedented in the
industry, distributors who buy at least 2 million gallons of fuel
annually can receive retirement benefits of $10,000 per year. Those
who purchase 30 million gallons per year or more can be eligible to
receive up to $35,000 per year in benefits.
   The benefits accrue to the owners of the Fina distributorships
or to the employees they designate, officials said Tuesday.
   ``This will motivate our jobbers to do a better job for
themselves as well as for Fina,'' said Stuart Pearman, Fina's vice
president of marketing and developer of the plan.
   Analysts said the move also will help the company polish the
outdated image of some locations and upgrade a retail network that
includes gas stations in Iowa, Nebraska and Kansas in the Midwest
and in Texas, New Mexico and Arizona in the Southwest.
   ``I think it benefits the company and the dealers,'' Mary Anne
Sudol, investment analyst with Fitch Investors Service in New York,
told the Dallas Times Herald.
   She called the retirement plan an imaginative ``carrot-and-stick
approach'' that will require distributors to improve the quality of
their stations to take advantage of the retirement program.
   The retirement program, which began Wednesday and runs through
May 1993, is provided at no cost to the distributors, although they
must meet certain company-imposed requirements. Fina, a unit of
Dallas-based American Petrofina, has about 4,000 service stations
nationwide.
   To be eligible, distributors must buy at least 2 million gallons
of gasoline or other refined products annually from the parent
company and reinvest available building funds in accordance with
Fina's ongoing building program.
   Retirement fund participants also are required to increase their
fuel purchases by at least 5 percent through May 31, 1989. Similar
annual requirements must be met for distributors to continue in the
program until its expiration on May 31, 1993.
   All of Fina's 460 distributors who own or operate about 3,850
stations in 22 states are eligible for the program, Pearman said.
   Pearman said the program is being financed through several
insurance companies and other lenders and that Fina may decide to
continue the program after the initial five-year period.
   The retirement benefits are guaranteed for the qualified
participant for life and are payable starting June 1, 1998, but not
before the participant reaches 65.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
