<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mazda-FlatRock     06-01 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mazda-Flat Rock,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mazda Adds Second Shift at Flat Rock Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLAT ROCK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mazda Motor Corp. has added a second
production shift as scheduled at its U.S. assembly plant in Flat
Rock, a company spokesman said Wednesday.
   The 1,300-worker second shift began work Tuesday, boosting
monthly production of Ford Probe and Mazda MX-6 coupes to 13,000
cars a month in June from 9,600 a month in May, spokesman Atsuo
Katada said.
   The $550 million plant employs 2,600 hourly workers and 550
salaried workers on two shifts. When it reaches full production in
August, it will be building 240,000 cars a year.
   The plant began production in September. More than 60 percent of
its production is devoted to the Probe, which is sold through Ford
dealers exclusively and has attracted so many dealer orders it is
sold out through October.
   Katada said Mazda has no plans to expand the factory or increase
its annual capacity beyond 240,000 vehicles despite Japanese
newspaper reports that it will build 300,000 cars a year there.
</TEXT>
