<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SeabrookWithdrawal     06-01 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook Withdrawal,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Investor Votes to Stop Payments on Troubled Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUDLOW, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the largest investors in the
Seabrook nuclear power plant decided Wednesday to start withdrawing
from the troubled project by stopping payments.
   ``Our many successes have been hidden by the shadow of
Seabrook,'' said Gary L. Hunt, general manager of the Massachusetts
Municipal Wholesale Electric Co., after the vote by the eight
directors.
   ``This is not a bailout of MMWEC or of individual towns,'' he
said. ``It will enable MMWEC to get on with its business.''
   The Massachusetts utility supplies power to 34 municipal
electric departments across the state. Its shares in Seabrook were
bought on behalf of 28 systems in Massachusetts and eight in other
Northeastern states, and the investors together owned an 11.6
percent share of Seabrook.
   The utility has sunk $875 million so far into the stalled plant.
The $5.4 billion reactor is completed, but lacks approved
evacuation plans required for commercial operation. The largest
investor in the project, Public Service Company of New Hampshire,
has filed for protection from creditors under federal bankruptcy
laws.
   Hunt said the board approved his recommendation to withhold the
June 1 payment toward the construction and maintenance of the power
project, but will continue paying off the bonds issued for its
share in the nuclear power plant.
</TEXT>
