<DOCNO> AP880601-0334 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NissanExpansion     06-01 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nissan Expansion,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan Expansion Planned for July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction on a $31 million expansion
project at Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. USA is expected to get
under way in July, company officials said.
   The expansions are to provide for assembly of Sentra engines and
rear truck axles and production of plastic parts for bumpers,
according to a report published Wednesday in the Nashville Banner.
The project is not expected to create many new jobs, Nissan
officials said.
   ``The major part of the engine assembly will be in existing
space in the plant. Adjacent to that, we're adding 7,500 square
feet,'' said Emil Hassan, Nissan vice president and director of
plant and process engineering.
   Once the engine assembly line is complete next spring, plans
call for the line to start piecing together engines at a rate of
about 145,000 a year after a short break-in phase, he said.
   Initial production, testing and ``de-bugging'' of the assembly
line should take place about May 1989.
   Later plans call for adding a second passenger car line, which
would increase the plant's capacity from 265,000 vehicles per year
to 400,000. That expansion will require a larger work force,
officials said.
   Engines for Sentras are currently made by Nissan in Mexico and
Japan; axles in Japan; and the bumper parts by Decoma Plastics, a
subsidiary of Magna International in Canada.
   The Smyrna facility now makes small pickup trucks and Sentra
passenger cars.
</TEXT>
