<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 1804EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SEC-Arbitration     06-01 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-Arbitration,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Allows Month To Air Objections To Proposed Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission decided
Wednesday to give securities industry officials a month to press
their objections to a proposal aimed at protecting investors'
option to sue their brokers.
   The commission had been scheduled to vote to ask Congress to
pass a law barring brokerage firms from requiring customers to
agree in advance to submit disputes to stock exchange-sponsored
arbitration panels.
   But the vote was postponed after commissioners Charles Cox,
Edward Fleischman and Joseph Grundfest said the matter required
more deliberation. Commissioners agreed to decide the matter during
the first week of July, before one of the advocates of the change,
Aulana Peters, leaves the commission.
   Peters and SEC Chairman David Ruder argued it was unfair to
require investors to give up the right to sue before they have any
idea of the nature or size of a dispute that may later arise.
Peters and Ruder also said that providing an alternative to
arbitration will serve as an incentive to keeping the system fair.
   Cox said he was inclined to support Ruder and Peters but wanted
to give the brokerage firms a chance to argue their case.
   A survey by the SEC staff of 65 firms, handling 90 percent of
all customer accounts, showed that virtually all require customers
to arbitrate disputes, particularly customers who borrow money
through margin accounts or trade in stock options.
   The North American Securities Administrators Association, a
group of state regulators, has been pressing to do away with
mandatory arbitration clauses. Staff members of the finance
subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce Committee are working
on an arbitration bill that would, among other things, forbid
forced arbitration.
   However, the Securities Industry Association, representing
brokerage firms, says it is unfair to dictate to brokers how they
must do business and that it makes little sense to force cases on
an overburdened and costly court system.
</TEXT>
