<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Gold Continues to Climb</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf to CORRECT Comex gold price to $457.60, sted
$457. Picks up 17th graf ``Silver bullion ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A post-holiday rally in the U.S. financial
markets sustained the dollar's strength in foreign exchange
Wednesday despite a slight dip in early Japanese trading.
   Gold prices also continued to climb. Republic National Bank said
gold bullion was bid at $457.50 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, up from
$454.30 late Tuesday. The price has moved up $6.50 over the past
two days.
   Currency traders said the dollar was benefiting from the
surprising rush of bullishness that has infected the American stock
and bond markets since investors returned from the long Memorial
Day weekend.
   Stocks and bonds moved up strongly again Wednesday for the
second consecutive day.
   Traders said investors appeared sanguine about the level of U.S.
interest rates and the pace of economic growth and were jumping
into equities and bonds to snap up bargains. The strength of the
U.S. currency mirrored the investors' new-found confidence in the
American markets.
   ``The sentiment has been so bearish for the dollar, most money
has been on the sidelines,'' observed Ronald Holzer, chief dealer
for Harris Trust & Savings Bank in Chicago. ``I think we're seeing
the first realization of fresh money moving back into the U.S.''
   Holzer said currency traders were restructuring their positions
in light of the sudden shift of capital into American stocks and
bonds.
   But he cautioned, ``The longevity of this thing is uncertain.''
   The dollar weakened during morning trading in Tokyo, where the
business day begins, after Bank of Japan governor Satoshi Sumita
told reporters he thought a long-term rise in the dollar unlikely.
   But the dollar soon recovered, closing in Tokyo at 125.23
Japanese yen, up from 124.80 yen on Tuesday. In later trading, the
dollar traded at 125.25 yen in London and 125.425 yen in New York,
compared with 125.235 late Tuesday.
   The British pound continued to weaken against the dollar and
West German mark. In London, it cost $1.8220 to buy one pound,
compared with $1.8385 late Tuesday. In New York, the pound fetched
$1.81335, compared with $1.8353 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.7308 West German marks, down from
1.73265; 1.44345 Swiss francs, down from 1.44525; 1.23035 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2333; 5.8425 French francs, up from 5.8300;
and 1,286.62 Italian lire, up from 1,284.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.7255 West German marks, down from 1.7292;
1.4390 Swiss francs, down from 1.4437; 5.8270 French francs, up
from 5.8215; 1.9330 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9333; 1,282.50
Italian lire, up from 1,279.95; and 1.2319 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2357.
   Gold, still riding the coattails of the recent strong move in
platinum, rose in London to a late bid price of $456.50 a troy
ounce, compared with late Tuesday's $454.80. Gold was higher in
Zurich as well, closing at a bid $457, compared with $455 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid $458.55, up from
$455.80.
   At the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery was quoted at $457.60 a troy ounce, up from $455 a troy
ounce late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.79 a troy ounce, compared
with Tuesday's $6.65.
   On the Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was quoted at
$6.818 a troy ounce, up from $6.600 late Tuesday.
   Jeffrey Nichols of American Precious Metals Advisors Inc. said
that while the metals rally reflected some lingering inflation
fears in the commodities markets, it also was a sign of relief
among investors who had been expecting further interest rates hikes
by the Federal Reserve.
</TEXT>
