<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HerbalTeaSuit 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Herbal Tea Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Connecticut Tea Company Attempts To Block Merger Of Herbal Tea
Giants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Horne in grafs 8, 11 and 12.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.C. Bigelow Inc., a maker of herbal
teas, said Wednesday it filed a lawsuit seeking to block Thomas J.
Lipton Inc.'s acquisition of Kraft Inc.'s herbal tea subsidiary on
grounds the merger would violate federal antitrust laws.
   In its complaint, filed last week in U.S. District Court in New
Haven, Norwalk-based Bigelow claimed Lipton's acquisition of
Kraft's Celestial Seasonings division would join the nation's two
largest sellers of herbal tea, leaving Lipton in control of about
82 percent of the U.S. herbal tea market.
   Bigelow also claimed Lipton agreed to pay a bonus price for
Celestial Seasonings in order to acquire a monopoly, said Paul
Windels Jr., a lawyer for Bigelow.
   U.S. District Judge Jose A. Cabranes on Tuesday entered a
temporary restraining order delaying the acquisition until a
hearing on Bigelow's complaint could be held June 10.
   Bigelow was established in 1945 by Ruth C. Bigelow, who
developed the recipe for an herb-flavored tea known as Constant
Comment. The company is now owned by family members.
   Bigelow introduced its line of herbal teas, containing no tea
but herbs and spices, in 1979 and ranks third in the herbal tea
market with about a 13 percent share, the company said.
   A call to Lipton's legal department seeking comment on the
lawsuit was not returned Wednesday.
   A Kraft spokesman, Scott Horne, said, ``We remain optimistic
about the deal and we intend to close the transaction as soon as
possible.,''
   Lipton, based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J., is owned by the
Dutch-English company Unilever Group.
   It markets Lipton and Oriental Treasures herbal teas and is the
dominant company in traditional black teas with more than 50
percent of the U.S. market.
   Celestial Seasonings, purchased by Kraft in 1984, accounts for
more than half of U.S. herbal tea sales, according to Bigelow.
Kraft, based in Glenview, Ill., had sales of $9.9 billion in 1987,
Horne said.
   The proposed sale of Celestial Seasoings was announced in
December 1987. The Federal Trade Commission is reviewing the
proposed sale, Horne said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
