<1ST_LINE>u b AM-BurlingtonNorthern 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burlington Northern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BN Suspends Stock Trading; Plans Major Announcement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Expands throughout to add spokesman's comments on Winona
Bridge; analyst's comments; background on BN.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Northern Inc. suspended trading late
Wednesday on both the Midwestern and Pacific stock exchanges
pending what the company described as a significant announcement.
   Company spokesman Howard Kallio declined late Wednesday to
elaborate, saying company officials planned a statement Thursday
morning.
   However, Kallio did say the announcement would not specifically
involve Winona Bridge Railway Co., a tiny subsidiary that BN
planned to use to run trains from Minneapolis to Seattle. Railroad
unions have objected to the subsidiary's plan to use smaller train
crews.
   BN suspended trade on the two regional exchanges after the 4
p.m. EDT close of the New York Stock Exchange.
   BN's stock closed Wednesday on the New York exchange at $67.38 a
share, up $2.38.
   ``I wish I knew myself,'' said M. Craig Schwerdt, an analyst
with Morgan, Olmstead, Kennedy & Gardner in Los Angeles.
   However, Schwerdt said the announcement could concern a
restructuring within the company, perhaps involving the sale of
some assets.
   Burlington Northern Inc. is the parent company of Burlington
Northern Railroad Co., the nation's largest rail system, with
28,000 miles of track stretching from the Pacific Northwest to the
Gulf of Mexico. BN is the third-largest corporation in Washington
state after Boeing Co. and Weyerhaeuser Co.
   BN was formed in 1970 with the merger of Great Northern Railway,
Northern Pacific Railway, Chicago Burlington & Quincy Railroad,
Spokane Portland & Seattle Railway and Pacific Coast Railroad.
   Since 1980, the company has diversified with ownership of a
major natural gas pipeline between Texas and California, an oil and
gas production company and real estate. Its holdings include some
2.5 million acres of land.
   BN had net income of $369.3 million on revenues of $6.62 billion
in 1987.
</TEXT>
