<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Takeshita     06-01 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Takeshita,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Prime Minister Calls For Increased Mutual Trade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Noboru Takeshita of Japan said on
Wednesday it ``goes without saying'' that Japan must keep trying to
open its markets wider to the United States. He promptly added that
Japan will be trying to increase its own exports.
   He refused to say, however, what he thought the appropriate
exchange rate should be between the dollar and the yen, commenting
that ``God only knows'' the answer.
   Earlier Wednesday, the dollar weakened briefly in morning
trading in Tokyo after Bank of Japan governor Satoshi Sumita told
reporters he thought a long-term rise in the dollar was unlikely.
   But the dollar soon recovered, closing in Tokyo on Wednesday at
125.23 yen, up from 124.80 yen on Tuesday.
   Takeshita held a news conference in New York after addressing
the U.N. General Assembly's special session on disarmament.
   Asked about the balance of trade between America and Japan,
Takeshita replied: ``It goes without saying that Japan must
continue with further efforts to open up the Japanese markets even
more. Having said that, I should also like to add that there will
be greater efforts to export Japan's goods.''
   He was less forthcoming about the outlook for exhange rates.
Takeshita will soon be meeting in Toronto with Japan's Western
allies for an economic summit, where the subject is likely to arise.
   He said that Japan considers the Louvre Accord, which deals with
policy coordination among the major countries on exchange rates,
``has been proceeding smoothly.''
   ``As for that other question, what level of the exchange rate we
think is most appropriate, I myself as well as our finance minister
make it the rule to say that `It is something that God only
knows,''' the prime minister remarked.
   Takeshita spoke in Japanese, aided by an interpreter.
   He declined to characterize progress on another thorny
U.S.-Japanese trade issue _ U.S. efforts to sell more beef and
citrus products in the highly protective Japanese market.
   Noting that bilateral talks on the issue were under way, he said
he did not want to prejudice the negotiations and would offer no
comment.
   Earlier Wednesday, Takeshita pledged increased efforts by Japan
in the cause of disarmament and world peace, including sending
Japanese technicians and advisers to Afghanistan to monitor
elections and to repair transportation, communication and medical
services.
   He congratulated President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev on achieving the intermediate-range nuclear forces (INF)
treaty scrapping medium and shorter-range nuclear missles, which
took effect Wednesday.
   At the same time, he enunciated a Japanese policy of cautious
disarmament based on negotiation.
   Takeshita is scheduled to meet Reagan on Friday in London, where
the president will brief Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on the
Moscow summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
